<DOCNO> AP880719-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Meese     07-19 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Meese,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Aides Say Meese Ethics Report Won't Hurt Politically</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Meese Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent counsel James McKay's conclusion
that Attorney General Edwin Meese III probably violated tax and
conflict-of-interest laws won't hurt George Bush politically, a top
aide to the vice president says.
   ``I wouldn't go as far as to say it's a dead issue, but it's not
going to be a central concern, in my judgment, when voters go vote
in November,'' Bush's campaign manager, Lee Atwater, said Monday.
   Bush aides contend that, for all practical purposes, Meese
ceased to be a major political liablity for the vice president, the
certain Republican presidential nominee, when Meese on July 6
announced he would resign.
   Bush, troubled by the accusations against Meese, previously had
sought to make ethics in government a major campaign theme, calling
for a tougher conflict-of-interest standard for all officials.
   However, the vice president had insisted he would not comment on
the Meese matter until the release of McKay's report.
   When that report was delivered on Monday, the vice president was
not available for comment. He was in a remote part of Wyoming on a
4{-day fishing trip with Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III that
began on Saturday.
   Speaking on Bush's behalf, Atwater said of the newly released
report: ``It's not going to have anything to do with this
election.''
   McKay concluded that Meese probably willfully filed a false
income tax return, failed to pay taxes on time and broke a criminal
conflict-of-interest law. The independent counsel said he would not
seek criminal charges against the attorney general, however.
   Meanwhile in Atlanta, one of Meese's more outspoken Democratic
critics in Congress said he didn't believe McKay's report would
have any effect on Michael Dukakis' candidacy.
   ``I don't think there is any partisan advantage or should there
be a partisan advantage,'' said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., whose
Senate governmental oversight subcommittee investigated Meese's
involvement with the scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
   ``I don't think Meese is a partisan issue. Republicans called
for his resignation as well as Democrats,'' said Levin, who was
attending the Democratic National Convention.
   Bush in the past has said that the attorney general should be
held to ``a high ethical standard'' and that he found some of the
allegations against Meese particularly troubling.
   A Bush campaign aide who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said Meese, by resigning, took away the McKay report as a campaign
issue. The official said Bush hadn't been bombarded by questions on
Meese since the attorney general announced he would step down.
   Before then, Bush had been asked at nearly every campaign stop
whether Meese should resign.
   When Meese announced he would step down as attorney general and
said he was vindicated by McKay's report, Bush said in a terse
statement: ``Ed did the right thing and I wish him well.''
   Atwater said Bush would deliver a major speech on ethics in
government within the next few weeks. ``I don't want to upstage him
on it. The speech isn't complete.''
   Campaign sources said Bush's ethics proposals, long in the
works, had been delayed to await the McKay report.
   In the past, Bush has said the new code he will outline ``will
help us avoid the excesses of the past.''
   ``People should come to Washington to serve, not to profit,''
the vice president said in a recent campaign appearance. ``When a
congressman goes bad, or a member of the executive branch betrays
the public trust, you know and I know that it hurts.''
   Before Meese announced his plans to resign, two top Bush
campaign aides _ pollster Robert Teeter and former communications
director Peter Teeley _ said publicly that the attorney general had
become a major campaign liability for Bush.
   Bush campaign aides said they had not heard from the presumptive
Republican presidential candidate since before he began the fishing
trip.
   ``He must be catching a lot of fish,'' Bush spokeswoman Sheila
Tate said.
   He planned reappear on Wednesday _ the next-to-last day of the
Democratic convention _ with campaign appearances in the Detroit
area, and also was to campaign daily at least through Sunday.
</TEXT>
