<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-WarofWords     07-19 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-War of Words,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>End of Meese Investigation Looses War of Words</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III has nothing
but angry words for a $1.7 million investigation into his ethics
that he believes both vindicates him and will allow him to ask the
government to pay his legal fees.
   Independent counsel James McKay ended a 14-month investigation
of Meese by issuing a lengthy report Monday while making no formal
charges. But the report precipitated an immediate war of words
between Meese and his lawyers and McKay.
   After court personnel handed out 6-inch-thick piles of documents
to more than 100 journalists who had waited in line as long as 2{
hours at the federal court building, the combatants began a string
of news conferences at the National Press Club.
   Meese lawyer Nathan Lewin compared McKay to a ``hit-and-run''
driver for accusing the attorney general of crimes and then running
away from filing charges.
   ``It was a cheap shot,'' Lewin said.
   He called the investigation ``a total bust, a colossal blunder''
and scoffed at the prosecutor's 814-page report, downplaying the
length of his own filing which was nearly as thick but printed on
only one side of each page.
   Lewin said his rebuttal, with sections titled ``Fishing in
Foreign Policy Water,'' ``The Empty Net'' and ``Procrastination is
not Willfulness,'' was more readable than McKay's.
   Lewin accused McKay of stretching statutes ``beyond what any
reasonable prosecutor would do,'' of trying to make an Iraqi
pipeline project look like ``the opening of a McDonald's franchise
in Baghdad'' and of making groundless accusations to justify the
high cost of his fruitless investigation.
   An hour later, McKay held his own news conference and repeated
for television cameras the accusations made against Meese in his
report: that Meese filed a false tax return, missed a tax filing
deadline and dealt with two separate matters that might affect the
telephone industry while holding stock in a local telephone company.
   In addition, McKay accused Meese, both in the report and at the
news conference, of insensitivity in dealings as a government
official with his close friend, E. Robert Wallach.
   But McKay said he was using his ``prosecutorial discretion'' not
to bring formal charges against Meese because such offenses
ordinarily would not lead to prosecution of a person who was not
attorney general.
   He said neither Meese nor his wife, Ursula, had a history of tax
evasion and he had no evidence that the attorney general took any
of the illegal actions for personal gain or that he deliberately
lied.
   McKay defended the high cost of the investigation. ``I didn't
spend it personally,'' he quipped. ``I feel confident we have not
wasted any government funds, any of the taxpayers' money.''
   Asked how he would respond to a lawsuit from Meese if one were
filed, he said, ``I've been sued before.''
   Finally, Meese strode into the same hall where McKay had just
appeared, angrily defending all his actions _ and attacking McKay.
   ``I'm glad that finally the long ordeal is over,'' Meese said.
``But I'm outraged at the tarnishing of our system of justice that
has gone on this afternoon and with the filing of this report by
the independent counsel.
   ``I am appalled that James McKay came in front of you and
violated every principle of fairness and decency.''
   ``I've always acted legally, ethically and properly,'' Meese
said, ``and any implication by the independent counsel that I have
in any way violated any law is absolutely false.''
   Meese said it went against the American judicial system for a
court official to publicly accuse someone of a crime and then not
file charges.
   ``If anybody did that in the Justice Department, they'd be
fired,'' he said.
   Meese said he would not disclose whether he would take any legal
action against McKay, but he said he would ask the government to
pay his legal expenses which lawyer Lewin said were approaching
$250,000 six months ago. Meese said he didn't know how much the
total bill would be.
</TEXT>
