<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan     07-19 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Remains Pleased With Meese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan still feels Edwin
Meese III has been ``an outstanding attorney general'' despite an
independent counsel's finding that Meese likely violated tax and
conflict-of-interest statutes.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters Monday
that Reagan believes Meese ``will be able to look back with great
satisfaction on the contributions he has made to the Justice
Department and to the administration of justice in general.''
   Reagan, who is vacationing with his wife, Nancy, at the couple's
secluded ranch in the Santa Ynez Mountains, has never wavered in
his support of his longtime California adviser and political
confidant.
   And the voluminous report by independent counsel James McKay,
which said Meese conceivably could have been prosecuted on a number
of matters, did not change the president's thinking.
   ``The president is pleased that, after extensive scrutiny, the
independent counsel did not charge the attorney general with any
criminal wrongdoing,'' Fitzwater told reporters at a briefing at an
oceanfront hotel.
   His remarks closely paralleled the statement that Reagan made in
behalf Meese earlier this month when the attorney general
pronounced himself vindicated because he was not indicted and
announced he was resigning, effective in late July or early August.
   The Reagan White House seemed taken aback by Meese's
announcement, even though it said the attorney general had alerted
Reagan months earlier to the fact he did not plan to remain until
the end of the administration next January.
   Reagan subsequently nominated former Pennsylvania Gov. Richard
Thornburgh as Meese's replacement, and the administration has said
it hopes Thornburgh can be confirmed easily by the Senate. There
have been no immediate problems on Capitol Hill, although the
confirmation hearings remain to be held.
   In the lengthy report released Monday, McKay said Meese probably
violated the law in the sense that the attorney general failed to
file his income tax form on time in 1985 and that the report failed
to disclose a substantial capital gains income by the attorney
general.
   McKay also concluded that Meese likely could have been
prosecuted for a violation of federal conflict-of-interest statutes
for taking part in meetings regarding the telephone industry while
still holding $14,000 in regional Bell telephone stock.
   Fitzwater said White House officials were in the process of
reviewing the McKay report, but he said Meese and his attorneys had
released a document ``which refutes the issues at hand.''
   Asked whether the McKay report in effect cast a new legal cloud
over Meese, the spokesman said, ``The attorney general has filed a
lengthy statement saying no.''
   Without commenting specifically on the Meese matter, Thornburgh,
on the day his nomination was announced by Reagan on July 5, said
he would follow such a case wherever the evidence leads.
   There have been widespread reports that Meese is prepared to
join the conservative-oriented Heritage Foundation, a research
organization, after he leaves office. There also have been reports
that he might become a senior fellow at the Hoover Institution in
Palo Alto, Calif., a similarly conservative think tank.
   While Reagan was defending Meese through his spokesman Monday,
the White House announced the resignation of a close associate of
recently resigned chief of staff Howard H. Baker Jr.
   Fitzwater said Reagan had accepted the resignation of Dan
Crippen, an economics adviser who is returning to private life.
   The spokesman said Crippen ``has been an integral part of the
president's economic team, playing an important role in many major
issues, including the trade bill, budget matters and general
economic planning.''
   He sought to minimize speculation that there is an exodus of
Baker associates from the White House, noting that the current
chief of staff, Kenneth Duberstein, is a close Baker friend.
   Both Baker and White House communications director Thomas C.
Griscom, who had been Baker's spokesman for years during Baker's
days in the Senate, resigned last month.
   Baker said he was leaving for personal reasons, including the
health problems of his wife, Joy. Griscom said he wanted to accept
a position at the University of Tennessee-Chattanooga.
   Duberstein will hold a high-level meeting of senior Reagan aides
here Thursday.
   ``It's just a planning meeting by the senior staff to go over
the last six months, to talk about agenda and themes, issues,
campaign activities, all those kinds of things,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
