<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Ursula'sJob     07-19 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Ursula's Job,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McKay Cites Possible `Ulterior Motives' By Meese Associates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Meese Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-month investigation into the financial
dealings of Edwin Meese III concluded that a real estate magnate
and a confidant of the attorney general ``may have had ulterior
motives'' in helping arrange a $40,000-a-year salary for Meese's
wife.
   Independent counsel James McKay, in the final report on his
investigation, also said he found no evidence to show that Meese
``was aware of such motives.'' McKay, whose report was made public
Monday, brought no charges against Meese or anyone else.
   The 814-page report says that Meese confidant E. Robert Wallach
received a $200,000 loan from real estate magnate Howard Bender
this February, shortly before investigators looked into their roles
in funding a job for Ursula Meese. It was their involvement in
arranging Mrs. Meese's salary on which McKay questioned their
motives.
   In their rebuttals, attorneys for Wallach and Bender objected to
McKay's references to their clients' possible ``ulterior motives.''
   As for the loan, Bender's lawyers said Wallach said the money
was needed for his legal fees because the government had frozen his
assets. They said the loan was disclosed to the U.S. attorney and
the federal court in New York, where Wallach is under indictment
for trying to peddle his influence with Meese.
   McKay said that in return for the $200,000, Bender received a
promissory note from Wallach and a deed of trust on real property
owned by Wallach.
   A separate agreement provided that Bender would advance Wallach
``additional funds up to a total of $500,000 if a deed of trust in
the amount of $525,000 were delivered to Mr. Bender,'' McKay said.
   This was one of several new elements turned up by McKay in his
investigation of an incident in 1985 when Howard and Sondra Bender,
head of a wealthy Washington real estate family, donated $40,000
for Mrs. Meese's salary. The money was to be paid by the Multiple
Sclerosis Society, where she had previously worked as a volunteer.
   The donation coincided with efforts by a Bender real estate
partnership to renew a lucrative lease on office space in the
Chester A. Arthur Building for Justice Department agencies.
   The lease was renewed at increased rent more than a year after
the donation and the Bender partnership quickly sold the building
for 60 percent more than it had paid for it about two years earlier.
   McKay revealed that Wallach brought Mrs. Meese's desire for a
paid job to the attention of the Benders. But McKay said he turned
up no information that Meese was aware of Bender's interest in the
building or took any role in the lease renewal.
   In their rebuttal, Bender's lawyers said he had only a 10
percent to 11 percent interest in the partnership.
   ``There is no basis in the report for the conclusion ... that
Mr. Bender may have had `ulterior motives' in supporting the
November 1985 contribution to the Multiple Sclerosis Society, which
was used by that reputable charity to provide employment to Ursula
Meese,'' Bender's attorneys wrote.
   They said the Bender family foundation made the grant because
they believed in Mrs. Meese's abilities to direct development of a
job match program for MS victims.
   Wallach's attorney, George Walker, said the reference to
ulterior motives on Wallach's part is ``gratuitous and without any
factual foundation.''
   McKay also disclosed that Mrs. Meese received $15,000 in
advances on her salary in both 1985 and 1986. He said the society
had no prior history of giving such advances and she testified she
needed them to pay bills.
</TEXT>
