<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pentagon-Honduras     07-19 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pentagon-Honduras,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Americans Wounded in Honduras In Good Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The six U.S. servicemen wounded in an apparent
grenade attack in Honduras are in very good condition following the
weekend incident in which an explosive device was thrown at their
automobile, the Pentagon says.
   The Defense Department on Monday released the names of five of
six. The name of the sixth wounded man was not released because his
family has not been notified, said Maj. Kathy Wood, a Pentagon
spokeswoman.
   The names of the five, their services, home bases and hometowns
were: Elbert Whitehead, an Army specialist assigned from Fort Polk,
La., and originally from Enfield, N.C.; James Jones, Army
specialist, Fort Sam Houston, Texas, originally from Ebensburg,
Pa.; Air Force Staff Sgt. Shawn Cunningham, George Air Force Base,
originally from Cheshire, Conn.; Air Force Sgt. Michael Shea,
Keesler Air Force Base, originally from Gardena, Calif.; and Army
specialist John Monroe, Fort Bragg, N.C., originally from Spring
Lake, Mo.
   Monroe was treated and released Sunday and the other five were
said to be in ``very good condition'' at the Palmerola Air Base in
Honduras.
   The six were wounded in the parking lot of the Confetti
discotheque in San Pedro Sula, 125 miles north of the capital of
Tegucigalpa. The disco is frequented by U.S. military personnel.
   Wood said no one had claimed responsibility for the attack.
   Earlier reports said four men had been wounded, but doctors at
Palmerola said another man was hit by sharpnel and a sixth had
injured an ankle.
   The wounded men were among 150 servicemen on a one-day
recreation leave from Palmerola. Following the incident, all were
recalled to the air base as a precaution, Wood said.
</TEXT>
