<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IntelsatCase     07-19 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Intelsat Case,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former No. 2 Executive Arrested In Aruba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former second-ranking executive at the
global satellite communications network Intelsat was arrested in
Aruba last week and charged with conspiracy to defraud the
organization of $3.8 million, according to a criminal complaint
unsealed Monday in federal court.
   Jose L. Algrett, fired as deputy director general of Intelsat in
December 1986, is the fourth person to be charged in a scheme that
allegedly defrauded Intelsat of $5.4 million through a combination
of unauthorized payments, bid-rigging, kickbacks and phony
commissions.
   The scheme, said to have been carried out between April 1984 and
September 1986, revolved around the construction and financing of
the second phase of the new Intelsat headquarters in Washington.
   Algrett had been living in since January 1987 in Venezuela. He
had sporadic talks with prosecutors and FBI agents aimed at a plea
agreement, but the talks reportedly broke off last month.
   When Algrett travelled to Aruba to meet with a U.S. agent, he
was arrested by Aruban authorities and put on a plane for Miami,
where he was arrested by the FBI.
   He was being held without bond pending a hearing Thursday before
a U.S. magistrate.
   Intelsat, the International Telecommunications Satellite
Organization, is a consortium of 114 member countries that develops
and manages communications satellites.
</TEXT>
