<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-USNavy Bjt   07-19 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-US Navy, Bjt,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Year-Old Convoy Operation Has Reaped Mixed Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP Extra</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's acceptance of a U.N. cease-fire
plan comes almost exactly a year after the start of the Persian
Gulf convoy operation that led to a massive U.S. naval buildup and
armed clashes with Iranian forces.
   Navy officials said they would adopt a ``wait and see'' position
on whether, when and how the Persian Gulf-based U.S. fleet of about
17 ships would be affected, should the eight years of Iraq-Iran
hostilities indeed be ended.
   As Tehran's surprise announcement was reported by its official
Islamic Republic News Agency on Monday, the 48th U.S. Navy convoy
of 1988 and the 70th in the past year was en route up the gulf.
   A spokesman at U.S. Central Command headquarters in Tampa, Fla.,
said the U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti gas tanker Gas Princess, escorted by
the missile frigate Fahrion, had passed through the Strait of
Hormuz ``without incident.''
   Since the Stars and Stripes was first run up the mast of the
renamed supertanker Bridgeton on July 21, 1987, the U.S. Navy has
sailed 42,000 miles, nearly equivalent to twice around the equator,
protecting 11 ``reflagged'' Kuwaiti tankers from Iranian attack in
the gulf.
   For Kuwait, ``Operation Earnest Will'' has guaranteed safe
transit for millions of tons of oil products that otherwise might
not have reached customers in Europe and Japan.
   For the Navy, it has meant a grueling test of ships, sailors and
technology in a twilight war where threats range from armed
speedboats and underwater mines to fast-moving aircraft and
dangerously deceptive signals on a radar screen.
   The escort operation got off to a shaky start when the
401,382-ton Bridgeton hit a mine on the first northbound convoy. It
is now semi-retired.
   The Navy's Middle East Force, based in the gulf since 1948, grew
swiftly from about four ships to the present level, with ten more
including an aircraft carrier in a support role in the Arabian Sea.
   ``A year ago nobody would have predicted we'd have 16 or 17
ships, helicopter carriers, minesweepers, or a lot of other stuff
in the gulf,'' an officer said recently.
   Neither could it be known that the Navy would sink or damage six
Iranian vessels in a one-day missile war, or that a U.S. cruiser
would on July 3 shoot down an Iranian jetliner, killing 290 people.
The Pentagon said the cruiser mistook the jetliner for an F-14
fighter jet.
   The incident is still being investigated.
   A second Kuwaiti tanker was knocked out of service for five
months by an Iranian missile attack on Kuwait's main oil terminal,
and U.S. forces have had at least three other significant clashes
with Iranian craft.
   About 100 commercial vessels were attacked in the past year,
many while sailing to or from Kuwait, which Tehran regards as
Iraq's ally in the war. But no U.S-flagged tanker has been molested
during a Navy convoy.
   The Reagan administration said its reflagging policy reflects a
long-standing U.S. commitment to freedom of navigation and would
blunt Moscow's effort to expand its influence in the oil-rich
region.
   It has opposed a Soviet-backed proposal for a U.N. force to
replace the seven foreign navies that together have about 30
warships in the gulf.
   Congressional opponents assailed the reflagging policy as
ill-defined and risky, but Reagan backers thwarted repeated efforts
to invoke the 1973 War Powers Act, which would require U.S.
withdrawal in 90 days unless Congress agreed otherwise.
   By rough calculation, the reflagged tankers carry about 20
percent of Kuwait's total oil product exports of 600,000 barrels a
day. About a third goes to Kuwait's retail outlets in Europe, the
rest to regular customers in Europe and Japan.
   U.S. diplomats say Kuwaiti officials have expressed satsifaction
with the convoy operation and that deliveries have been smoother
since January, when the convoys were increased in frequency but
reduced in size, often to one tanker.
   The Pentagon estimates the cost of its expanded gulf force at
$20 million a month. Officials say this has been reduced since
Kuwait began providing U.S. warships with free fuel.
   Nine Americans have been killed in the gulf in the past year,
all in helicopter crashes.
   The missile frigate Samuel B. Roberts was nearly sunk by an
Iranian mine, but officers say the crew's ability to save it
validated lessons learned in the May, 1987 Stark disaster, when an
errant Iraqi missile attack killed 37 crewmen on the U.S. frigate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
