<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Disasters     07-19 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Disasters,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Natural Disasters Kill 529 in First Half of Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Natural disasters killed 529 people and caused
$540 million in damage in China in the first half of this year, an
official newspaper reported today.
   The China Daily, quoting a Civil Affairs Ministry official, said
floods, drought, landslides and cold spells also injured 11,588
people, destroyed 470,000 homes and affected 64 million of China's
1.07 billion people.
   Disasters also damaged $2.4 million homes and killed 90,000
horses and oxen, it said.
   Most the deaths and injuries were caused by floods that ravaged
large areas of southern China last month, washing away at least
$1.1 billion pounds of grain.
   The report said 65.8 million acres of land have been affected by
drought, which has dried up crops in 18 provinces in central,
southern and western China. Another 24.7 million acres has been hit
by floods.
   China has about 296 million acres of arable land.
   The daily said the Civil Affairs Ministry had allocated $130
million in disaster relief. It did not give comparative figures for
casualties and damage in 1987.
   In 1986, natural disasters claimed 5,381 lives, injured 40,396
and destroyed 2 million homes. The government that year spent $384
million to help disaster victims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
