<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     07-19 0965</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,1006</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ike Turner, who gained fame in the
1960s singing alongside then-wife Tina Turner, received a one-year
sentence in county jail for possession and transportation of
cocaine.
   Turner, 56, of Cerritos was taken into custody after Monday's
sentencing. He also was sentenced to three years of probation, said
Al Albergate, a spokesman for the district attorney.
   Turner was convicted April 15 on two drug-related felony counts
of possession and transportation of cocaine stemming from an August
arrest in West Hollywood.
   In October 1986, Turner admitted he had used cocaine daily for
at least 15 years and said he was undergoing rehabilitation to kick
the habit.
   Ike and Tina Turner, who divorced in 1976, topped the music
charts during the 1960s with such songs as ``A Fool in Love,''
``It's Gonna Work Out Fine,'' and ``Proud Mary.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charlton Heston will direct Herman Wouk's
play ``The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial'' this fall in China, the
actor said.
   ``Art has always been an effective ambassador between nations,''
said Heston, who recently directed and starred in London,
Washington and Los Angeles productions of the play.
   The play is scheduled for mid-October in Beijing People's Art
Theatre, Heston said in announcing the project Monday.
   The venture grew out of the efforts of a non-profit association
formed by author Bette Bao Lord and James A. Doolittle. The
association works to involve performing and creative artists from
China and America in theater projects.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Anne blames the ``disposable
mentality'' of modern society for water pollution and is calling
for stronger controls to ensure clean water supplies.
   ``With water resources, it cannot be worth waiting to see if the
worst does happen,'' the princess told delegates to an
international conference on water pollution Monday in this southern
England city.
   ``I sometimes wonder if it is only a disaster or major failure
that really gets things moving,'' she said.
   Anne, the only daughter of Queen Elizabeth II, recalled that one
of her ancestors, Queen Victoria, ordered an investigation into
river pollution in the 19th century.
   ``I suspect she might be appalled by the lack of progress in
many areas, largely due to the disposable mentality and short-term
outlook of modern man,'' the princess said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boy suffering from kidney disease had a
visit from football star Jim McMahon and says that despite
McMahon's wiseguy reputation, the Chicago Bears quarterback wasn't
``cocky or anything.''
   Friends of Scott Bremer's family organized McMahon's visit to
the Bremers' home Friday to bring attention to the family's
financial plight due to Scott's illness.
   Scott, 13, was born with polycystic kidney disease and has
endured two kidney transplants in the past three years, both of
which have failed and left him dependent on kidney dialysis. He
also has survived 13 operations, a heart attack and collapsed lung.
   Emily Bremer, Scott's mother, said the football star didn't live
up to his reputation for being arrogant. ``He was so nice and
caring,'' she said.
   Scott said he too was surprised by McMahon's demeanor.
   ``He was shy and he didn't talk much at first,'' Scott said.
``But later we started talking real good. He wasn't cocky or
anything.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen youngsters are planning a
scholastic mission to the moon this summer under the direction of
former astronaut William Pogue.
   Pogue, who served as pilot of the 84-day Skylab 4 mission in
1973-74, is teaching two two-week courses on space exploration in a
Tulsa Junior College program called College for Young Scholars. The
program is for students in grades six through 10.
   The former member of the Air Force Thunderbirds was on the
support crews of Apollo 7, 11 and 14 and traveled 35.5 million
miles in space on Skylab.
   He says his classes stress the importance of taking inventory
and keeping accurate records.
   ``When we were up in Skylab we had 10,000 things stored and we
still couldn't find anything,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Esquire magazine thinks Bush and Dole would make
a good Republican presidential ticket _ George Bush and Elizabeth
Dole, that is.
   The magazine named Mrs. Dole its Woman of the Year in its August
issue and endorsed her for the vice president's office.
   Esquire said Mrs. Dole was selected for its annual honor because
she ``looks soft but plays tough... was Queen of the May at Duke
(University), but also Phi Beta Kappa ... is utterly open about her
ambition, but tucks all the rest of herself away.''
   Mrs. Dole left her post as U.S. transportation secretary to help
her husband, Senate Minority Leader Robert Dole, in his
unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential nomination earlier
this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Red Skelton got a surprise from fellow
funnyman Milton Berle at a benefit performance when Berle emerged
from the audience to lead a rendition of ``Happy Birthday'' for
Skelton.
   The tribute came near the end of the two-hour benefit Sunday
during which Skelton collapsed due to heat exhaustion, a charity
spokesman said.
   Skelton was feeling better Monday, when he turned 75, said Lynn
Cook, executive director of the March of Dimes Chapter of the
Pacific.
   ``He's just fine. He got a good night's sleep and is planning on
having a wonderful birthday,'' Cook said.
   Skelton, overcome by heat, humidity and dehydration, collapsed
as he left the Waikiki Shell stage 90 minutes into his performance
Sunday.
   But Berle, who turned 80 last week, stepped up from the
audience, took the microphone and sang ``Happy Birthday'' to
Skelton, who then returned to the stage.
   Skelton plans to have a full medical exam after he returns to
his home in Palm Springs, Calif., Cook said.
</TEXT>
