<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     07-19 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Ballet of Canada Gives Theatrical Evening</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two theatrical ballets were given their New York
premieres on opening night of the National Ballet of Canada's
one-week season at the Metropolitan Opera.
   The program Monday began with ``La Ronde,'' an entertaining
ballet based on Arthur Schnitzler's 1900 tale of serial liasons
among ten characters.
   All 10 dancers were splendid. Ronda Nychka has an enticing solo
in the first scene, ``The Prostitute and the Soldier,'' which ends
with John Alleyne as the soldier walking away without looking back.
He returns for ``The Soldier and the Parlormaid,'' an expansive,
exuberant duet with Kimberly Glasco. He struts away from that
encounter.
   And so it goes, as we see the narcissistic Young Gentleman, the
Young Wife, the Husband, the Sweet Young Thing and so on. The final
scene has the Count (Frank Augustyn), after a duet of sophisticated
decadence with the Actress, encountering the prostitute from the
first scene.
   Tetley then runs his 10 scenes through again on fast-forward _ a
few steps from each. ``La Ronde'' would be stronger without that.
   And he errs somewhat on the side of subtlety. The differences
between scenes should not be as broad as burlesque, but sometimes
the differences Tetley draws are so subtle that contrast is lacking.
   ``Blue Snake,'' choreographed by Robert Desrosiers, seems overly
influenced by performance art. Its most striking feature is its
sets, with weird costumes coming in second.
   It is set in a jungle, with modern music by Ahmed Hassan and
John Lang. Dancers dressed as zebras in abstract black and white
leotards cavort and undulate. Monkeys run about to strains of jazz.
The face of a giant appears; his arms move in from the side walls,
his hands gathering up monkeys and stuffing them through his open
mouth.
   There is drumming, eerie music, people in black with tall
dancecaps, three women in blue with gold quills down their spines,
people with square pieces of cloth fastened to head, ankle and
wrists so they look like flying kites, and people wearing
gyroscopes on their heads. It ends with a long snake flying through
the air.
   It's very visual, which must intrigue some audiences. We'd
rather see a ballet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
