<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BankFire 3rdLd-Writethru a0452 07-19 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Fire, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0452,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire in Downtown Los Angeles High-Rise Declared Extinguished</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with no injuries reported, quotes from
fire officials, records show sprinklers in basement, 30th floor,
other detail. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smoky fire erupted Monday night at the
downtown Union Bank building, burning offices on two upper floors
of the 38-story tower before it was extinguished.
   At least two workers in the building escaped safely after the
fire broke out about 8:20 p.m. No injuries were reported, said
Battalion Chief Bob Defeo.
   On May 4, the worst high-rise fire in the city's history killed
one man and injured 40 people at the nearby First Interstate bank
building.
   ``There were some lessons learned in the First Interstate
fire,'' said Inspector Ed Reed, who told reporters that
firefighters quickly raced up 34 floors to get to the Union Bank
fire before it could rage out of control.
   In the First Interstate blaze, firefighters had had difficulty
reaching the flames.
   Monday's fire was declared extinguished shortly after 9 p.m.,
said fire spokesman Jim Williamson. About 75 firefighters were at
the scene.
   Michael Turner said he was working on the 35th floor when the
fire broke out.
   ``I was in our law library doing some research, and I felt two
explosions which I thought was an earthquake,'' he said. ``When I
realized it wasn't an earthquake, I went back to my desk and the
fire alarm went off.''
   ``I went and found a co-worker. We looked out one of the windows
and saw flames coming up, and we got the heck out of there.''
   The fire burned two offices on the 34th floor and 1{ offices on
the 35th floor, said Defeo, adding, ``This was nowhere near the
Interstate fire. We got it in time.''
   Before the fire was controlled, a television news helicopter
circled the tower and spotted flames coming from an upper-story
office and thick smoke coming from other windows.
   The Union Bank tower is located within blocks of the First
Interstate Bank building.
   A sprinkler system was being installed at the First Interstate
building, but was not yet operating on the night the fire
devastated the upper floors of the state's tallest skyscraper.
   Alexander Handy, a 24-year-old maintenance worker, died after he
became trapped in an elevator. Several people were trapped inside
the smoke-filled building for hours as firefighters worked to
rescue them.
   The Union Bank building was equipped with sprinklers in the
basement and on the 30th floor, according to Fire Department
records. It was built before the 1974 city ordinance requiring
sprinklers in high-rises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
