<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Intelsat-Fraud     07-19 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Intelsat-Fraud,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former No. 2 Executive Arrested In Aruba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former second-ranking executive at the
global satellite communications network Intelsat is the fourth
person to be charged in a scheme that allegedly defrauded the
company of $5.4 million.
   Jose L. Algrett, fired as deputy director general of Intelsat in
December 1986, was arrested in Aruba last week and charged with
conspiracy to defraud the organization of $3.8 million, according
to a criminal complaint unsealed Monday in federal court.
   He was being held without bond pending a hearing Thursday before
a U.S. magistrate.
   The scheme, said to have been carried out between April 1984 and
September 1986, revolved around the construction and financing of
the second phase of the Intelsat headquarters in Washington and
allegedly included a combination of unauthorized payments,
bid-rigging, kickbacks and phony commissions.
   Algrett had been living in Venezuela since January 1987 and had
sporadic talks with prosecutors and FBI agents aimed at a plea
agreement, but the talks reportedly broke off last month.
   When Algrett traveled to Aruba to meet with a U.S. agent, he was
arrested by Aruban authorities and put on a plane for Miami, where
he was arrested by the FBI.
   Intelsat, the International Telecommunications Satellite
Organization, is a consortium of 114 member countries that develops
and manages communications satellites.
</TEXT>
