<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--ConventionNotebook     07-19 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Notebook,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Behind-The-Scenes People Perk Up Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With enough cameras present to cover every
conceivable angle of the Democratic National Convention, Franklin
McMahon seemed as obsolete as the flash bulb.
   But there he was, pencils in hand, sketching the scene on his
artist's tablet, recording the proceedings for time, rather than
for the moment.
   ``I do this because an artist sees differently,'' McMahon said.
``I see what all these cameras can't. I see around the corners.
What I do is not just a snapshot. It's a statement, and the camera
usually doesn't make a statement.''
   McMahon, from Chicago, has been lending his perspective to the
political scene for three decades now. His work is being shown at
the CNN Center adjacent to the Omni during the convention.
   While the convention buzzed around him, McMahon deliberately
outlined a picture, looking for nuances and special characteristics
of this convention. He placed a computer terminal in the
foreground, symbolizing the equipment used to count each state's
votes.
   ``I try to bring an element of humor to it,'' McMahon said.
``This is a TV show and I make sure I show TV some way.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Thelma Grundy is giving the Democrats and reporters gathered
here some food for thought.
   Her home-cooking hole-in-the-wall restaurant _ strategically
located just blocks from the convention center _ has been spooning
up okra, squash, collard greens, ribs and fried chicken so fast she
hasn't had time to wash the flour from her apron.
   ``The Lord is good to me,'' she chuckled.
   Even though a plethora of fancy eateries surround the convention
area, Thelma's Kitchen has served a steady stream of customers.
She's been going through a 10-pound crate of okra a day, and at
least 30 pounds of chicken.
   It's the busiest she's even been in 20 years of serving food.
   ``Business is so rushed I can't get to my favorite recipe. It's
a special recipe which the Lord gave me and I don't think anyone
else has _ okra cakes. A lot of people rave about it.''
   The cakes and other southern specialties have spawned a loyal
following for Thelma, including local lawyers, businessmen, Atlanta
Hawks basketball players and even _ in her pre-fame days _ Vanna
White.
   But when it comes to politics, Thelma says she doesn't have much
stomach for it.
   ``I like to feed 'em, but I don't much like it otherwise,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   From Danny Bigay's perspective, some 65 feet above the Omni
floor, the Democratic National Convention hasn't been as well
organized as, say, a rock concert.
   Bigay was part of the crew that rigged and focused the hundreds
of lights that Democrats hope make their convention shine. He crept
across steel trusses hung from the ceiling, used rope-climbing
techniques and delighted in thrilling the early-arriving reporters
and delegates by descending upside-down.
   ``They've never done this before, so they were kind of making it
up as they went along,'' Bigay said of the organizers. ``But there
haven't been any major problems. There's nothing that's not
working. And nobody got hurt.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880719-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--PodiumPolitics     07-19 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Podium Politics,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pols Fight for Time on Podium to Impress Folks Back Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forget all the pomp and preparation, the careful
creation of convention images for national consumption. For the raw
guts of politics, check the podium schedule.
   From lowly House challengers to sitting governors, politicians
are lobbying fiercely for a moment or two in the spotlight at the
Democratic National Convention. The evolving schedule provides
clear-cut evidence of the pressure, the winners and the losers.
   For instance, consider this year's Senate candidates.
   On the schedule issued Saturday, they were allotted 10 minutes
tonight for introductions. In a revision released Monday, the
contenders were up to 19 minutes and brief remarks.
   True, they were scheduled for 4:50 p.m. _ but any exposure is
good exposure for challengers fighting for recognition from the
home folks who read the local newspaper and watch local TV.
   ``Podium time is a good boost for these candidates. They'll
certainly be covered in their print outlets,'' said Anita Dunn,
spokeswoman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
   The success of her group sparked a competitive drive at the
House Congressional Campaign Committee. ``We are co-equal branches
of government,'' explained committee chairman Beryl Anthony, D-Ark.
   His tongue was in his cheek, but he made his point. The revised
schedule showed Wednesday proceedings starting 39 minutes earlier
than initially planned. More than half an hour was devoted to the
House candidates.
   The House segment on the updated schedule was followed by an
all-new governors' segment, as the National Governors Association
weighed in. The leaders of Pennsylvania, Kentucky and Louisiana
secured four or five minutes apiece _ a princely chunk in the
fast-moving new world of abridged television coverage.
   ``People have been astonishingly cooperative about time,'' said
Mike McCurry, spokesman for the Democratic National Committee.
``We've been able to persuade them that four minutes on the podium
constitutes a major address.''
   Other late additions to the schedule included introductions of
others who ran for president, all of them except Sen. Joseph Biden,
D-Del., who is not here, and former Sen. Gary Hart, who is here as
a newspaper columnist and television commentator.
   The new schedule set aside time for House Majority Leader Tom
Foley of Washington and Washington, D.C. Mayor Marion Barry, for
introducing Geraldine Ferraro, and even for introducing someone
identified as ``the Young Delegate.''
   It appeared that Walter Mondale, the presidential nominee in
1984, was one of the casualties of the revised schedule. Designated
to be introduced by House Speaker Jim Wright on the initial
program, he was nowhere to be found on the revision.
   ``You caught what must be either a typo or a lapse in the
synapses of the press secretary,'' said McCurry. Mondale was indeed
introduced, at about 8:30 Monday night _ a half hour before network
coverage began. Asked the meaning of this, McCurry replied, ``Prime
time was 8 to 11 last time I checked.''
   There were some true casualties, or heroes, forced to sacrifice
their precious podium time to the demands of the modern convention.
Everyone presenting a section of the platform lost a minute; Wright
and Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., each lost four.
   Bob Farmer, the Dukakis finance chairman widely considered a
miracle worker, dropped from four minutes to two. And a videotape
of praise for DNC Secretary Dorothy Bush, who calls the roll, got
slashed from six minutes to three.
   The time pressure is such that McCurry wouldn't even consider a
reporter's question about the possibility of roll call rather than
voice votes on platform amendments. ``I wouldn't want to
speculate,'' he said, ``on anything that would keep the clocks from
running on time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880719-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--JacksonFallout Bjt   07-19 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Jackson Fallout, Bjt,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Jackson Delegates Still Smart from `Insult'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Cederick is correct in 8th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deep bitterness smolders among many of Jesse
Jackson's black delegates over what they see as Michael Dukakis'
``slap in the face'' of their candidate and they say whether it
hurts Dukakis in November will be settled by Jackson _ not Dukakis.
   Even after the breakfast accord between Dukakis and Jackson,
William Crawford of Indianapolis, Ind. speaks for many when he
says: ``George Bush is not attractive, but I don't think we can say
Dukakis at any price.''
   State Sen. Hank Sanders of Selma, Ala., echoes Crawford _ and
then some: ``At some particular time, dignity becomes more
important than any election,'' he says. ``I'll give up anything for
dignity, including life.''
   But political activist Joe Reed of Montgomery, Ala., draws the
line at voting Republican. ``There's not a Democrat here who wants
to see George Bush elected,'' he says. ``Jesse Jackson has as much
obligation to get the Democratic ticket elected as Dukakis does.''
   On the floor of the Democratic convention Monday night, Jackson
delegates chanted ``Jesse, Jesse'' and said they were trying to
send a message.
   ``I think we are trying to show we still support Jesse Jackson
and also show the Democratic Party it should include us more in the
power structure,'' said Bernard Parker of Detroit.
   Associated Press reporters interviewed a sampling of black
Jackson delegates on the potential November fallout from what many
blacks call the insulting way Dukakis treated Jackson in picking a
Southern moderate, Lloyd Bentsen, as running mate at the very time
Jackson had started campaigning for the job _ and then failing to
tell Jackson of that decision.
   Arthur Eve of Buffalo, N.Y., deputy majority leader of the lower
house in the state legislature, says his fellow black New York
delegates are ``outraged'' over a ``snub'' of Jackson that was
``very deliberate and very planned.''
   Milton ``Toby'' Fitch, a black legislator from Wilson, N.C.,
calls it ``a slap in the face,'' adding: ``You don't have some
underling contact Rev. Jackson; you do it yourself.''
   Dissents Cederick Dwyer, 45, of South Haven, Mich.: ``I don't
feel insulted and I don't think Jesse Jackson was insulted.''
Nonetheless, he says: ``Dukakis needs to make an apology.''
   Some black Jackson delegates say Jackson retains enormous power
because the signals he sends will decide whether blacks will vote
in massive numbers for the man from Massachusetts.
   Painter George Wood, 71, from Richfield, Minn., says he'll
follow Jackson's cues. ``Whatever way he goes, I'm with him 100
percent,'' Wood says.
   Chimes in Jim Richardson of Charlotte, N.C., a state senator:
``Most of the delegates I know will stick with Jesse right down the
line, wherever it takes us.''
   ``A strong endorsement (of Dukakis by Jackson) would get me to
support him strongly, but it has to come to that,'' says Wayne
Williams of Delaware.
   Adds Mary Jo Haywood of Camilla, Ga.: ``If he comes out
enthusiastically for the ticket, then black voters will support it.
But if he's lackadaisical, they will interpret it as meaning that
it doesn't matter if they vote in November or not.''
   Nebraska Brace, a black alderman from Albany, N.Y., says the way
Dukakis handled Bentsen was an insult to ``black people in
general,'' but he feels the Jackson forces will return to the fold.
``We'll win in November and we'll win with the black vote,'' he
predicts.
   The interviews yield these additional impressions:
   _Some see a Machiavellian duplicity in the way Dukakis let word
slip out before notifying Jackson. ``He did it deliberately,'' says
Rep. Cardiss Collins of Chicago, relaxing during a ride on an
antique railroad. ``He was trying to appeal to a certain segment of
Democratic voters who would like that kind of thing. He was trying
to ... say that he wasn't going to be dictated to by the Jesse
Jackson supporters.''
   Adds Gail Peterson, 35, a community organizer from Grand Rapids,
Mich.: ``By choosing Bentsen, Dukakis made a statement to the
conservative wing of the party.''
   _But some, like Howard P. Rawlings of Baltimore, Md., pay
grudging respect to Dukakis' pragmatism. Rawlings says Dukakis
``has a tough balancing act to maintain.'' and adds that Jackson
would not want to leave the convention ``with the weight of a
potential Democratic loss on his shoulders.''
   _Some black delegates say the incident displayed Dukakis'
remoteness from black concerns. ``The Dukakis campaign has to be
more sensitive to the needs and concerns of black constituents,''
says William Gibson of South Carolina.
</TEXT>
