<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--ConventionKitsch     07-19 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Kitsch,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Souvenir Booths Lend Carnival Atmosphere to Convention Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's more than one way to sell a donkey.
   You can sling an elephant gun over his shoulder, name him
``Dembo'' and put him on a T-shirt.
   You can put him on a beer mug or a key chain, or show him
kicking an elephant into the next county on the side of a coffee
cup.
   It's all here at row after row of hastily erected souvenir
booths near The Omni, site of the Democratic National Convention.
There's something for every taste, or lack of it, at this sun-baked
bazaar of political kitsch.
   The Democratic National Committee has licensing rights on items
carrying its official logo, which also has a donkey it. But it's
open season in Atlanta this week on other donkey goods.
   There are rolls of toilet paper with ``1988 Democratic
Convention'' (no donkey) printed in red, white and blue on each
sheet.
   There are donkey hats, donkey balloons, donkey buttons and a red
and white cushion depicting a donkey's generous hindquarters with
the helpful legend, ``For Your ...''
   There is a donkey on a bib (``One For My Baby. 1988 Democratic
Convention''), a donkey call for $10 and, in a bow to prospective
party nominee Michael Dukakis, a stuffed donkey imprinted with ``I
Like Mikey.''
   Wait, there's more.
   There are donkey shoelaces, donkey running shorts and an
staggering variety of donkey buttons and T-shirts.
   ``Get your souvenir delegate's button here,'' whooped one
pitchman at passing delegates who streamed toward The Omni for
Monday night's opening session.
   ``I've got Al Gore buttons,'' yelled another.
   How are they selling?
   ``I don't have any,'' he admitted. ``I saw the lady wearing one
and I wanted her to stop and look at this other stuff.''
   ``I've got Jesse Jackson soda pop,'' shouted a vendor standing
over an ice-filled cooler.
   The side of the cans said ``Coke.''
   Roy McClure of Atlanta has erected a collage of Washington,
D.C., with portraits of Republican Party leaders scattered among
the landmarks.
   For a dollar you stand behind a line and throw three darts. If
one of them nails George Bush you get a free convention T-shirt.
   ``You don't get anything if you hit Reagan except a good time,''
McClure said. Business was brisk.
   ``Shirts and hats are selling real well,'' said Chris Moore,
operating another booth. ``And coffee cups. And Jackson. Anything
with Jesse Jackson on it.''
   One entrepreneur is offering small jars of genuine red Georgia
clay with a donkey on the label for $1 each. Another popular item
is a red, white and blue fan on a stick (``I'm a fan of the
Democrats''). It was 92 degrees in Atlanta on Monday.
   Shoppers can choose among Georgia peaches, a golf ball with a
peach and ``Atlanta '88'' on it, or a jar of Georgia peach
preserves.
   Rhett Butler peers from the chest of one shirt uttering his
immortal line, ``Frankly, my dear ... ''
   Another booth offers china figurines of Scarlett O'Hara in a
hoop skirt. There are no donkeys on Scarlett.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
