<DOCNO> AP880719-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Rules-Credentials     07-19 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Rules-Credentials,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Show Unity With Quick Adoption of Rules, Credentials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats pointed to the quick adoption of major
rule changes and the seating of more than 4,000 delegates without a
fight as a sign to the nation of their commitment to party unity
and hopes for victory in November.
   ``We decided to go down the road of cooperation and it leads to
victory in 1988,'' Sen. John Breaux, D-La., told delegates on
Monday at the start of the 48th Democratic National Convention.
   Rules and credentials, constant points of contention for the
Democratic Party, were resolved weeks before the convention and
adopted without a single floor fight or nay vote shortly after
Democratic chairman Paul G. Kirk gaveled the gathering to order.
   The speedy adoption _ within 45 minutes _ broke a 25-year
Democratic record of fighting.
   ``We are here to unite tonight,'' said Leroy Irvis, speaker of
the Pennsylvania House and chairman of the Credentials Committee.
``I give you a report and there will be no minority report filed.
Every single one has been unanimously approved of. Every single
debate has been resolved.''
   Negotiators for nominee-to-be Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson
reached agreements last month and the rules and credentials
committees ratified the results to ensure a unified convention.
   Dukakis had enough delegates to win the nomination plus a
600-delegate cushion that allowed him to concede to Jackson's
demands for added delegate representation in Kansas and Indiana.
   ``Everybody had to swallow a little to win big,'' said Rep.
Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., who served on the Credentials
Committee.
   ``We had 24 disagreements and we resolved every single one of
those disagreements before we had a formal meeting,'' Irvis told
the convention. ``We met in Washington, D.C., without a single
problem to resolve.''
   And when the delegates responded with unanimous ayes to the
credentials report, Kirk noted that it was ``the first sign of
unanimity and unity.''
   On the issue of rules, Dukakis agreed to Jackson's call for a
change in the delegate selection process for 1992 to make it more
closely conform to the popular vote expressed at the primaries and
caucuses.
   The new rules will reduce the number of ``super delegates'' _
elected or party leaders _ from 643 to 394, or 15 percent of the
delegate total to about 10 percent.
   Super delegates are not bound by the results of their state
contests. Jackson contended that his super delegate support, which
was about one-tenth that of Dukakis, did not reflect the popular
vote backing he received in some states.
   The rules also ban direct-election and ``bonus'' primaries,
which had the effect of awarding delegates on a
``winner-take-more'' basis.
   In states such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Massachusetts,
those systems enabled Dukakis to amass the delegates needed to
clinch the nomination on the last day of the primary season.
   ``We worked out our differences in a spirit of compromises,''
said Kathy Vick, vice chairman from Louisiana and head of the Rules
Committee.
   Marion Barry, mayor of the District of Columbia and
representative of the Jackson forces, said this year ``we worked
together ... for a winning team.''
   As he left the podium, Ms. Vick said, ``Thank you, Governor
Barry,'' a reference to one of the other rule changes. The party
will recognize the mayor of Washington, D.C., as a governor in the
delegate selection process. The only requirement is that he be a
Democrat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
