<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--ConventionScene     07-19 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Scene,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Entire Hall Is No-Smoking Section As Convention Gets Squeaky-Clean
Start</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic National Convention opened with a
smoking ban, a pledge to stay on time, some homespun politics and a
child's view of the presidency. But unity?
   Not really.
   Supporters of the Rev. Jesse Jackson, some wearing buttons
reading ``Respect Blackocrats Or Else,'' waged a war of shouts on
the floor of the Omni Monday night.
   They chanted ``Jesse, Jesse, Jesse'' each time their candidate's
name was mentioned, and audibly overpowered the refrains of ``Duke,
Duke.''
   The message wasn't lost on the majority of delegates for Michael
Dukakis.
   ``They can have their time,'' said Dukakis supporter Don Ortiz
of New Mexico.
   ``When the whole thing is over, we'll be demonstrating
together,'' predicted Pennsylvania delegate David Bielski. ``The
party has received their message.''
   The party also received a folksy Pledge of Allegiance from radio
raconteur and author Garrison Keillor and a group of first graders,
as well as celebrity readings of children's essays on the
presidency.
   If that weren't enough wholesomeness, the party banned smoking
in the convention hall, driving smokers out to a hazy arena outer
lobby.
   Joe Agostinelli, a Warwick, R.I., businessman was on the floor
chomping on an unlit cigar. ``I don't like it, but what are you
going to do? I've been a cigar smoker for 35 years. It's tough,''
he said.
   Agostinelli, a visitor, not a delegate, said, ``I haven't had it
lit since I got out of the car, but three people have come up to me
and said, `Would you mind putting that out?'''
   The Democrats offered everything from biographical videos of
keynote speaker Ann Richards and former president Jimmy Carter to
music videos of pop star Neil Diamond.
   There was a brass band, enough celebrities to satisfy
``Entertainment Tonight,'' and plenty of corny provincialism _ like
cardboard crab placards for the Maryland delegation.
   The opening affair ran a few minutes late, and there were a few
awkward moments, like the 90 seconds the podium was empty after
Polly Baca of Colorado was introduced.
   No matter.
   ``I feel like I'm on the brink of history,'' said Dukakis
delegate Leslie Hutchinson of Baltimore, Md.
   ``This party's not used to not having fights,'' said Richard
Trumka, president of the United Mine Workers and a Pennsylvania
delegate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
