<HEAD>Pentagon Probe Into Airliner Downing Will Last Through July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's investigation into the downing
of Iran Air flight 655, originally due to end on Monday, will last
at least until the end of July.
   A Defense Department announcement Monday said Rear Adm. William
M. Fogarty ``has requested additional time to complete his
investigation.''
   Fogarty flew to the Persian Gulf on July 4, the day after the
incident, and has been there since, trying to determine how
officers aboard the USS Vincennes mistook the Iranian A300 Airbus
for an attacking F-14 fighter.
   The Pentagon said he will send all ``findings of fact,
conclusions and recommendations'' to the commander of American
forces in the Persian Gulf, Gen. George B. Crist, who will forward
the report to the Joint Chiefs of Staff. It will then be sent to
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Abortions Further Restricted at Military Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors at military hospitals will not perform
abortions starting Oct. 1 unless the mother's life is in danger.
   Doctors have been barred since 1979 from performing abortions
paid for by the government unless the life of the mother is
endangered, but were allowed to perform so-called ``pre-paid
abortions'' in ``certain countries in which quality medical care
may not be locally available.''
   A memo obtained Monday signed by Dr. William Mayer, assistant
defense secretary for health affairs, changes the policy. It says
``it might suggest insensitivity to the spirit of the
congressionally enacted policy of withholding government
involvement in the provision of abortions.''
   There were 10,829 abortions performed at military facilities in
1980 and 88 in 1980, after Congress passed the prohibition,
according to a Pentagon audit.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embezzlement Suspect Released On $500,000 Bond</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agency for International Development
employee charged in the embezzlement of $1.2 million in government
funds is free on $500,000 bond after his brother and sister put
their home as collateral.
   William John Burns, an AID financial officer, was arrested last
week on allegations of diverting unused government travel funds and
released from jail on Monday. Government prosecutors opposed
releasing Burns, calling him a ``very serious flight risk.''
   The government has put a restraining order on Burns' bank
account, his home in suburban Burtonsville, Md., as well as five
cars and luxury goods allegedly bought with stolen government funds.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Air Force Challenges Proposed Fine For Radioactive Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force is taking issue with a proposed
fine by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission for alleged violations
associated with a 1986 spill of radioactive powder at an Ohio
military base, officials say.
   The $102,500 fine was proposed by the NRC last month for what
the agency said was willful failure to report the spill at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base within 24 hours and for the
internal exposure of an individual to the powder.
   ``The Air Force denies that it violated any of the NRC
regulations in the handling of this matter,'' the Air Force said in
its response to the NRC.
   Air Force spokeswoman June Green said Monday there is
disagreement among NRC workers themselves about the true nature of
the reporting requirement.
   No one was injured in the Sept. 19, 1986 spill of americium-241.
</TEXT>
