<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--ConventionBriefs     07-19 0936</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Briefs,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Gives Dukakis Lead Among Hispanic-Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis holds a 58 percent to 32
percent lead over Republican George Bush among Hispanic voters,
according to a poll released by a Spanish-language television
network.
   The survey of 612 likely Hispanic voters, which had a margin of
error of 4.7 percentage points, showed the Massachusetts governor
held a better than 2-1 margin among Mexican-Americans and Puerto
Rican-Americans, Univision said.
   But the vice president is favored by 80 percent of
Cuban-American voters _ a traditionally strong Republican
community, the network said.
   Overall, 10 percent of the Hispanic voters were undecided.
   The survey was conducted July 1-13, using a combination of
door-to-door and telephone interviews, Univision said.
   An ABC survey of 458 registered voters conducted Sunday,
meanwhile, found Dukakis and Vice President George Bush in a dead
heat among all voters, with 45 percent for Dukakis and 46 percent
for Bush.
   The survey, with a margin of error of five points, found Bush
doing better with women than in past surveys and found Dukakis
receiving no immediate benefit from the selection of Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas as a running mate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Convicted Ohio Delegate Gets To Stay; Poor Attendance Gets Other</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Booted
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor attendance at Democratic Party functions,
but not a criminal conviction, is grounds for dismissal from the
Ohio delegation to the Democratic National Convention.
   State party chairman James Ruvolo on Monday replaced former
State Sen. Marigene Valiquette as one of Ohio's ``super delegates''
following criticism of her continued absences from party events
over the last several months.
   But Ruvolo took no action to remove a Cleveland labor leader who
is appealing a felony conviction for illegally using union money
for a political purpose.
   Ruvolo had reportedly been under pressure to replace Martin J.
Hughes, who has attended every convention since 1964. The chairman
said that national party rules contain no provision for the removal
of Democratic National Committee members.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Handicapped Delegates Plan To Demonstrate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Handicapped delegates and alternates are facing
their normal share of troubles getting around during the Democratic
National Convention, says one of them, Carolyn Emerson of
Minneapolis.
   ``This really is no worse than normal,'' said Emerson, who must
walk with crutches because of a childhood bout with polio. Emerson,
41, said Monday she was an hour late for a meeting of disabled
delegates and alternates because of transportation problems.
   Activists for the disabled were planning a demonstration today
to protest rejection of their platform proposals, said delegate Tom
Isaac of Aspen, Colo.
   The advocates want the platform to include an endorsement of the
Americans with Disabilities Bill of 1988, which they say would end
discrimination against disabled people.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Plans 10,000 Fund-raising House Parties Thursday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Michael Dukakis takes center stage Thursday
night to accept his presidential nomination, his fund-raising team
will be trying to coordinate 10,000 house parties intended to bring
his campaign into the nation's living rooms.
   ``It's a way of getting people involved. Everyone can get
involved,'' said Kristin Demong, staff director of the Democratic
Victory Fund, the money-raising operation recently created by
merging the finance sections of the Democratic National Committee
and the Dukakis presidential campaign.
   Against the backdrop of a general election fund-raising goal of
at least $50 million, the house parties _ with a projected average
donation of $250 a head _ may not produce more than a fraction of
the fall total.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Celebs To Grace DNC Stage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They're outnumbered by the politicians, but the
stars are coming out to shine at the Democratic National Convention.
   Starting with humorist Garrison Keillor's recitation of the
Pledge of Allegiance and closing with music by gospel singer
Jennifer Holliday, the convention has so many celebrities it almost
threatens to be entertaining.
   Some of the entertainment Thursday will come from two members of
Gov. Michael Dukakis' clan. Cousin Olympia Dukakis, Oscar winner as
best supporting actress in the film ``Moonstruck,'' will introduce
the governor.
   Harry Ellis Dickson, his father-in-law and former associate
conductor of the Boston Pops, will conduct the ``Fanfare for
Michael Dukakis'' by composer John Williams, who also is the Pops'
conductor.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Callers Can Listen To Convention Uninterrupted On 900 Phone Number</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who don't want to miss any part of the
Democratic National Convention because of a beer commercial or some
other interruption may dial for a live feed at 1-900-909-DUKE.
   Uninterrupted convention coverage is available at a cost of $2
for the first minute and 35 cents for each minute after that, on a
national 900 telephone number.
   The service is offered by Elliott Communications, the
Washington-based information firm behind the number.
   ``Dial Duke'' callers will hear convention proceedings live from
the podium. An announcer will identify speakers and place events in
context.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Union Calls Off Picketing After Talking To DNC's Kirk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union trying to organize downtown janitors says
it is suspending its picketing of selected social events associated
with the Democratic convention in a truce arranged by party
chairman Paul Kirk.
   John Sweeney, president of the Service Employees International
Union, on Monday announced the ``pause'' in its campaign after Kirk
telephoned him the previous night relaying a message that Atlanta
architect and developer John Portman had expressed a new
willingness to negotiate.
   The union had focused on Portman's Peachtree Center properties
as its initial target in trying to unionize some 1,500 janitors in
56 downtown Atlanta office buildings. The center is where many of
the private receptions associated with the convention are being
held.
</TEXT>
