<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CVN--CarterText 3Takes   07-19 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Carter Text, 3 Takes,480-1680</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the speech by former
President Jimmy Carter to the Democratic National Convention Monday
night.
   When we left Washington 7{ years ago, I invited all my
Democratic friends to come to Georgia to see us. But I never
expected that you would all come _ and at the same time.
   Well, this is a grand gathering of Democrats. But there's going
to be an even greater one in January when we all meet in Washington
to celebrate the inauguration of Michael Dukakis as president and
Lloyd Bentsen as vice president.
   Oh, yes, I almost forgot. I have one announcement to make _
which, like a lot of other things this year may come as a bit of a
surprise to the incumbent vice president. My name is Jimmy Carter,
and I am not running for president! Did you hear that George?
   Well, I have to admit there are some parallels with both of our
final candidates. I'm a Southerner, I'm a Baptist, some people even
like to say I love to preach, and my political career was made
possible by the civil rights movement. That does sound familiar.
   There have been a lot of comparisons made between Mike Dukakis
and myself. But I know one thing for sure. Mike Dukakis is also
going from the State House to the White House.
   Our party has been blessed with good candidates this year. And
not just this year. Wouldn't Ed Muskie have made a great president?
   Jesse Jackson has stirred the soul of our country, he's given
hope to millions, and he's healed wounds that have too long divided
us one from another. He is an inspired leader, he is destined for
further greatness. Jesse, we salute you.
   Mike Dukakis ran a brilliant campaign of substance and respect
for the intelligence of the American people. He'll be a great
leader for our country.
   Mike is being compared to John F. Kennedy. He is from
Massachusetts. He has chosen a running mate from Texas. And he's
going to defeat an incumbent Republican vice president.
   Mike Dukakis deserves that comparison. But he reminds me of
other great leaders of our party as well. Like Woodrow Wilson, he's
an idealist who believes we can be true to our own best selves in a
brutal world.
   Like Harry Truman, he's a tough fighter.
   Like Franklin Delano Roosevelt, he's an innovator with the
courage to experiment and the confidence to find solutions.
   And let's be clear about one thing:
   We want Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen to be elected _ not just
so Democrats can take office in Washington, but because we know
that change is long overdue. We want a federal deficit brought
under control. We want a coherent foreign policy. And we want to
bring back to Washington people who are more interested in public
service than they are in private gain.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880719-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CVN--CarterText 1stadd   07-19 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Carter Text, 1st add,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: private gain.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Each of us pauses on occasion to reassess our own lives: to look
at what we have become, the mistakes we've made, and to decide what
we would like to be.
   I think, as a nation, we make this same kind of reassessment
when we elect a president. Now is the time to reconsider our
opportunities and our challenges _ to make a change _ and to decide
what we want for the future. Especially to decide what we want for
the future.
   A democracy is always an unfinished creation. Each generation
must rediscover the meaning of America's dream.
   Tonight I'm thinking not only about the next president, but
about our nation's children and how they will live in years to
come. Rosalynn and I have six grandchildren. What kind of world
will we leave to them and to other young people?
   In thinking about the past eight years and looking ahead, let's
recall the words of a great American president, Franklin Roosevelt.
Listen to what he said:
   ``Governments can err. Presidents do make mistakes; but...better
the occasional faults of a government that lives in a spirit of
charity than the consistent omissions of a government frozen in the
ice of its own indifference.''
   For the sake of our children, for the sake of our future, we
must melt that ice.
   It's time to reach out for the homeless, to families broken by
drug addiction and disease.
   It's time to clean up those Pentagon scandals and build a lean,
tough, competent military force.
   It's time to have a Justice Department that fights for civil
rights.
   It's time to quit living on credit and expecting our children to
pay the bills some day.
   It's time to tackle the continuing problems of poverty, of a
decaying environment, of the bankruptcy of family farms.
   And it's time to invest in the education and care of our
children.
   Because that's the kind of nation we are. That's the kind of
people we are.
   In some ways, America is a big family. A family does not ignore
the sickness or pain of any of its children. A family gives all its
members help and love. That is the kind of families we have _ and
that's the kind of nation we want.
   And a good family plans for its children's future _ and that
means education. Eight years ago, no American student was deprived
of a college education because of financial reasons. But now, for
many young Americans, these opportunities have been wiped out.
Starting in 1989, that is going to change.
   We Democrats do not fear change. We welcome it. Because change
means hope. Change means life. Above all, change means opportunity.
   And no changes are more profound than those taking place in the
Soviet Union. The world is fascinated with the news from Moscow.
General Secretary Gorbachev has made move after move that would
have seemed unthinkable a decade ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880719-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CVN--CarterText 2ndadd   07-19 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Carter Text, 2nd add,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: decade ago.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   It is still too early to assess the permanence or sincerity of
these changes. We must never forget that Mr. Gorbachev's actions
are designed to help his own country, not ours. Certainly the
competition between our superpowers will remain. But it can become
more peaceful and more constructive. And in that kind of
competition, the United States of America has all the advantages.
   We have a free and creative system of government. We are strong
economically. Our farm lands are highly productive. We espouse
basic human freedoms and democracy. We are a religious people. We
are on the cutting edge of technological and scientific progress.
Our neighbors are our friends, and not our slaves.
   Building on these foundations, our next president must regain
America's world leadership as the acknowledged champion of peace,
of arms control, of human rights, and of justice.
   The free world looks to us for leadership, but we cannot lead by
using military force to impose our will on other people. We can
best fight communism in Central America by joining with other
democratic nations to make sure that the Sandinistas and the
Contras carry out all the provisions of the Arias peace plan _ and
that the people of Central America have freedom from both
oppression and war.
   We have other responsibilities far from home.
   Camp David is not just a weekend retreat; it is a symbol of the
courage and determination of two great leaders _ an Egyptian and an
Israeli _ to make peace. Arabs and Jews still cry out for peace,
but without a strong and persistent involvement of the president of
the United States, they will not have peace. Starting in 1989, that
will change.
   It's time to renew our environmental commitments. The greenhouse
effect, the destruction of the ozone layer, acid rain are no longer
just theoretical possibilities _ they are immediate threats to all
of us. Beginning in 1989, a new Democratic president will work
other leaders on earth to ensure our children, and to ensure us, a
decent planet on which to live.
   This nation deserves a foreign policy based on the values that
unite us as Americans _ a foreign policy that can win the support,
for a change, of both political parties. The consequences of
unilateral decisions made in the White House bring back to us vivid
and unpleasant memories; U.S. Marines dying in Lebanon; harbors
illegally mined and Contras illegally armed; ransom paid to the
ayatollah in weapons; appeasement in the face of apartheid in South
Africa.
   Starting in 1989, that is also going to change.
   Ours is the strongest nation on earth _ but sometimes we forget
what measures our strength. America is strong when we are for peace
instead of belligerence. America is strong when we are the leading
defender of human rights. America is strong when we reach out to
the suffering. America is strong when we work with other nations to
reduce nuclear arsenals and to curtail the world's horrendous trade
in deadly weapons. America is strong when we protect the green
planet that gives us life.
   My fellow Democrats, our party is best equipped to meet the
challenge of change because we are the party of change.
   We are the party of diversity. Just look around this hall _
you'll see all the beautiful variety that makes America strong and
special and great.
   Because we are so inclusive, many of the conflicts of American
life are fought _ and creatively resolved _ within our ranks.
   That is our strength. But it is also our danger.
   That is why, if I had to give you just one special message
tonight, I would summarize it in a single word:
   Unity.
   One more time. One more time so you won't forget: Unity.
   Let us go forth from this convention united behind our
candidates and our ideals _ and with our eyes on the prize.
   United, united, we Democrats will bring a great future to
America.
   Our grandchildren _ and yours _ will be grateful.
   Thank you. God bless you. Good night. On to victory. Thank you.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Carter Text _ 3 Takes</HEAD>
</DOC>
