<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     07-19 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Says Rebels Shell Kabul, Kill Eight People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels fired rockets into the Afghan capital of
Kabul this morning and one missile blast killed eight people and
wounded nine, the Soviet news agency Tass reported from Afghanistan.
   It was the second reported bombardment of Kabul in five days.
   Tass said rockets rained down on city streets and crossroads as
people went to work. The only known casualty toll was from the
rocket that exploded in the city's Khairkhan district, it said.
   On Friday, 21 rockets were fired into residential areas of
Kabul, killing 20 people, wounding 34 and damaging a mosque and
other buildings, Tass reported.
   It blamed the attacks on insurgents fighting the Moscow-backed
government of President Najib.
   But Abdul Haq, a rebel leader in Peshawar, Pakistan, denied that
guerrillas target civilian neighborhoods and said the Soviets
themselves might have staged the bombardment to sap support for the
rebels.
   The Soviets began withdrawing their more than 100,000 troops
from Afghanistan on May 15. Under terms of U.N.-brokered accords,
all are to be home by February.
   Both Afghan and Soviet media have said the guerrillas are
stepping up their military activity as the Soviet troops leave.
</TEXT>
