<HEAD>ATLANTA: being held.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Turner Denied Own Parking Space In Security Mixup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ted Turner, owner of the CNN Center and the Omni
Hotel, could not get into his parking space Monday morning because
of security measures adopted during the Democratic National
Convention.
   Turner's car was turned away from the executive parking area
below the complex by security guards who apparently did not
recognize his credentials.
   Turner eventually parked two blocks away and walked to his
building, said Jim Kitchell, vice president of special operations
for Turner Broadcasting System Inc.
   Kitchell said the problem had been resolved and Turner would be
allowed to park beneath the building today.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>__</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nobody Remembered To Invite The Archbishop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta Roman Catholic Archbishop Eugene Marino
was scheduled to give an invocation at the opening of the
Democratic National Convention, but nobody remembered to invite him.
   Printed schedules distributed by the Democratic National
Committee showed Marino praying shortly after the call to order
Monday afternoon.
   Marino looked surprised when a minister mentioned it to him
during an interfaith service Monday at Morehouse College.
   ``That's the first I've heard of it,'' he said.
   The invocation was given by L. Bevel Jones III, a bishop in the
United Methodist Church.
   Archdiocese officials contacted party officials Monday, and
Marino accepted an invitation to give the benediction for the
convention at 11 p.m. Thursday.
   ``There was a mixup,'' said the Rev. Peter Dora, spokesman for
the archdiocese.
</TEXT>
