<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Gulf-Raids 2ndLd-Writethru a0517 07-19 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gulf-Raids, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0517,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iraqis Conduct Air Strikes On Iran Coast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comment from Iraq, Iran. No pickup.
ADDS byline.
^By RICHARD PYLE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi warplanes conducted raids along the
Iranian coast Tuesday, a day after Iran announced it would accept a
U.N.-sponsored cease-fire to end the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   Iraq claimed it shot down an Iranian F-14 in a dogfight and
informed sources in the gulf said Iran might also have downed an
Iraqi jet fighter.
   An Iraqi military spokesman was quoted by Baghdad Radio as
saying an Iraqi warplanes shot down on Iranian warplane over the
gulf near the Iraqi port of Ammiq.
   The report, monitored in Nicosia, Cyprus, said all Iraqi planes
returned safely to base.But gulf sources said an Iranian F-14 had
also apparently shot down an Iraqi jet.
   ``There are a lot of planes in the air,'' said one source,
insisting on anonymity.
   The targets were not immediately identified, he said. It was not
known if any of Iran's tankers or oil terminals were attacked.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Nicosia, said Iraqi warplanes had violated Iran's airspace in
southeastern Khuzestan province.
   ``They were intercepted by heavy fire of the Iranian air defense
gunners,'' the IRNA report said. It did not mention any destruction
on the ground, but the agency usually reports bombing as air space
violations.
   The apparent raids were mounted a day after Iran announced it
would accept a cease-fire resolution passed by the U.N. security
council on July 20, 1987.
   The truce would not take effect until details were worked out
``within a week to ten days,'' United Nations Secretary General
Javier Perez de Cuellar said on Monday.
   Iraq has regularly attacked Iranian shuttle tankers and key oil
terminals in the gulf in an effort to choke off it's enemy's
revenue-earning exports. The last two reported Iraqi raids were on
July 14.
   The sources said it was not immediately clear what type of Iraqi
aircraft were involved, but they are usually French-built F-1
Mirages armed with Exocet missiles and other aircraft that carry
missiles and boimbs.
   The Iraqi air activity began about 8 a.m. (1 a.m. EDT) and
continued more than two hours later, said one of the sources, who
are well informed on shipping activity in the gulf.
   An Iraqi aircraft was shot down over the central gulf, the
sources said, apparently by one of Iran's U.S.-built F-14 fighters,
some of which are known to be based at Bushehr on the Iranian coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
