<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Flood     07-19 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Flood,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flash Floods Kill Up to 18 At Sacred Peak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flash floods and mudslides killed as many as 18
people and stranded about 1,000 on central China's Mount Huashan,
one of the country's five most sacred peaks, according to reports
today.
   The overseas edition of the official People's Daily (Renmin
Ribao) said soldiers were called in to rescue climbers and
tourists, including an undetermined number of foreigners.
   Some people were apparently stranded on the mountain for up to
three days.
   The report said torrential rains and hailstorms washed out paths
and caused cave-ins on Friday and that almost all those on the
7,000-foot mountain had been evacuated by Monday.
   The official Xinhua News Agency, quoting Shaanxi province
police, said 18 climbers were killed on the mountain, while the
army rescued most everyone else who had been stranded.
   An official of the Shaanxi province Foreign Affairs Office,
contacted by telephone, put the death toll at 15.
   The official, who declined to be identified by name, said nine
of the dead were private vendors working at the foot of the
mountain. He said no foreigner was among the dead or injured.
   Mount Huashan, known for its steep cliffs and spectacular
scenery, is popular among summertime climbers and tourists.
</TEXT>
