<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Coming To America' Earns $10 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Coming to America,'' starring Eddie Murphy as
a prince in search of a bride, earned $10 million as the top draw
at the nation's weekend box office, while Clint Eastwood's ``The
Dead Pool'' came in second place with $9 million.
   Two Walt Disney movies, ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' and
``Bambi,'' were in third and fourth place, respectively, separated
by 46 years and several generations of cartoon technology.
   ``Roger Rabbit,'' which mixes live and animated action, earned
$8.5 million, while ``Bambi,'' originally released in 1942, sold
$7.2 million worth of tickets.
   The boy-in-a-man's-body comedy ``Big'' was in fifth place with
$5 million in sales, while the baseball movie ``Bull Durham'' was
in sixth place with $3.3 million. The robot fantasy ``Short Circuit
2,'' with $3.2 million in sales, was seventh, and teen-on-wheels
comedy ``License To Drive'' was eighth with a $2.9 million take.
   The Dudley Moore sequil ``Arthur 2: On The Rocks,'' dropped from
third to ninth place in its second week of release, earning just
over $2.9 million. In 10th place was the Ausssie adventure-comedy
```Crocodile Dundee' II,'' with $2.2 million in sales.
   Two movies that fans had been awaiting but were not widely
released made their debut this week and racked up large per-theater
earnings.
   ``Die Hard,'' starring Bruce Willis as an off-duty cop who takes
on a band of terrorists, earned $601,851 at just 21 theaters. The
20th Century Fox release averaged $28,660 per screen.
   The John Cleese mystery-comedy ``A Fish Called Wanda'' opened at
just three theaters for a weekend take of $115,418, or $38,473 per
theater. The release is from MGM-UA.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Coming To America,'' Paramount, $10.4 million, 2,064
screens, $5,047 per screen, $66.7 million, three weeks, $30 million.
   2. ``The Dead Pool,'' Warner Bros., $9 million, 1,831 screens,
$4,954 per screen, $12.7 million, one week, $18 million.
   3. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' Disney, $8.5 million, 1,314
screens, $6,567 per screen, $69.2 million, four weeks, $40 million.
   4. ``Bambi,'' Disney, $7.2 million, 1,483 screens, $4,866 per
screen, $7.2 million, one week, n-a.
   5. ``Big,'' 20th Century Fox, $5 million, 1,346 screens, $3,740
per screen, $68.5 million, seven weeks, $15 million.
   6. ``Bull Durham,'' Orion, $3.3 million, 1,134 screens, $2,921
per screen, $32.3 million, five weeks, $12 million.
   7. ``Short Circuit 2,'' Tri-Star, $3.2 million, 1,348 screens,
$2,395 per screen, $10.2 million, two weeks, n-a.
   8. ``License To Drive,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.91 million, 1,225
screens, $2,381 per screen, $10.4 million, two weeks, n-a.
   9. ``Arthur 2: On The Rocks,'' Warner Bros., $2.90 million,
1,426 screens, $2,035 per screen, $10.2 million, two weeks, $18
million.
   10. ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' Paramount, $2.2 million, 1,248
screens, $1,837 per screen, $96.1 million, five weeks.
