<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Sweep Through Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms spread drenching rain over much of the nation
today after a series of violent storms hit Nebraska, bringing a
tornado, heavy rains that flooded streets and fierce winds.
   Showers and thunderstorms were spread early this morning from
eastern Wyoming across eastern Colorado, from southwestern South
Dakota across western Nebraska and western Kansas, over southeast
Oklahoma, northern Arkansas, southern Missouri, the Ohio Valley,
the lower Great Lakes, Pennsylvania, Virginia, New Jersey,
Delaware, Maryland and southeast Georgia.
   A tornado touched down Monday night at Hershey, Neb., but there
were no reports of damage.
   Heavy rains from thunderstorms also flooded many streets of
Clovis, N.M., where waters were reported to be waist high.
   Several areas of south-central Nebraska were deluged with rain
early this morning. Two inches of rain hit Red Cloud in a 10-15
minute period and Holdrege reported receiving 4{ inches of rain. An
area near Phelps was inundated by 5\ inches of rain in one hour.
   Thunderstorm winds gusted to 60 mph south of Kimball, Neb., and
near Wewoka, Okla., to 66 mph at Goodland, Kan., and to 70 mph at
Wray, Colo.
   High winds and heavy rain swept through Tavares, Fla., on
Monday, damaging mobile homes, battering businesses and knocking
out electricity for more than an hour, police said.
   A mobile home park in the central Florida town reported one if
its homes destroyed and several others damaged. Aluminum roofs and
carports also were blown off at a few homes and a 4-foot-wide oak
tree fell in the storm, police said.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from New
England across North Carolina, from the lower Great Lakes across
the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, Alabama, the lower
Mississippi Valley, the upper Texas Gulf Coast, Kansas, southern
Nebraska, and southern and central Florida.
   High temperatures were forecast for the 70s over northern New
England, northern Minnesota, the Dakotas, western Nebraska and from
eastern Colorado across Montana; in the 90s from Virginia to
Florida, from the Tennessee Valley across the central Gulf Coast,
over the lower Mississippi Valley, Oklahoma, the eastern two-thirds
of Texas, New Mexico and the Pacific Northwest; 100 degrees and
hotter over the remainder of Texas; 100 to 115 over the desert
Southwest; and in the 80s over the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 47 at
Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 95 at both Desert Rock, Nev.,
and near Las Vegas, Nev.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 79 fair; Boston 74 partly cloudy; Buffalo 71
cloudy; Charleston, S.C., 81 fair; Cleveland 71 showers; Detroit 70
rain; Miami 77 partly cloudy; New York 71 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 78 cloudy; Pittsburgh 70 foggy; Portland, Maine, 72
cloudy; Washington 77 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 57 fair; Chicago 71 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
87 fair; Denver 62 partly cloudy; Des Moines 72 fair; Indianapolis
73 foggy; Kansas City 75 fair; Mpls-St. Paul 71 fair; Nashville 82
fair; New Orleans 77 fair; St. Louis 77 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 70 windy; Anchorage 63 fair; Las Vegas 94
fair; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 89 fair; Salt Lake City 68 fair;
San Diego 68 partly cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 71 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 72 showers; Toronto 73 cloudy.
  
