<DOCNO> AP880719-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0729EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-19 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen gallons of jelly bean ice cream
are on their way to President Reagan after being pronounced fit for
the presidential palate by Senate taste-tester Jake Garn.
   Utah congressional candidate Richard Snelgrove and his family
spent days whipping up a jelly bean recipe after Reagan, a jelly
bean aficionado, asked for it when Snelgrove visited the White
House with a group of Republican candidates last month.
   Snelgrove, a part-owner of Snelgrove Ice Cream Co., was told the
president's favorite jelly bean flavors are cherry and tangerine,
so the company made batches of both.
   After sampling the sweet concoction, Garn, R-Utah, pronounced it
a `10.'
   ``Now the Secret Service will test it before it's served to the
president,'' he said. ``Maybe they'll put a freezer in the Oval
Office.''
   Snelgrove joked that since he's providing desserts for Reagan,
other candidates may demand equal time.
   Reagan will not be the first president to sample the Snelgrove
family's treats. In 1935 the company provided Thanksgiving dessert
for President Franklin Roosevelt at Warm Springs, Ga., Snelgrove
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people might be thrilled to be feted by the
mayor and the governor, but Dr. Rosita Pildes says her favorite
birthday honor was the chance to see nearly 400 children she helped
heal.
   ``It's the best birthday present I could have _ to see all these
children getting well,'' said Ms. Pildes, 59, who has worked at
Cook County Hospital for 20 years.
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer and Gov. James Thompson proclaimed Monday
``Dr. Rosita Pildes Day'' in recognition of her work as chairwoman
of the hospital's Neo-Natal Network station.
   Ms. Pildes received the proclamations at a reunion picnic, where
nearly 400 children, from infants to teens, met many of the doctors
and nurses who had saved their lives.
   Dr. Lonnie Edwards, commissioner of the city's Department of
Health, and Bernard Turnock, director of the Illinois Department of
Public Health, presented Ms. Pildes with ``Mother of Neo-Natalogy''
awards and bouquets of flowers along with proclamations, said Wanda
Robertson, a hospital spokeswoman.
   The party was organized by staff members of the Neo-Natal
Network Station, which cares for premature infants who weigh less
than a pound, and for seriously ill newborns.
   ``We called the kids neo-natal graduates to remind them of the
medical problems they had, and that they succeeded at this point in
life,'' Ms. Robertson said.
</TEXT>
