<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `In Zurich ... late Monday,' to RESTORES
dropped digits. Picks up 10th graf, `Earlier, in ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened in early European trading
today, stung by dollar selling by the West German and Swiss central
banks, dealers said. Gold prices were higher.
   The dollar recovered slightly in late morning trading from
opening lows but remained lower against all major currencies
compared with Monday's late rates.
   Sales of dollars by the West German and Swiss central banks in
the open market depressed the dollar and unsettled the market,
dealers said.
   ``A lot of traders got their fingers burned, so for the moment
the central banks are in charge,'' said a dealer at a major Italian
commercial bank in Rome.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar dropped 1.30 Japanese yen to a closing 133.85 yen. Later, in
London, it was little changed at 133.88 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8648 West German marks, down from 1.8823
   _1.5470 Swiss francs, down from 1.5625
   _6.2885 French francs, down from 6.3415
   _2.0995 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1130
   _1,382.05 Italian lire, down from 1,390.50
   _1.2055 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2095
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6867 from $1.6693 late
Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $436.40 a troy ounce, up
from $436.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $437.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $437, up from $435 bid late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.02 to close at a bid $438.98.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $7.15 a troy
ounce, up from $7.13 bid late Monday.
</TEXT>
