<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Newborn-Airliner     07-19 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newborn-Airliner,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>County Retains Temporary Custody of Baby</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who hid her pregnancy from her
husband had only a short time to decide what to do when she gave
birth unexpectedly and secretly in a jetliner restroom, her lawyer
said.
   ``In 20 minutes, she had to make some decisions _ not only
physically how to deliver a baby in a DC-10, but how does she
resolve the dilemma she's created for herself by not telling
anyone?'' John L. Williams said Monday.
   ``(But) she never tried to harm the child. All she tried to do
was hide the child the way she tried to conceal the pregnancy,'' he
added.
   Williams, lawyer for Christina LoCasto of Staten Island, N.Y.,
spoke at a news conference after a juvenile court commissioner
ruled that her 5-day-old daughter would remain in the temporary
custody of San Mateo County.
   Mrs. LoCasto pleaded innocent last week to a felony charge of
child endangerment. The 24-year-old woman, who is free on $50,000
bail, is accused of abandoning her newborn daughter under the sink
of the jet restroom on a cross-country flight.
   Commissioner Patricia Bresee decided the infant will stay in a
foster home at least until Friday, when county social workers
present a report on the homes of LoCasto relatives as to their
fitness as a home for the baby.
   But until then, the LoCastos will be allowed to visit their new
daughter, Alyssa Frances LoCasto, under county supervision, Bresee
ruled.
   In making her decision, Bresee rejected a plea by Mrs. LoCasto's
husband, Louis LoCasto, 26, to grant him custody of the infant.
LoCasto's right to his daughter is not in dispute, but the couple's
decision to remain together was one reason for Bresee's decision,
his lawyer said.
   ``They are determined to remain united as a family unit and have
their daughter with them as soon as possible,'' attorney Vicki
Yeley said.
   The LoCastos and relatives rushed out a back door of the
courthouse and declined to talk with reporters.
   Williams said it was still uncertain why his client denied she
was pregnant ``to herself as much as others.''
   The LoCasto had been having domestic problems at the time Alyssa
was conceived, less than a year after the birth of their second
daughter, Tina, now 18 months old, Williams said. The couple also
has a 6-year-old daughter, Janine.
   Mrs. LoCasto denied she was pregnant when her husband asked, her
lawyer said.
   ``Once having told a lie of that magnitude, it became more
difficult to tell the truth,'' he said. ``As it became
progressively more difficult to tell the truth, the lie got bigger,
literally and figuratively.''
   Mrs. LoCasto, who had not sought medical care, was not aware she
was about to give birth when she, her husband and two daughters got
aboard a United Airlines jet in Newark, N.J. Wednesday for a family
vacation, Williams said.
   After the birth, Mrs. LoCasto told her husband she was sick,
Williams said. The flight crew, seeing blood in the restroom,
sealed it during the flight, and the newborn was found only after
the plane landed in San Francisco.
   The brown-haired, blue-eyed girl is now in a foster home.
   ``Alyssa is fine. She is healthy. She appears to be a normal
5-day-old infant ... suffering no ill effects of what occurred,''
said Gerry Hilliard, the baby's court-appointed lawyer.
</TEXT>
