<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0904EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     07-19 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Americans Leaving The Israeli-Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 Arab Americans have moved out of
the occupied territories because the Palestinian uprising has
threatened their safety and the education of their children, a U.S.
official said today.
   U.S. consulate spokesman David Good said the 2,000 Arab
Americans represent about one-quarter of those who lived in the
West Bank and east Jerusalem before the uprising began Dec. 8.
   On Monday night, some 3,000 Palestinians in Beit Sahour village
turned a funeral into an anti-Israeli demonstration after
17-year-old Admon Elias Hilal was killed by a brick that fell from
a fourth-floor army lookout post.
   Earlier in the day, Dutch Foreign Minister Hans Van Den Broek
toured the Kalandia refugee camp north of Jerusalem, setting off a
protest by Arab youths who chanted slogans and hurled rocks at
reporters.
   After Van Den Broek left, troops fired rubber bullets to break
up crowds who raised outlawed Palestinian flags and pictures of
Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Good said the main reason the Arab Americans are leaving the
occupied lands is the ``unsettled conditions'' caused by the
Palestinian rebellion. ``Many people are concerned about their
children's education or about them being caught up in violence,''
he told The Associated Press.
   The Israeli military administration closed Arabs schools in the
West Bank for four months during the uprising and cut short the
school year by about a month. The administration believes the
schools are centers of unrest.
   Many of the 224 Palestinians who have been killed since the
unrest broke out are teen-agers. Four Israelis also have died.
   Faris Bouhafa, spokesman for the Washington-based American Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee, said some departing Arab Americans
planned to return once conditions are calmer in the occupied
territories.
   Bouhafa, who said his 8-year-old organization has 61 chapters
and 20,000 members in the United States, is in Israel to expand the
role of the group's east Jerusalem branch, which was established
three months ago.
</TEXT>
