<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0915EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MacArthurAwards 1stLd-Writethru a0465 07-19 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MacArthur Awards, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MacArthur Award Winners Include Puppeteer, Firefighter,
Handicapped Writer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to recast, include more detail on Dubus,
picking up 6th graf pvs, ``Recipients of xxxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A writer who had to borrow money for treatment
after he was disabled in an accident received one of 31 MacArthur
awards announced today and said he will use the money ``to pay the
people who take care of me until I die.''
   Fiction writer Andre Dubus said he felt ``gratitude so extreme
that I haven't recovered from it yet.''
   Like other recipients, Dubus, whose latest book was ``The Last
Worthless Evening,'' learned of his award last week.
   ``I've been using borrowed money for the people who take care of
me,'' said Dubus, 51, in an interview Monday from his Haverhill,
Mass., home. He was injured and had a leg amputated two years ago
after he was hit by a car while helping another motorist.
   He said he plans to invest his $310,000 grant so that he will
have enough money to pay for his treatment and caregivers for the
rest of his life.
   Dubus, whose work has concentrated on discontented New
Englanders, has already won a Guggenheim grant, the PEN-New England
Award for literary distinction and an award from the American
Academy and Institute of Arts and Letters.
   Last year Stephen King, John Irving, Kurt Vonnegut, John Updike
and other authors gave a series of readings to help raise $100,000
for Dubus' treatment.
   Other MacArthur winners include a firefighter who studies the
cultural history of fires, noted jazz percussionist Max Roach and
the granddaughter of President Theodore Roosevelt.
   Recipients of the awards, which range from $150,000 to $375,000,
are free to use the money as they wish.
   Individuals are nominated anonymously for the fellowships _ they
may not apply _ and a 15-member selection committee reviews the
nominations.
   The John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation's board of
directors gives final approval of the winners.
   ``We believe that in enabling these extraordinarily talented
individuals to discover and create free of financial constraints,
the Fellows Program makes a valuable contribution to American
scientific and cultural life,'' said John Corbally, the
foundation's president.
   ``The whole goal is to give you the freedom to develop your
research in the way that you see best,'' added recipient Anna
Curtenius Roosevelt, an archaeologist and granddaughter of the
country's 26th president.
   Ms. Roosevelt, 42, who won a $265,000 grant, has been studying
ancient cultures of the tropical lowlands of South America for
nearly 15 years.
   ``We believe that we have found the earliest pottery in the New
World in a site near the city of Santarem in Brazil,'' she said in
a telephone interview Monday from New York, where she is a visting
researcher at the American Museum of Natural History.
   Other 1988 winners include novelist Thomas Pynchon, whose works
include ``Gravity's Rainbow''; Bruce D. Schwartz, a Los Angeles
puppeteer who draws from Japanese and European traditions; and Ruth
Behar, an anthropologist from Ann Arbor, Mich., who studies Mexican
sorcery and at 31 is the youngest recipient this year.
   ``I'm still in kind of a state of shock about it,'' said
recipient Hipolito Roldan, head of the Hispanic Housing Development
Corp., a private non-profit group that finds housing for low-income
Hispanic families in Chicago.
   ``Housing or a home is the place where lives get built or
shattered,'' he said. ``To the extent that a kid has a space, maybe
even their own room, to study in ... to plan for the future, is a
very important thing.''
   Stephen J. Pyne, 39, an environmental historian and professional
firefighter, called his $250,000 award ``a bolt out of the blue.''
   Pyne, who studies ways in which people have interacted with fire
throughout history, figures he was selected for ``doing kind of
original stuff, different kinds of things in environmental
history.''
   A total of 254 MacArthur fellows, ranging in age from 18 to 82,
have been named since the program began in 1981. Fellows receive
their grants in increments over five years, with the larger awards
going to the older recipients. Winners also receive health
insurance.
   The grant-making foundation is one of the largest private
philanthropic groups in the United States. MacArthur, owner of
Bankers' Life And Casualty insurance company, established it
shortly before his death in 1978. His wife died shortly thereafter.
   After he created the foundation, MacArthur told his board of
directors, ``I figured out how to make it, you figure out how to
spend it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
