<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--BeachBashing     07-19 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Beach Bashing,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Blasts Bahamas Ad For Slighting New Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional candidate says an ad
campaign for the Bahamas that alludes to beach pollution problems
in New York and New Jersey is in poor taste and should be halted.
   Joseph Azzolina, a Republican candidate in New Jersey's 3rd
Congressional District, said a full-page ad in Friday's editions of
The New York Times undercuts the drawing power of beaches in the
two states.
   Beaches in New York have been plagued by raw sewage and medical
waste. Several beaches in New Jersey remained closed Monday after
water samples continued to show high levels of a bacteria
associated with human waste.
   The Bahamas ad, created by the D'Arcy, Masius, Benton & Bowles
agency, depicted a beach with a shell washing ashore and read:
``The only thing that washes up on our beaches.''
   ``As a businessman I know that it is not smart ... to turn
someone else's misfortune into your own gain,'' Azzolina said in a
letter to the firm.
   Agency officials could not be reached for comment. Calls to the
firm's New York City office were unanswered.
</TEXT>
