<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0559 07-19 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0559,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Warplanes Attack Iran One Day After Peace Breakthrough</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Iraq claiming it shot down
another Iranian warplane; Iran saying its nuclear plant damaged but
providing no further details. Pickup 9th graf pvs ``U.S. Navy...''.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With PM-UN-Iran-Iraq, Bjt
^By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Iraqi warplanes raided a
nuclear plant and other targets in Iran today, causing deaths and
injuries a day after Iran accepted a U.N. plan for ending the
8-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   Iran claimed it shot down three Iraqi warplanes while Iraq said
it downed two Iranian jet fighters.
   Iran said the nuclear power station in the gulf city of Bushehr
was damaged in the Iraqi raid, but the report from the official
Islamic Republic News Agency did not provide details. The
unfinished plant was bombed last November, and 11 people were
killed. Iran at the time claimed fissionable material was stored at
the site, but the report was never confirmed independently.
   The Iraqi fighters also damaged a petrochemical plant and other
industrial targets in Bushehr, according to the IRNA report
monitored in Cyprus.
   The unfinished petrochemical plant is a joint Japanese-Iranian
project. IRNA said Japan announced today it was willing to begin
talks on completing the project.
   The Iranian agency said the Iraqis also launched air raids near
the city of Ahvaz in the southwestern province of Khuzestan. ``They
were intercepted by heavy fire of the Iranian air defense
gunners,'' IRNA said.
   The agency said several people were killed and wounded in the
Iraqi attacks.
   The Iraqi military claimed it shot down two Iranian F-14 jet
fighters, one in a dogfight over the gulf near the Iraqi port of
Ammiq and another over Iraqi territory in the northern oil
producing city of Kirkuk.
   An unidentified military spokesman quoted by the Iraqi news
agency said the warplane downed over Kirkuk ``tried to violate
international borders to raid residential areas ... and our
anti-air defenses shot it down.''
   A Baghdad Radio report, also monitored in Cyprus, said all Iraqi
planes returned safely to base.
   IRNA quoted an unidentified air force commander as denying any
Iranian planes were lost. IRNA said Iran shot down three Iraqi
planes, two in dogfights over the gulf and one by anti-aircraft
guns. It did not say where the third plane went down.
   U.S. Navy officials in the gulf declined to comment on the
reports.
   On Monday, Iran announced it had agreed to a year-old United
Nations resolution for a cease-fire in its war with Iraq, which has
claimed an estimated 1 million lives.
   The cease-fire would not take effect until details are worked
out within a week to 10 days, U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez
de Cuellar said Monday.
   Iraq has regularly attacked Iranian shuttle tankers and key oil
terminals in the gulf in an effort to choke off its enemy's
revenue-earning exports. The last two reported Iraqi raids were on
July 14.
   The sources said it was not immediately clear what type of Iraqi
aircraft were involved in today's raids, but they are usually
French-built F-1 Mirages armed with Exocet missiles and other
aircraft that carry missiles and bombs.
   The Iraqi air activity began about 8 a.m. (1 a.m. EDT) and
continued more than two hours later, according to an informed
source in the gulf.
   An Iraqi aircraft was shot down over the central gulf, the
sources said, apparently by one of Iran's U.S.-built F-14 fighters,
some of which are known to be based at Bushehr.
</TEXT>
