<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--StartingTime     07-19 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Starting Time,160</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic National Convention will start at
3 p.m. EDT today, 90 minutes earlier than planned, to give
delegates more time to discuss any controversial issues in the
platform.
   Paul Kirk Jr., chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
said both the campaigns of Michael Dukakis, the presidential
nominee-to-be, and Jesse Jackson, who ran second in the primaries,
agreed to the change.
   Kirk said the party wanted to have ``free, open and comfortable
debate.'' without impinging on the time allotted to tonight's
speakers, including Jackson and Rep. William Gray, D-Pa.
   The delegates are to vote tonight on two minority platform
planks put forth by Jackson's supporters. They include a call to
raise taxes on the wealthy and a pledge against first use of
nuclear weapons.
   Delegates will debate a third Jackson minority plank on the
issue of a homeland for the Palestinians but will not vote on it,
Kirk said.
