<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSEstimates     07-19 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Estimates,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYC To Lower Estimate Of Number Of Residents Infected With HIV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City health officials have lowered their
estimate of the number of New Yorkers infected with the AIDS virus
by nearly half, to 250,000, according to a report published today.
   The new estimate is based mainly on a reduction in the estimated
population of homosexual and bisexual men living in the city, The
New York Times reported.
   The new estimates were to be presented tonight to a panel headed
by Health Commissioner Stephen C. Joseph. The Times attributed the
250,000 estimate to an epidemiologist who worked on the figures.
   The previous estimated number of infected New Yorkers was
400,000, or one in every 18 city residents. Then-Health
Commissioner David Sencer released that figure in 1985 and called
it ``conservative.''
   In the earlier projections, health officials estimated there
were half a million gay and bisexual men in the city, with 60
percent believed to be infected. The new estimate is expected to be
cut roughly in half, with the percentage infected to remain the
same, the Times said.
   The number of infected intravenous drug users, who now account
for more new cases in the city than any other group, is not
expected to change.
   There is no known cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome,
which is caused by a virus that attacks the body's immune system.
   Timothy Sweeney, deputy director of the Gay Men's Health Crisis,
told the Times he believes the figures undercount the gay
population.
   ``Everybody knows that big cities, and New York in particular,
act as a magnet and that there has been a great migration of
gays,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
