<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-BragaSantos     07-19 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Braga Santos,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portuguese Composer Dies At 64</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Manuel Braga Santos, one of
Portugal's leading composers and a conductor, died of a heart
attack at his home in Lisbon. He was 64.
   The composer died Monday, according to a spokesman for the
Radiodifusao Portuguesa radio network, where Braga Santos was a
music director.
   His six symphonies, as well as overtures, opera and choral works
have been performed by orchestras in Europe, the United States and
Japan.
   In 1966, Braga Santos' Fifth Symphony was awarded a United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
International Composers' Tribune prize.
   The early works of the composer, who studied at the Lisbon
Conservatory and in Italy, were influenced by the Portuguese
Renaissance and traditional music from the southern Alentejo
region. He later developed a more chromatic and often dissonant
style.
   Braga Santos also conducted Portuguese orchestras, wrote musical
criticism for several newspapers and taught at the National
Conservatory.
   Funeral services were to held today at the Campo Grande Church
in Lisbon.
</TEXT>
