<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Protests 1stLd-Writethru a0493 07-19 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrests at Anti-Abortion Blockade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new to add arrests today and CORRECT spelling of
``Lenora'' in 5th graf pvs, Williams however</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested more than 100 anti-abortion
protesters today, early on the second day of the Democratic
National Convention.
   In midtown Atlanta, blocks from the convention site, 134 people
were charged with criminal trespassing, unlawful assembly or other
counts after trying to block access to a clinic where abortions are
performed.
   Police Maj. Ken Burnette said there was no violence.
   The protest started a third day of demonstrations at or near the
convention. Until today's anti-abortion rally only one arrest had
been reported.
   On Monday, black activists marched through downtown Atlanta to
protest the way prospective Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis has treated Jesse Jackson. But they got into a shouting
match with a leftist black candidate over her suggestion that they
bolt the Democratic Party.
   Meanwhile, gay rights activists staged a ``die-in'' memorial to
AIDS victims while police thwarted a gay ``kiss-in'' on Monday.
   The march to protest the treatment of Jackson was led by civil
rights activist Hosea Williams, who led the group to a protest zone
near the Democratic Convention hall. Williams has been an outspoken
critic of Jackson's in the past, but the banner in front of the
line read, ``Jesse, we're with you in '88. America is still
racist.''
   The marchers were greeted by Lenora Fulani, an independent
candidate on the leftist New Alliance ticket, who accused Dukakis
of being a ``white supremacist candidate.'' Ms. Fulani said she
would hold a ``people's convention'' outside The Omni convention
hall to offer herself as the best candidate for black America.
   Williams, however, urged the crowd not to turn its back on the
Democratic Party and twice wrestled with Ms. Fulani for control of
the microphone, saying, ``We are not going to let anybody run us
out of the Democratic Party.''
   When Williams left, Ms. Fulani turned the microphone over to the
Rev. Al Sharpton of New York, who called for justice for Tawana
Brawley, the New York teen-ager who says she was sexually and
racially abused by six white men in Dutchess County, N.Y., last
November.
   She appeared on the rally stage surrounded by her mother and a
knot of supporters but did not speak.
   In another demonstration, about 20 gay men and lesbian women
affiliated with a group called ACT UP, or AIDS Coalition to Unleash
Power, held a ``kiss-in'' in front of the Omni Hotel.
   Within minutes, about 80 riot-helmeted police, holding shields
and chanting ``move, move, move,'' forced the demonstrators about
1{ blocks past the designated demonstration area, where they were
taunted and spat on by groups of young men with shaved heads and
combat boots.
   One bystander was hit in the head by a rock and was taken to a
hospital for stitches, said Red Cross spokesman Bill Saye.
   Kevin Squatter, 19, hometown unknown, was arrested on a charge
of aggravated assault for allegedly throwing a rock that hit the
bystander, said Sandra Blount of the convention coordination center
in charge of security.
   At the ``die-in'' memorial, protesters drew chalk outlines
around others lying on the asphalt, while names of AIDS victims
were chalked in and read over loudspeakers.
   In another protest, anti-abortion activists, displaying aborted
fetuses to reporters and holding a banner branding Michael Dukakis
``The Duke Of Death,'' and an anti-war group known as No Business
As Usual.
   The No Business demonstrators, young people in ragged clothing,
some carrying skateboards, chanted, ``Pro-life is a lie; you don't
care if women die,'' and other slogans.
   Temperatures reached above 90 Monday and Red Cross officials
braced for a brisk week of treating heat exhaustion cases. About
two dozen protesters succumbed Sunday, and 30 to 40 were treated
Monday.
</TEXT>
