<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0565 07-19 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0565,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiite Moslem Clan Continues Attack On Christian Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to update with 5 dead, 25 wounded,
cease-fire called. Picks up 4th graf pvs ``The attacks ....''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem Shiite tribesmen bombarded a
Maronite Catholic town with rockets, howitzers and mortars for a
third day today. Police said five people were killed and 25 wounded.
   The flighting raised the casualty toll to 11 dead and 45 wounded
since clashes began Sunday between members of the Jaafar Shiite
clan and other residents of the Syrian-policed town of Qoubaiyat,
70 miles northeast of Beirut.
   A police spokesman in Tripoli, the provincial capital of north
Lebanon, said residents of Qoubaiyat early today repulsed three
major attacks by about 2,000 members of the Jaafar clan. A
cease-fire was called for 2 p.m., and police said the fighting
abated after that time.
   The attacks were preceded by a fierce barrage from rocket
launchers, howitzers and mortars, with shells slamming into
Qoubaiyat at the rate of about 10 rounds per minute, added the
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said several
mortar rounds fell into the courtyard of the town's ancient stone
church, causing some damage. The church houses six monks and 20
nuns, who were unhurt, he added.
   The spokesman said the clashes began Sunday, a day after armed
shepherds from Qoubaiyat and the Jaafars engaged in a brief
firefight over grazing rights in sheep pastures on the town's
western edge.
   ``Two people were killed in the original clash for pastures. But
it seems the incident has developed into a Shiite-Maronite war,''
the spokesman said. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The residents of Qoubaiyat appealed to Pope John Paul II in Rome
for ``immediate intervention to stop the military offensive against
our peaceful town.''
   The appeal said there were ``a number of wounded people trapped
in the town who need hospitalization.''
   Qoubaiyat, population 25,000, is the fourth largest Catholic
town in north Lebanon. Most of its younger men serve in the
Lebanese army.
   The Jaafar clan, estimated to number about 35,000 people, is
based in the central Bekaa Valley on the western edge of the Akkar
plateau, a region traditionally dominated by Maronite Catholics and
Sunni Moslems.
   The police spokesman said the Syrian command in north Lebanon
and the Bekaa Valley was ``in contact with representatives of the
two sides to work out a lasting cease-fire.''
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 25,000 troops
in the Bekaa and north Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate
from the 21-nation Arab League.
   About 15,000 Syrian troops also are deployed in Moslem west
Beirut and the city's predominantly Shiite southern slums.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
