<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Democrats     07-19 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Democrats,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Spokeswoman Says Democrats' Barb About Bush Was `Thin'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush probably didn't catch Democratic
keynoter Ann Richards' barb that he had ``a silver foot in his
mouth,'' but a campaign spokeswoman said today Americans ``are more
interested in leadership than laugh lines.''
   ``Her audience liked it. I'm not sure how well it will play
everywhere else. I don't think nastiness ever plays very well,''
said Bush's press secretary, Sheila Tate.
   Bush, fishing in Wyoming with Treasury Secretary James A. Baker
III, had no plans to watch or listen to the Democratic National
Convention, and thus likely missed Monday night's keynote address,
Ms. Tate said.
   In that speech, Ms. Richards, who is Texas' state treasurer,
brought roars of delight from Democrats with her ``silver foot''
line.
   ``I do think it played well to that liberal convention crowd.
But I thought it was thin on substance, thinner on facts and I
thought it was thinnest on any vision,'' Ms. Tate said.
   ``It seems to me that people are more interested in leadership
than in laugh lines,'' she added.
   The spokeswoman said that, while Bush likely didn't hear any of
the speech, ``I'm sure we'll tell him about it.''
   ``He wanted to stare at a fish eye, not the CBS eye or the NBC
peacock,'' Ms. Tate said.
