<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Wedtech-Wallach     07-19 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wedtech-Wallach,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sets Jan. 3 Trial Date for Ex-Meese Associates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next Wedtech corruption trial, which
involves two former associates of Attorney General Edwin Meese III,
won't begin until early next year.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Owen scheduled a Jan. 3 start for
the trial of attorney E. Robert Wallach, 53, a longtime Meese
friend, former Meese financial consultant W. Franklyn Chinn, 45,
and R. Kent London, 44, a Chinn business associate.
   The date guarantees the corruption trial, with its potential for
politically embarrassing the Reagan administration, won't take
place until after the November presidential election.
   Prosecutors asked Owen for an earlier date but the defense said
it needed more time and one defense attorney said he would be tied
up in other trials until early December.
   Wallach and Chinn, of San Francisco, and London, of Honolulu,
are charged in a racketeering conspiracy with allegedly extracting
millions of dollars from Wedtech Corp., a now-bankrupt defense
contractor, to influence Meese and other officials. All three have
pleaded innocent.
   Meese was not charged with any wrongdoing and a special
prosecutor in Washington, while critical of the attorney general's
conduct regarding Wedtech and other matters, decided there was not
enough evidence to indict him.
   Meese plans to leave office by early August.
   Another Wedtech-related racketeering trial involving Rep. Mario
Biaggi, D-N.Y., Wedtech founder John Mariotta and five others is
nearing completion at federal court in Manhattan.
</TEXT>
