<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--For$50Million 1stLd-Writethru a0472 07-19 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--For $50 Million, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greasing the Wheels of the Dukakis Fund-Raising Machine</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS new graf 21 with $12 million collection; picks up pvs
graf 21: While the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas oilman G.P. Cokinos watched in joyful
reverie as a roomful of his fellow Dukakis fund-raisers danced to a
blaring band. ``I am having one of the finest times of my life,''
he yelled over the din.
   The Michael Dukakis campaign wouldn't have it any other way. The
financial juggernaut of the primary season is greasing the wheels
this week for a $50 million effort this fall by courting big money
with a fervor rare in Democrats.
   ``I have 14 events today. Five dinners! And I'm trying to lose
weight,'' said Robert Farmer, mastermind of the Dukakis money
machine. ``It's like a six-day party where everybody you ever met
is there, and you're the host.''
   This host wants the most. The Democrats long have lagged in fund
raising, relying instead on their political networks. No more, said
Farmer: ``We're going to create a level playing field with the
Republicans for the first time in my lifetime.''
   To even come close, the effort requires platoons of wealthy,
motivated fund-raisers. So in Atlanta, with a barrage of
celebrity-packed parties, the campaign is courting monied men and
women for all they're worth.
   For starters, there are the 1,100 Dukakis backers who each
raised at least $10,000, and some more than $50,000, in the
primaries. There are old-line fat cats from the financial capitals.
And there are scores of supporters of the vanquished Democratic
candidates.
   ``They have taken all of the Gore people, all of the Gephardt
people,'' said Howard Glicken, formerly a top money man for Rep.
Richard Gephardt's Florida campaign. When Gephardt dropped out of
the Democratic race, Glicken said, he didn't call the Dukakis
people. ``They called me.''
   That kind of organization is Farmer's hallmark. Fund-raisers are
thanked with notes, calls, personal visits. The campaign arranged
their flights and hotel rooms for convention week. Each has a full
schedule of strategy sessions.
   And there are the parties.
   ``There's something every day, social as well as business,''
said Frank Salafia, a Lawrence, Mass, chiropractor. ``This is part
of what Michael's all about. He doesn't forget people. He's not
afraid to say `thank you'.''
   One of the first events, billed as a Greek festival, was a
classic of political stroking. Dukakis wasn't in town, but his son
and daughter-in-law greeted the crowd at a downtown mall with the
news that she was pregnant.
   Cheers. Then Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., announced,
``Actually, I'm Greek.'' More cheers.
   Then Alpha Omega Sound started spinning out the dance tunes. The
costumed dancers of Troupe Hellas hit the floor. The wine and beer
and soft drinks flowed. Heaps of souvlaki were served. Farmer
worked the crowd.
   ``It is very pleasing to be made to feel a part of the family,''
said Atlanta computer consultant Krishna Srinivasa. ``I am not
Greek. But I feel Greek here _ getting Greek food, listening to
Greek music. They are turning us all into Greeks.''
   Not that Indians won't do nicely. Two friends of Srinivasa,
Rameshwar Singh of San Jose, Calif., and Himmat Kulharya of Dallas
said they'd raised $90,000 for Dukakis in the Indian-American
community.
   Chiropractor Salafia said he'd come up with ``sizable''
donations. Cokinos, an effusive Beaumont, Texas, oilman, proudly
pulled a photocopied $10,000 check from his wallet and said he'd
raised more than $25,000 in all.
   ``When Cokinos calls, they give me some attention,'' he said of
the Dukakis campaign. ``They could not treat me nicer. I asked for
some press credentials and they turned me down so nicely I was
almost sorry I asked.''
   As well as they've done for Dukakis, these men will have to
increase their production vastly to reach the big leagues.
   Farmer so far has recruited 135 people to raise or donate
$100,000 each for the general election. He wants $20 million from
that effort. Another $20 million is supposed to come from 30
traditional fund-raising dinners that Dukakis will attend around
the country. And $10 million is sought through smaller mail-in
donations.
   The law says only that $8.3 million of the total can be used
directly for Dukakis. The rest of his ``hard money'' is $46 million
in federal financing. The vast bulk of the cash that Farmer is
seeking is ``soft money,'' earmarked for general party-building
activities in each state.
   Party officials said Monday they already had collected $12
million toward their goal.
   While the Democrats like to stress their reliance on small
donations, the focus this week is on the big-ticket givers. The
poshest parties include one held by Atlanta developer John Portman,
and another honoring former President Carter is being hosted by
longtime fund-raiser Walter Shorenstein of San Francisco.
   At each event, lavish or not, is the ever-attentive Bob Farmer.
He even got in a plug at the biggest gathering of all, the
convention itself.
   ``If you'll excuse me now,'' he told the delegates after a short
speech Monday night, ``I have a few fund-raising calls to make for
Gov. Dukakis.''
</TEXT>
