<2ND_LINE>PM-Runaway Car,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families Of Children Victims Urge Leniency For Elderly Driver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The families of three children killed
when an elderly man's car careened onto a sidewalk have persuaded
authorities not to prosecute the man.
   But Stanley Dlugolenski will have to give up his car and
driver's license in the interest of public safety, said Kent County
Prosecutor William Forsyth.
   Dlugolenski, 79, told police he lost control of his car when the
brakes failed, but authorities concluded last week the Cadillac
involved in the July 8 accident didn't have any mechanical defect.
   The decision not to prosecute was heavily influenced by the
victims' families, who are Dlugolenski's neighbors, Forsyth said.
   ``It's unusual for a family to feel this way, and it's a factor
we had to give a lot of weight to,'' Forsyth said.
   Jody Murray, mother of 1{-year-old R.J. Murray, who was killed
in the crash, said she believes Dlugolenski ``did everything in his
power to avoid (the accident).''
   The other two children killed in the crash were Jason Northrup,
9, and his sister, Marlene, 7. The three were struck as they played
on the sidewalk in front of their homes.
   ``He feels horrible about what happened,'' Forsyth said. ``I'm
sure he'd love to undo what happened.''
   Dlugolenski has had three prior accidents and told authorities
his accelerator stuck in at least one of those accidents, Forsyth
said.
