<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewspaperCarrier     07-19 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspaper Carrier,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Carrier Helps Save Elderly Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old newspaper carrier may have
saved a 94-year-old woman's life when he noticed that she was not
collecting her newspapers, police said.
   David Wallace alerted his supervisors at the Beacon Journal on
Sunday after he noticed the woman had not picked up her morning
newspaper for two days. They called police after getting no answer
at the woman's apartment door.
   Officer Ron Deger said police broke into the apartment and found
the woman lying in her bed, unconscious but breathing.
   The unidentified woman was taken to Akron General Medical
Center, where doctors said Monday that she had made tremendous
recovery, going from critical to fair condition.
   Wallace said he has worked the paper route for eight months and
knew it was unusual that the woman had not picked up her papers
right away.
   He said at first he thought she might be on vacation, but said
his customers usually notify him if they are going to be away.
   ``She seems like a nice lady,'' said Wallace. ``I didn't have
that much contact with her because she paid by mail, but she's
always friendly when I see her and even gave me a bonus last
Christmas.''
