<HEAD>Judge: Elvis Buddy Can't Sell Home Movies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former member of Elvis Presley's
entourage cannot sell his home movies of the king of rock 'n' roll,
a judge says.
   Joe Esposito, a personal aide to Presley, wants to sell copies
of the movies, but managers of the dead singer's estate say they
have the sole rights to market his name and image.
   Chancellor Neal Small, granting a request from the estate,
issued a temporary injunction Monday directing Esposito not to sell
the movies until a lawsuit over the dispute is settled.
   The movies reportedly include shots of Presley, relatives and
friends at Graceland, where Presley died in 1977.
   Graceland, one of Memphis' largest tourist attractions, is
managed by the Presley estate for the financial benefit of the
singer's only child, Lisa Marie.
   No trial for the lawsuit was scheduled.
