<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0552,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Say First Interstate Blaze Helped Battle Latest Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with 3 grafs on cause, damage estimate, picks up graf
2, ``Two of the''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that damaged two floors of a 38-story
downtown bank tower was caused by vapors from a furniture
refinishing project, officials said today.
   The blaze started Monday night on the 34th floor of the Union
Bank tower and spread to the 35th, said Fire Department spokesman
Jim Wells. He estimated the damage at $350,000. It forced the
evacuation of two dozen workers but was quickly extinguished.
   ``It was accidental,'' said Wells. ``Chemical vapors made
contact with an electrical outlet,'' causing a flash fire.
   Two of the 150 firefighters who responded Monday night were
treated by paramedics at the scene for exhaustion and heat
exposure, but there were no other injuries.
   Firefighters responding to the Union Bank fire used lessons
learned in a May 4 high-rise fire, which killed one person and
injured 40 people as it tore through five floors of the 62-story
First Interstate Bank tower.
   Firefighters used advanced communications gear and left
equipment at two staging areas inside the building instead of the
one used during the previous blaze.
   They also lugged hoses and other equipment weighing as much as
100 pounds per person up the 34 flights of stairs until it was
determined the elevators could be used safely, said fire Battalion
Chief Bob DeFeo.
   The fire, extinquished in 43 minutes, was contained to a pair of
office suites on both the 34th and 35th floors, he said. Smoke
damage in other areas of the floors was minor, said fire Inspector
Ed Reed.
   The cause of the fire was undetermined, and officials said they
had not determined the dollar value of the damage.
   Michael Turner was doing legal research on the 35th floor of the
building when the fire alarm went off Monday night. He said he
immediately alerted a co-worker.
   ``We looked out one of the windows and saw flames coming up, and
we got the heck out of there,'' he said.
   ``I was jumping three steps at a time,'' said Bradley Franks,
who was among about 20 asbestos removal workers on the 28th floor
when he heard an evacuation call on an intercom. ``A few people
were following and some stumbled and fell. I was on the 16th floor
when I saw firefighters coming up the stairs.''
   Like the First Interstate Bank tower, the Union Bank tower was
not equipped with sprinklers, officials said, although they were
being installed. Both buildings were built before a 1974 city
ordinance required sprinklers in high-rises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
