<2ND_LINE>PM-Navajo Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0561,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution, Defense Offer Opening Statements in Navajo Murder
Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS third graf to CORRECT that Atenes are half-brothers, not
cousins</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL ERTELT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have yet to solve the
slayings of two Navajo policemen who were shot, doused in gasoline
and set on fire, a defense attorney argued as the federal trial of
four tribesmen opened.
   ``If you think it's all going to be tidied up and you're going
to know what went on _ you're not, because they arrested the wrong
men,'' Walter Bugden, attorney for Marques Atene, said in his
opening statement Monday.
   Atene, 22; his half-brother Ben Atene Jr., 24; Vinton Bedoni,
31; and Thomas Cly, 22, are charged with first-degree murder in the
deaths of officers Andy Begay and Roy Lee Stanley, whose charred
bodies were found Dec. 5 in a burned-out police truck in a remote
canyon in southern Utah.
   In his opening statement, Assistant U.S. Attorney Stewart C.
Walz said the killings occurred after the officers arrived the
night of Dec. 4 at a party and bonfire near Gouldings following a
high school basketball game.
   A month earlier, Stanley arrested Cly, who threatened him in
front of a witness, Walz said.
   Walz said the two officers were beaten and shot in the back,
then were taken in their police trucks to Copper Canyon southeast
of Lake Powell. They were placed in one of the trucks, which was
doused with gasoline and set on fire.
   Walz said prosecution witnesses would testify that Cly and
Bedoni got into a fight with Stanley at the party, subdued him and
took him behind his truck, where he was shot.
   Walz said Bedoni was seen after that shooting with a gun hin his
hand, and was seen pointing a gun at Begay, who had been summoned
to the scene.
   All four defense attorneys maintained their clients were not at
the crime scene, and said prosecution witnesses' reliability would
be an issue.
   The trial is being held in federal court because the killing
occurred on an Indian reservation.
</TEXT>
