<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Peru-Strike     07-19 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Strike,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Strike Against Price Increases; Railroad Tracks Blown Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters bombed railroad tracks and halted a
train carrying 1,200 workers to jobs today, Lima police said, as a
communist-led labor federation began a two-day national strike
against government economic policy.
   Strikers in the capital blocked key highways with burning
garbage and leftist guerrillas sparked a blackout in the highlands,
but there were no early reports of violent clashes between police
and strikers, officials said.
   Police said a train carrying workers to their jobs in Lima from
Chosica, 25 miles to the east, was halted midway when saboteurs
blew up a small section of track. The train stopped before reaching
the damaged track and there were no injuries.
   The 48-hour strike was called by the General Confederation of
Peruvian Workers to protest government-approved increases of
between 20 and 100 percent for food prices. They also protested
rising inflation, expected to hit 400 percent this year.
   The organization, which claims more than 1.5 million members,
said two-thirds of the nation's seven million workers were joining
the two-day walkout.
   The strike, the third against President Alan Garcia, was
declared illegal by the government. Dozens of armed police were
deployed on transit buses to ensure that workers reach their jobs.
   Traffic in Lima flowed smoothly but was lighter than normal with
fewer buses on the streets.
   A spokesman at the capital's international airport said flights
were normal.
   Maoist guerrillas blew up power pylons and caused a blackout in
Ayacucho, 225 miles southeast of Lima, as the strike there
paralyzed most business activity, police said.
   Radio Programas, Peru's leading news station, reported the
strike slowed commercial activity in the provincial capitals of
Huancayo, Arequipa, Puno and Cuzco.
   There were no serious reports of violence in Lima early today,
but reporters said police fired tear gas to drive off small pockets
of protesters who attempted to block key arteries into the capital
with burning garbage.
   The nation's largest mine workers federation began an indefinite
strike Monday, which has slowed or halted most mine operations
across the country, strike officials said.
   It was still unclear in the capital today how effective the
strike was in closing factories and halting economic activity.
   On Monday, police said leftist guerrillas exploded a car bomb in
front of the military's joint command headquarters in Lima,
wounding three people.
   Police said a student protester was shot dead during a
demonstration at Lima's San Marcos University medical school Monday
but circumstances surrounding the death were unclear.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
