<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--KoreanAuthors     07-19 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Korean Authors,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Publication of Pro-North Korean Writers' Books Permitted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday lifted a
decades-old ban on the publication of literary works by about 120
South Korean writers who defected to North Korea during the Korean
War, government officials said.
   Officials at the Culture-Information Ministry said the action
was in line with South Korea's continuing efforts to reconcile with
North Korea and promote contact between the two Koreas.
   The literary works were written before the authors defected, but
South Korea had banned their publication under its anti-North Korea
policy.
   The government action left only five writers on the blacklist,
including Paek In-jun, a former South Korean film scriptwriter who
currently serves as head of North Korea's Literary Arts League, the
officials said.
   In April, the government permitted publication of books by two
prominent South Korean poets who switched loyalty to North Korea
during the 1950-53 war.
