<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0562 07-19 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0562,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Touts Civil Rights Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 7 grafs with Bentsen comments, picking up 2nd
graf pvs, ``I can; deleting grafs 8-9 pvs, Bentsen a; trims at end.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, seen by some as a
conservative counterpoint to Michael Dukakis, played up his civil
rights record today, saying ``no one can doubt'' his commitment to
that cause.
   On a day that began with a salute to the civil rights movement,
Bentsen praised Jesse Jackson, saying he ``has acted more on his
own for the cause of freedom and justice, more than the Reagan
administration has been able to achieve in the last eight years.''
   Bentsen continued to brush aside any differences between him and
the Democratic presidential nominee-to-be, stressing their common
views on such issues as civil rights.
   ``No one can doubt Michael Dukakis' commitment to civil rights;
no one can doubt my commitment,'' Bentsen told a civil rights
breakfast hosted by House Speaker Jim Wright.
   Later, he told Texas delegates that the convention is showing
unprecedented Democratic Party unity.
   ``As I visited with Jesse Jackson this morning, as I talked to
Mike Dukakis time and time again yesterday and I listened to
(keynote speaker) Ann Richards last night, I have never, never seen
this Democratic Party more united than it is now,'' Bentsen said.
   In a series of television interviews earlier today, Bentsen
emphasized his civil rights credentials.
   ``I can say I've been fighting for civil rights as far back as
the `40s,'' Bentsen said on NBC-TV. ``I'm no latecomer to that
process. ... I wouldn't be sitting here today as Michael Dukakis'
running mate if I didn't have a civil rights record.''
   The Texas senator's record on some issues is at odds with stands
now advocated by Dukakis, including aid to insurgents in Nicaragua
and support for the tax cuts advanced by President Reagan in 1981.
On ABC-TV, Bentsen acknowledged differences but added, ``There are
a lot more similarities than you have in the way of differences.''
   On the major theme of the Democratic campaign, he said, he and
Dukakis are together. ``We are talking about economic growth, jobs,
education, health care, housing.''
   Bentsen spent a good part of Monday wooing delegates who don't
know him or his record. Some found their fears about him
evaporating.
   ``He doesn't frighten me,'' said Harry Meshel, minority leader
of the Ohio Senate. ``You don't expect him to be a loose cannon.
That's the kind of thing you're looking for: stability.''
   ``He's smooth, like pouring honey, and I mean that in a
complimentary way. If he walked on water, he wouldn't stir it,''
said Richard Daschbach, a New Hampshire legislator.
   Some delegates made no secret of their disappointment in
Dukakis' choice for a running mate. Jackson supporters threatened
to challenge Bentsen, but such talk may have been muted by the
outcome of Monday's Dukakis-Jackson meeting, which ended with
pledges of unity.
   Aides say Bentsen did not take part in the talks between Dukakis
and Jackson, although he did have two candid telephone
conversations with Jackson last week that aides say enabled Jackson
and Bentsen to establish a good rapport. Jackson told Bentsen after
one call that ``you understand grits talk,'' said Bentsen spokesman
Jack Devore.
   Bentsen arrived in time fr the trio to hold a press conference
Monday. Afterward, he told a meeting of Ohio delegates ``I just
left a meeting with Gov. Dukakis and Jesse Jackson and we have put
it all together.''
   He was well received by the Ohio crowd, despite their hopes that
Ohio Sen. John Glenn would get the nod for the ticket's No. 2 spot.
   Meshel, the Ohio Senate leader, called the choice ``very
practical.''
   ``When you analyzed the political landscape, it seemed more
important to have Bentsen in terms of winning Texas than it was to
have Glenn ... because I think we're strong in Ohio and the
Midwest,'' said Meshel.
   At the New Jersey delegation, Bentsen was greeted by an ovation
but also some Jackson placards. The Jackson supporters said later
they were still committed to their candidate, but that Bentsen
should not take it personally.
   Wayne Bryant, a New Jersey assemblyman from Camden, said he
remained concerned about what role Jackson will have in the
campaign, but called Bentsen's civil rights record ``very
distinguished.''
</TEXT>
