<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GolfingLeave 1stLd-Writethru a0572 07-19 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Golfing Leave, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0572,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Seeks Sick Leave For Jaunt On Green</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to include name of school where she worked.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public school teacher was only doing what the
doctor ordered when she took a day off and played golf, a review
panel decided in granting her request for sick pay.
   ``We find it unbelievable,'' said school district attorney Jose
Gonzalez, who last week filed a request for a rehearing in Superior
Court.
   The three-member review panel, known as the Commission on
Professional Competence, ruled last month that teacher Ethel H.
Williams could file for sick leave for her June 12, 1987, golf
outing.
   The panel said the outing was ``related to the respondent's
health.'' It found that Williams was under an unusual amount of
job-related stress while working as a special education elementary
school teacher at Walker Elementary School.
   Williams, who has been teaching for 17 years, had been advised
by her physician to take a day off when she was bothered by stress.
Her physician thinks golf ``serves this mental health purpose
well,'' the ruling said.
   The matter went to the panel after school officials received a
tip about the golf outing. Williams denied going until confronted
with her score card.
   The district sought to have her suspended for 10 days for
unprofessional conduct for abusing the sick leave policy and for
denying she had spent the day playing golf.
   ``We didn't feel that going out and playing golf is adequate
medical therapy,'' said George Flanigan, the district's director of
certificated personnel.
   The panel's ruling notes that Williams has been evaluated as ``a
very effective teacher.'' It also says she has a handicap of 12.
</TEXT>
