<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 1stld-Writethru a0489 07-19 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st ld-Writethru, a0489,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Mark Ninth Anniversary of Revolution Triumph</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs on Ortega's speech. Picks up x graf pvs
``The anniversary....''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega, speaking at
the ninth anniversary of his leftist government, said today that
Nicaragua has been socialist since 1979.
   ``There were expectations on this July 19 that we were going to
declare outselves socialists,'' the president, wearing a plaid
cowboy shirt, said in the nationally broadcast speech. ``They
haven't understood yet that we are socialists, and there's
socialism in Nicaragua since 1979.''
   It was believed to be the first time that he or any of the
Sandininista leaders described themselves as socialists. Recently
Sandinista leaders have said that the country had a mixed economy
with socialist orientation.
   Ortega spoke to a crowded stadium in the central city of
Juigalpa, 85 miles east of the capital.
   He also urged the United States to renew bilateral talks, last
held in 1984, to normalize relations.
   The president called on the U.S.-backed rebels, known as
Contras, to reopen stalled discussions on a definitive cease-fire.
He also said government troops would extend a truce until Aug. 30.
The current cease-fire was due to expire at the end of this month.
   The anniversary marks the day Sandinista guerrillas arrived
triumphantly in Managua, the capital, after a 1{-year civil war
that ended four decades of dictatorial rule by the Somoza dynasty.
   Troops on Monday conducted searches at roadblocks along the road
to the site of the festivities in Juigalpa, 85 miles east of
Managua. Also, the Interior Ministry banned alcohol sales for 24
hours in Chontales province, where anniversary festivities also are
being held.
   The measures followed three days of military exercises that
ended Sunday. The armed forces, using tanks, helicopters and guns,
joined civilians to act out air strikes and land attacks.
   Also Sunday, thousands of youths attended dances to celebrate
the ``Day of Happiness,'' marking the day in 1979 when President
Anastasio Somoza left the country.
   The celebrations come as a quick and permanent end to the
government's 7-year war with the Contras remains elusive.
   Negotiations broke down in June for a lasting peace to the
conflict that has claimed 26,000 lives. The rebels in recent weeks
have staged almost daily ambushes despite a cease-fire agreement
signed March 23.
   The Defense Ministry said Monday five rebels had been killed in
two attacks on troop positions. The statement said rebels kidnapped
10 civilians Friday and Saturday.
   The government last week expelled U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton
and seven other American diplomats. It accused the U.S. Embassy of
being behind a plan to incite domestic unrest.
   Also last week, courts sentenced to six months in jail three
dozen opposition figures who attended an anti-government
demonstration that police broke up with tear gas and beatings.
   The Sandinistas also shut down the Roman Catholic radio station
and a private news show and suspended the only opposition
newspaper, La Prensa, for 15 days. Citing economic reasons, the
government nationalized the largest private enterprise, the San
Antonio sugar refinery.
   Lawmakers in Washington are discussing resuming military aid to
the Contras, which Congress cut off in February in hopes the
Sandinistas would deliver on promises of democratic reforms.
   The government claims most of Nicaragua's problems center on the
war with the Contras, which it says has caused $3.6 billion in
damage to the economy.
   The threat of renewed fighting means thousands of displaced
people cannot return home in north and central regions. Meanwhile,
the unpopular military draft continues.
   The war has stifled promises of social programs. Scores of
schools and clinics built after 1979 have been destroyed. The
country's more than 3 million people suffer shortages of rice,
beans, water and gasoline.
   Most of the blame has been placed on the United States, which
financed the Contras, cut off economic aid in 1981 and established
a trade embargo in 1985.
   But the Sandinistas express pride in having survived to their
ninth anniversary without the U.S. invasion they have always said
they expect.
   On Monday, a cartoon in the Sandinista newspaper Barricada
depicted a baseball game, the nation's most popular sport, between
the United States and Nicaragua. It showed a score board noting 9-0
and a disheveled Uncle Sam.
</TEXT>
