<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     07-19 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiites And Catholics Clash In North Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maronite Catholics in north Lebanon on
Tuesday repulsed fierce attacks on their town by Shiite Moslem
gunmen, and police said five people were killed and 25 wounded in
the fighting.
   The attacks raised the casualty toll to 11 dead and 45 wounded
since fighting began Sunday between the Shiite Jaafar clan and
residents of the Catholic town of Qoubaiyat, 70 miles northeast of
Beirut.
   A police spokesman in Tripoli, the provincial capital of north
Lebanon, said residents of Qoubaiyat repulsed three attacks Tuesday
by 2,000 Jaafars before a cease-fire was called.
   He said the Jaafars launched the attacks with a fierce barrage
from rocket launchers, howitzers and mortars. The shells slammed
into Qoubaiyat at the intensity of 10 rounds per minute at one
point, the spokesman said.
   He said several mortar rounds fell into the courtyard of
Qoubaiyat's ancient stone church, causing some damage. But the six
monks and 20 nuns sheltered there were not hurt.
   The Jaafar clan, estimated at 35,000 people, is based in the
central Bekaa Valley on the western edge of the Akkar plateau, a
region traditionally dominated by Maronite Catholics and Sunni
Moslems.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 25,000 troops
in the Bekaa Valley and north Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the 21-nation Arab League.
   The spokesman, who requested anonymity, said Brig. Gen. Ghazi
Kenaan, chief of the Syrian army's military intelligence in
Lebanon, drove to Qoubaiyat shortly after midday to supervise
implementation of the cease-fire.
   The Syrian army is to control ``a buffer zone separating
Qoubaiyat's fighters from the Jaafars,'' the spokesman said.
   He said the clashes started Sunday, one day after armed
shepherds from Qoubaiyat and the Jaafars engaged in a brief
firefight over sheep grazing terrain in the hamlet of Shanbook, on
the town's western edge.
   ``Two people were killed in the original fight for pastures. But
it seems the incident has developed into a Shiite-Maronite war,''
the spokesman added.
   Tuesday's attack on Qoubaiyat shattered a Syrian-sponsored
cease-fire declared on Monday.
   Qoubaiyat, population 25,000, is the fourth largest Catholic
town in north Lebanon. About one-fourth of Qoubaiyat's residents
serve in the Lebanese army.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
