<DOCNO> AP880719-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--ForeignMedia     07-19 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Foreign Media,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3,000 Foreign Reporters Cover the Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People the world around are following events at
the Democratic National Convention here, but their interest level
often is tied directly to their distance from Atlanta.
   ``We're watching from afar, figuratively and literally,'' says
Francois Champey, a reporter covering the convention for the French
television station La Cinq.
   Allan Hogan, of the Australian Broadcasting Company, says his
countrymen are interested but not intensely so. ``We're just
concentrating on the highlights, things like the platform and the
Jackson-Dukakas fracas,'' he says.
   On the other hand, the Mexican and Canadian reporters at the
convention are giving their readers a blow-by-blow account. They
say the folks back home are especially eager to know what positions
the Democrats will take on issues such as acid rain, trade barriers
and funding for the Contras in Nicaragua.
   ``The Democratic platform hints of being very protectionist on
trade issues, which could hit us hard,'' says Jose Carreno, a
Washington-based correspondent for the Mexican News Agency.
   Carreno says he thinks most Mexicans would rather see a Democrat
become president this time around.
   ``If the Republicans win, it probably will mean political
problems for us,'' he says. ``If the Democrats win, it may mean
economic problems but nonetheless, the Mexican people, for one
reason or another, tend to think the Democrats are better for
Mexico. Then, too, most Mexican Americans lean toward the
Democratic Party.''
   Christopher Thomas and Michael Finley of the Canadian
Broadcasting Corporation also say they think the Canadian people
want to see a Democrat in the White House next year.
   ``People in Canada think it's time for a change, says the
Toronto-based Finley. ``There's an intense interest in this
convention and in how the election works out in the fall; we'll be
covering it all the way.''
   The Democratic National Committee estimates as many as 3,000
foreign reporters are covering the convention. They say 319 foreign
news organizations from 51 countries have registered to attend the
big show at the Omni.
   Many of these reporters are especially interested in Jesse
Jackson, whom Carreno calls ``easily the best-known American
politican in the world, after Ronald Reagan.''
   John Magnus of VG, Norway's largest newspaper, says he has
interviewed members of the Minnesota, many of whom are of Norwegian
descent. But he says his readers also are very interested in
Jackson's convention activities.
   ``Norwegians like the fact that he speaks about racism and
challenges the establishment,'' says Magnus. ``Also, Jackson's
social programs reflect the thinking of many people in our country.
He'd be a mainstream politician in Norway.''
   No so in Taiwan, says Norman Fu of the China Times.
   ``I've been focusing on Gov. Michael Dukakis and whether he will
be able to win,'' says Fu. ``This convention is a big story in our
country because it touches foreign policy and the Reagan
administration, which has been a good friend to us.''
   For Ingo Pressler of the East German wire service ADN, a big
problem has been explaining the convention process to his readers.
   ``I'm describing the debates and touching on the issues,'' he
says. ``But frankly it's hard for our people, as it is for many
Americans, to see a real difference in your political parties.''
   Many of the foreign journalists file their stories at the U.S.
Information Agency foreign press center. They complain of being
stuck in motels far from The Omni and of the lack of access to the
convention's leading figures, who are dominated by the domestic
media.
   For Lily Chaves of the daily newspaper Excelsior in Mexico City,
major problems have been the language barrier and grasping the U.S.
nomination process.
   ``I've been concentrating on the Hispanic caucus,'' she says,
speaking in halting English.``This is my first American convention
and it's so different from Mexico, where the same party has been in
power for 59 years and everyone thinks the presidential election is
just for show.''
</TEXT>
