<DOCNO> AP880719-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--OnTheFringe Bjt   07-19 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--On The Fringe, Bjt,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outside the Convention: Filtering Out All That BS (Blue Smoke)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Butler is due in court Wednesday morning
back home in Stuart, Fla., but he thought it important that he be
here to peddle his unique product at the Democratic National
Convention.
   The product, to put it delicately, is a filter to keep ``from
being choked to death by verbal and visual pollution.'' Its name
has two initials that could stand for Beneath Sanity, but they
don't.
   Butler could be found on Day Two of the convention hawking his
product in a block-long parking lot near the convention hall set
aside for speech-making. A sort of Atlanta Hyde Park.
   ``This convention is all Beneath Sanity,'' said Butler, a
lawyer. He used the initials, but this way it gets cleaned up.
   His filter wasn't needed right at that moment. The speaker at
the mike was addressing an audience of 17, outnumbered better than
two-to-one by 40 portable johns and more than evenly matched by
more than two dozen bored, hot, riot police.
   Butler is an oddity among the 35,000 people attracted to Atlanta
for the convention because he doesn't want to get into The Omni,
which he regards as a megasource for Blue Smoke, which is also not
the words he used.
   ``I'm trying to avoid it,'' he said. ``My filters would stop me
at the door.''
   The filters, according to the instructions, work best when
placed between the user and the source of the pollution. Its uses
include filtering out ``politicians saying they are for the common
man'' and ``lawyers asking you to trust them.''
   Ten bucks, but free to reporters looking for Bully Stories.
   While Butler was touting his product, a mock trial was being
held for House Speaker Jim Wright on the city-provided podium.
   ``Repeatedly, Jim Wright disobeyed the law,'' said Lisa
Williams, a student at the University of Georgia. ``The facts speak
for themselves and they make a liar out of Jim Wright.''
   Her reasoning is that Wright, who is chairman of the convention,
took foreign policy in his hands by negotiating with Central
American leaders to advance his own peace plan and violated
campaign finance law by having associates buy his autobiography.
   A young man named James Bieber stepped forward. ``I represent
Jim Wright and the evidence is so overwhelming, my client pleads
guilty and we throw outselves on the mercy of the court.'' Bieber,
from Costa Mesa, Calif., is Orange County chairman of the
right-wing Young Americans for Freedom.
   He came to Atlanta, he said, because ``the streets are full of
red flags and communists.''
   The trial ended with the ``judge'', Eugene Delgadio, shouting
into the microphone: ``I ask for Jim Wright to come forward. I seek
any delegate within the sound of my voice to come forward and
defend Jim Wright.''
   Nobody came. ``It's a crying shame,'' said Delgadio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
