<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--RepublicanVersion     07-19 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Republican Version,440</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>GOP Squad Sees Democrats ``in the Twilight Zone'' with Platform
^By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic platform is a gloomy document that
doesn't acknowledge there are ``good times in America,'' Republican
critics charged Tuesday.
   ``Last night I listened (to the speeches) and I also read the
Democratic platform. Frankly, I don't know what country they're
talking about,'' said James Miller, head of the Reagan
administration's Office of Management and Budget. ``It seems to me
they're either deceiving the American people or they're in the
Twilight Zone somewhere.''
   ``The Democratic Party is pulling together to help perpetuate
the fraud,'' said South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell.
   ``That's the traditional philosophy,'' said New Hampshire Gov.
John Sununu. ``It is the tax and spend wing that is in control.
They have written a platform that attempts to hide that.''
   On the day the convention took up the platform, a GOP ``truth
squad'' took aim at the document, arguing that it demonstrates that
certain nominee Michael Dukakis is cast in the traditional liberal
mold.
   ``They can hide from the `L' word all they want,'' Campbell
said. ``It's a fact of life. There is a fraud being perpetuated on
the American public.''
   Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., said Republicans must make it clear
that Dukakis is cut from the liberal mold, despite his efforts to
dodge the label.
   ``His history has been a history of public service that involves
tax and spend,'' Lewis said. ``The Democratic Party intends to be a
party without principle practicing the politics of deception.''
   Miller argued that while Democrats are trying to soft-pedal the
question of tax increases, they would be inevitable in a Democratic
administration.
   ``I know you can't do all those things the Democrats here in
Atlanta are talking about without raising taxes,'' Miller said. ``I
think somebody ought to make that point and I think the Democrats
ought to be held accountable for it.''
   Rep. Don Sundquist, R-Tenn., attacked House Speaker Jim Wright,
who chairs the Democratic convention and is under investigation for
allegations involving a book written by a staffer.
   ``I think it's devastating to have Jim Wright on the platform,''
Sundquist said. ``I think if they had any way to get him off the
platform without embarrassing him they would.''
   The GOP squad tried to turn the selection of conservative Texas
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen for the No. 2 spot on the ticket to Republican
advantage, suggesting there's a philosophical split and remembering
earlier Bentsen criticisms of ``ultraliberals.''
</TEXT>
