<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Bermudez     07-19 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Bermudez,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Contra Director Seen In Nicaragua As No. 1 Mercenary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Contra Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enrique Bermudez, newly elected to the
rebels' directorate, is portrayed here as the man personally
responsible for murdering civilians and the epitome of President
Reagan's anti-Sandinista policies.
   Leftist government publications constantly refer to the
56-year-old former colonel's position in Anastasio Somoza's
national guard to evoke the memories of an often brutal
dictatorship deposed by the Sandinistas nine years ago.
   ``Somozista Guard Controls The Directorate,'' read a headline
Tuesday in the Sandinista newspaper Barricada. ``The United States
Believes In A New Somoza,'' said El Nuevo Diario, also
pro-government.
   State-run television showed pictures of Bermudez in his uniform
during the 1978-79 revolutionary war combined with shots of bodies
of burned babies.
   He is described in Nicaragua as a CIA pawn and the head of the
mercenaries, as the Sandinistas call the rebels. The rebels, or
Contras, have been backed by the United States since they began
fighting the government in 1981.
   Recent Defense Ministry bulletins reporting military actions by
the Contras begin: ``Mercenary groups loyal to the Somozista
ex-colonel...''
   Bermudez, the military chief of the Contras, was elected Monday
to the political directorate of the exile Nicaraguan Resistance
Assembly which was meeting in the Dominican Republic. The election
marked the first time the rebel combatants have had direct
representation on the political directorate.
   Bermudez was one of the founders of the first rebel groups in
1981 and then of the Nicaraguan Democratic Force, the largest
Contra fighting force, whose core is disgruntled former guardsmen.
   He is known among his followers as Commander 380, a reference to
his number at military school. He graduated in 1952. Bermudez also
studied military engineering in Brazil and spent time at the School
of the Americas in Panama.
   The former colonel took part in the U.S. actions against the
Dominican Republic in 1965. From 1976 until the Sandinistas came to
power in 1979 he served as Somoza's military attache in Washington.
   The Nicaraguan Democratic Force joined with southern front
groups and Atlantic Coast Indian rebels in 1985 under the name the
United Nicaraguan Opposition and was known by its Spanish acronyn
as UNO, which means one. But the varied Contra groups never were
seen as united.
   The only thing they have agreed on is that the Sandinistas, whom
they view as hardened Marxists, must be ousted.
   The Contras reorganized again in 1987 as the Nicaraguan
Resistance.
   Representatives of that group, made up of politicians, most of
whom live in Miami, signed the March 23 cease-fire agreement with
the Sandinistas after three days of meetings at the southern border
post at Sapoa.
   The Contras in recent weeks have staged scores of attacks in
violation of the cease-fire. The leadership claims that the actions
are by individuals acting on their own. The rebel ranks suffer deep
splits.
   In May a group of seven Contra field commanders were expelled
from Honduras to the United States for speaking out against
Bermudez.
   Contra leaders, who remain loyal to Bermudez, told The
Associated Press that Pedro Joaquin Chamorro would lose his
position on the directorate because he backed the young officers
against Bermudez.
   Chamorro was voted off the board Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880719-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--JustTheFacts     07-19 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Just The Facts,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Figuring Out Facts Just Part of Convention Fun, Ma'am</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Atlanta Chamber of Commerce believes
Democrats _ and media representatives _ are rather voracious
consumers, it seems.
   The group predicted the Democratic National Convention would
produce $60 million for the local economy _ half of it in direct
spending by visitors, and another $30 million in rollover spending
by local businesses and employees.
   The chamber figures, for example, that each of the 35,000
visitors estimated to be here for the political gathering will eat
and drink his or her way through $300 over five days, and spend $86
a piece at retail stores _ not counting T-shirts purchased on the
street.
   Democrats are doubling up in hotel rooms, the chamber says. A
figure of 17,200 rooms was used in the calculations, at more than
$100 a night each.
   All told, Atlanta is counting on $857 from each of the 35,000
people.
   So are the estimates coming true? Convention organizers aren't
saying. The hotel reservations office says it can't release the
number of rooms actually in use.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Mavis Jackson has been answering 15 to 20 questions an hour
during the convention, and she isn't even a politician.
   Ms. Jackson is a librarian for the Atlanta-Fulton Public
Library, which set up a Fast Facts Information Center in the World
Congress Center adjacent to the Omni.
   The queries have come from all corners _ reporters, delegates,
even protestors. What was the text of the 1984 party platform? Who
nominated Jimmy Carter in 1976? What was the wording of the U.S.
Supreme Court opinion on sodomy? How many registered voters have
there been for each election since 1964?
   Even: What shows did Michael Dukakis' actor son John have a part
in? (``Little House on the Prairie'' and ``Jaws II.'')
   ``Whatever is going on each day _ that's what the questions seem
to focus on,'' Ms. Jackson said.
   What's been the most frequent question from delegates?
   ``How do I get to my party?'' she said.
</TEXT>
