<DOCNO> AP880719-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HurricanePlanes     07-19 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Planes,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forecasters Worried By Plan to Cut Hurricane Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force proposal to end hurricane
reconnaissance flights as part of a belt-tightening plan would
strip coastal areas of their most reliable early-warning storm
defense, forecasters said.
   Air Force officials have decided to eliminate the WC-130 flights
that complement weather satellites and land-based radar used to
track storms in the Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico, said Rep. Tom
Lewis, R-Fla.
   ``We feel strongly that the aircraft reconnaissance is important
to us,'' Mark Zimmer, chief of the Tropical Satellite Analysis
Center at the National Hurricane Center, said Monday. ``When you
get down to warning the coastal population, we feel that we need
the precise information of the aircraft.''
   Weather satellites provide a broad picture, Zimmer said. ``But
when we get down to actually trying to measure the wind velocity
and the pressure, we feel that the aircraft can best do that.''
   The proposal to end the reconnaissance flights would take effect
Oct. 1, 1989, just after the height of next year's Atlantic
Hurricane Season.
   It would save about $25 million a year, said Lt. Col. John Olsen
of the Military Airlift Command headquarters at Scott Air Force
Base in Illinois.
   Tracing hurricanes ``can be done other ways cheaper and
faster,'' added Air Force spokesman Capt. Mike Laughlin in
Washington, who said tests with new technology in the Pacific _
where the flights have already been eliminated _ were successful.
   He also said sending a plane and crew into the eye of a
hurricane was dangerous.
   But Lewis disagrees that the flights can be eliminated.
   ``This is ill-advised and, if carried out, would literally leave
Florida naked and defenseless in the path of a fast-moving killer
hurricane,'' Lewis said.
   Lewis said he has talked to Air Force Secretary Edward C.
Aldridge and hopes to meet with him soon.
   If he cannot dissaude Aldridge, Lewis said he hopes to unite the
Florida congressional delegation _ along with legislators from
states along the Gulf Coast _ against the cut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
