<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LesbianSoldier     07-19 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lesbian Soldier,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ben-Shalom Asks Judge To Assist Her Re-Enlistment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a year after she won reinstatement, Army
Reserve Sgt. Miriam Ben-Shalom asked a federal judge Tuesday to
prohibit the Army from denying her re-enlistment because she is a
lesbian.
   ``I don't want to stand up waving a banner and screaming `I'm
gay.' All I want is to serve the country I love and to be a good
soldier,'' Ben-Shalom said after the court hearing.
   Ben-Shalom, 40, who won reinstatement last year after a federal
appeals court ruled that she could not be discharged for admitting
her homosexuality, said she was informed she will not be allowed to
re-enlist when her term expires Aug. 11.
   Her attorney, Patrick T. Berigan, asked U.S. District Judge
Myron L. Gordon for a temporary injunction preventing the Army from
considering her sexual preferences when deciding on her request to
re-enlist.
   He also sought a permanent injunction that would effectively end
the Army's ban on homosexuals.
   ``She has been denied solely because of her sexual preference
and if the Army is denied to consider that issue then I'm confident
she will be re-enlisted.... She is an outstanding soldier,''
Berigan told the court.
   Gordon said he would try to rule on the preliminary injunction
before Aug. 11 and then move quickly to consider the other motions.
   Berigan said he was appalle that Army Reserve regulations ban
admitted homosexuals from re-enlisting even if there is no proof _
as in this case _ that any homosexual acts were performed in the
service.
   ``Here is an individual who has received nothing but high
accolades from her superior. She gets along with everybody and her
homosexuality has not been a problem and I don't see any reason why
she shouldn't be allowed to re-enlist,'' Berigan said.
   Berigan cited a February ruling by the 9th Circuit Court of
Appeals which extended the Constitution's equal protection clause
to protect homosexuals from government discrimination.
   Kenneth Kohl, a U.S. Justice Department attorney representing
the Army, said the 9th Circuit case has been scheduled for
rehearing and that three other federal appeals courts have upheld
the Army's ban on homosexuality.
   He said courts have allowed the Army to arrest soldiers for
homosexual conduct and if ``they are allowed to arrest someone for
homosexual conduct then certainly they can deny someone a job
because they are homosexual.''
   Kohl said the Army believes homosexuals are not only a risk to
national security, but undermine discipline, morale and recruiting.
   Kohl asked Gordon to consider precedents in which courts have
decided against involving themselves in internal matters because
``they found the Army is better left to make its own decisions.''
   Ben-Shalom enlisted in the 84th Division of the Army Reserves in
1974 and was promoted to sergeant in 1976 before she was discharged
later that year after she told a superior she was a lesbian.
   She appealed her discharge and in 1980, U.S. District Judge
Terence T. Evans ruled she could not be discharged for admitting
her homosexuality.
   The decision was appealed and Ben-Shalom was prohibited from
finishing her three-year term until August 1987 when a federal
appeals court in Chicago upheld the lower court's ruling that she
was protected under the First Amendment.
   The appeals court ruling did not address the issue of
re-enlistment.
</TEXT>
