<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--DukakisDelegates     07-19 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dukakis Delegates,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Delegates Praise Accords with Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis' peace accords with Jesse
Jackson marked a fair conclusion of their political jockeying, and
Jackson now should yield to his party's nominee-elect, some Dukakis
delegates say.
   ``Jesse likes the center stage and that's fine,'' said Irving J.
Stolberg, speaker of the Connecticut House. ``At this point,
however, we're in the process of having Mike Dukakis become the
captain.''
   Stolberg, like several other Dukakis delegates interviewed about
the Dukakis-Jackson truce, expressed no resentment at Jackson's
demands for influence for his supporters within the campaign and
the Democratic Party.
   ``Everybody's doing what you would expect them to do _ posturing
for position,'' said state Sen. David Karem of Louisville, Ky.
   ``It's typical, what you'd expect of bargaining,'' said Edward
Smith, of Cairo, Ill.
   Some delegates said Jackson took advantage of Dukakis' failure
to notify him of his rejection as vice presidential running mate
last week, when Sen. Lloyd Bentsen was selected. But they did not
fault Jackson's approach.
   ``Tactically last week Dukakis gave Rev. Jackson an opportunity,
and we all seize our opportunities politically,'' said Edward
Treacy, a delegate from Indianapolis. ``When someone does something
that's not by the book, you seize the moment.''
   While the Dukakis gaffe gave Jackson ``something of an upper
hand,'' Treacy said, ``he has to remember who the nominee will be.''
   Dukakis and Jackson met Monday and emerged pledging cooperation.
Aides said Jackson's gains included about half of 25 new Democratic
National Committee seats, campaign jobs for Jackson's aides and
rules changes for 1992.
   The delegates expressed satisfaction with Dukakis' effort.
   ``He's not allowing himself to get jerked around. There's
definitely an attempt at it, but it's not successful,'' said Laurie
Donnelly of Louisville.
   ``There was a little bit of games-playing,'' said Carol Barr of
Decatur, Ill. ``I don't think it's going to hurt the fall
campaign.''
   Other Dukakis delegates were sympathetic to Jackson's purposes.
   ``Jesse had to make a point,'' said John B. Larson, Connecticut
Senate president pro tem.
   Barr said she was not bothered by Jackson's name being placed in
nomination Wednesday night; ``That's what he ran for.'' But she,
like other Dukakis delegates, also said the time was at hand for
Jackson to drop his candidacy and take up the Dukakis cause.
   ``Jesse, in the next couple of days, has his last moments of
negotiating the role he's going to play,'' said Stolberg, the
Connecticut House speaker. ``After that point, he's one of the
lieutenants in the Dukakis campaign, and I think he's going to be
an important one.''
</TEXT>
