<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WisconsinLobbying 1stLd-Writethru a0652 07-19 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wisconsin Lobbying, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lobbying Probe Hits Wisconsin's Clean Image</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, `Wisconsin hasn't...,' to CORRECT to
secretary of state sted attorney general.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wisconsin's squeaky-clean image has been
shaken by accusations that a top Madison lobbyist bought meals for
legislators and paid for travel in a possible violation of state
law.
   Some legislators and others say the the infractions are minor _
one of the meals cost $5 or $6 _ especially when compared to states
with a greater history of government scandal.
   But the state director of Common Cause, the self-styled citizen
lobbying group, said Wisconsin should judge itself by its own
standards, not by those of states where such infractions would
barely leave a ripple.
   By Wisconsin standards, he said, ``we've got some problems
here.''
   Wisconsin's lobbying law, believed to be tougher than most,
prohibits public officials from accepting anything of value from
lobbyists, except limited campaign contributions after June 1 of
election years. Common Cause is pushing for an even tougher law.
   Lobbyist Gary Goyke, a former state senator, filed lawsuits last
week in a so-far unsuccessful attempt to stop Milwaukee Magazine
from publishing an article about his lobbying practices that he
contends were based on office files taken by a former employee. The
article is to appear late this month in August editions.
   Goyke also asked for a state investigation into his activities,
predicting it would show he had violated no laws.
   The U.S. attorney's office disclosed it already was
investigating. And state Attorney General Don Hanaway said Tuesday
he would launch an investigation, after Secretary of State Douglas
La Follette announced he would drop his probe to avoid any
appearance of conflict of interest or political use in his bid for
the Democratic nomination for the U.S. Senate.
   Goyke contributed to La Follette's campaign for secretary of
state in 1986 and the two are acquiantances.
   ``It's like a witch hunt,'' said state Rep. David Travis, whose
name has not been linked to any questionable activity. ``We've all
been tarred and feathered already and there's not a heck of a lot
that's come out.''
   Goyke had a reputation as a clean politician when he was in the
state Senate, especially after waging a campaign against secrecy in
government.
   Kevin Millikin, a Madison lawyer, said he thought the incidents
didn't amount to much, ``It's friendships, a few nights in a hotel
room, a few drinks.''
   But Millikin said that means a lot in Wisconsin.
   ``The citizens expect a clean government,'' he said. ``It
certainly had the appearance of impropriety. If what you read is
true, people in Wisconsin aren't going to like it.''
   William E. Hauda, Wisconsin director of Common Cause, said the
incidents are serious for Wisconsin, whose reputation for honest
government dates to the turn-of-the-century Progressive movement.
   Wisconsin hasn't had a major government scandal this century,
since Gov. Robert M. ``Fighting Bob'' La Follette ended the
railroad lobby's stranglehold on the Legislature in 1903. The state
secretary of state says he is a distant relative of the former
governor.
   ``We're not quite as clean as people would like to have you
believe,'' Hauda said. ``You have to judge things based on
community standards, just like obscenity. Based on Wisconsin's
standards, we've got some problems here.''
   Hauda's group said Goyke's wife, attorney Nancy Rottier, gave
thousands of dollars to more than 30 legislators' campaigns, which
she defended as her right. Hauda argued that was a method used by
lobbyists to circumvent lobbying restrictions.
   Milwaukee Magazine has not said what its article will say, but
some legislators have admitted taking favors from Goyke.
   State Rep. Gordon Bradley accepted a $5 or $6 fish dinner from
Carl Otte, a former legislator and employee of Goyke.
   Wausau Mayor John Robinson, a former state representative,
failed to report $247 in air fares for members of his family
accepted from Pfizer Inc., one of Goyke's clients, to a Chicago
health-care conference at which Robinson spoke.
   Several legislators attended a Green Bay Packer-Chicago Bears
game in Green Bay, possibly at Goyke's expense.
   State Sen. Jerome Van Sistine acknowledged accepting two nights
of lodging in Los Angeles during his honeymoon as a present from
Goyke's wife, a family friend.
   Goyke says he intends to reclaim his image.
   ``I believe in being a nice guy. I like the legislative process.
I respect it,'' he said. ``I think that we have a very, very clean
state, I honestly do.''
</TEXT>
