<1ST_LINE>r w AM-VietnamMemorial     07-19 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam Memorial,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Park Service Says Scratch on Vietnam Wall Was There Since Wall
Built</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Park Service officials said Tuesday
that they have ruled out vandalism as the cause of a 4-inch scratch
on the Vietnam Veterans Memorial and that the damage has been there
since the wall was built.
   ``We were greatly relieved to rule out vandalism,'' said Sandra
Alley, a National Park Service spokeswoman.
   She said the hairline scratch, which is 4 inches long and an
eighth of an inch wide, was made when names of fallen servicemen
were sandblasted onto one of the wall's 121 granite panels. The
engravers decided to finish the job without removing the scratch,
Alley said.
   The scratch was discovered on Sunday by a park ranger.
   ``It's such a shallow mark, it was nearly invisible,'' Alley
said. ``Unless the light is right, it's very difficult to see. I'm
sure that's why it wasn't discovered before.''
   The memorial, which includes the names of 58,156 military
personnel known to have been killed in the Vietnam War, opened on
Veterans Day 1982. It quickly became the most popular monument in
the nation's capital, and now attracts 12,000 to 15,000 visitors
daily.
   Two months ago, the memorial was scratched and defaced by
vandals. More than $80,000 has been raised through private
donations to repair that damage, although work has not yet begun,
Alley said.
</TEXT>
