<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-19 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTAGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Officer Rick Flynn is down in the
dumps. But that's easy to understand because he's patrolling in a
dump truck.
   The only police car in this eastern Pennsylvania community of
about 3,500 broke down this week, and officials were concerned
about possible insurance problems if officers used their own cars.
   So officials gave police the borough's dump truck.
   ``People who see me in the dump truck think it's funny,'' Flynn
said. ``I think it's funny, unless I'm driving it. That thing
bounces a lot.''
   Flynn said the police car should be repaired Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dick Howe paid out nearly $60 and a lesson
in human nature to students in his remedial math class this summer.
   In return, he got his students' attention, and that was worth
every penny, Howe says.
   When Howe walked into his summer school class of fourth- and
fifth-graders at Southside Elementary School last month, he knew
that motivating 18 students in the heat of summer would be
difficult.
   ``I thought, `Why not pay them? I'm getting paid to be here, so
why not them?' '' Howe said.
   The students were told they would be paid up to 20 cents per
day, depending on attendance, behavior and performance.
   ``It gives them a purpose for being here. Students have to have
goals to achieve, and this gave them something as a goal,'' Howe
said.
   The change in attitude was almost immediate.
   ``They were aware of it when I put their name on the board (for
misbehaving). They knew they were losing money,'' the teacher said.
   Payday was Friday, the end of the term. Students were paid $4.70
down to $1.70. No one got the maximum $5 for the six-week session.
   ``They left a little richer than they came in, in one way or
another. If that makes a lasting impression, then it was worth
it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
