<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1606EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--JacksonDelegates     07-19 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Jackson Delegates,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Delegates Cool To Jackson-Dukakis Solidarity Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is a notable lack of enthusiasm among Jesse
Jackson backers about his solidarity agreement with Michael Dukakis
even as they express hope the relationship could bring tangible
victories in the future.
   The official Jackson campaign line on the Jackson-Dukakis
agreement is a positive one _ emphasizing the agreement in which
Dukakis will involve Jackson and his staff in the general election,
providing resources for Jackson to campaign for the Democrats.
   But many Jackson supporters, who wanted their candidate on the
ticket, are disappointed in the agreement, campaign aides
acknowledged.
   ``The important thing here is that Reverend Jackson, who was
disturbed over feeling that he was not being properly courted by
the Dukakis people, is now satisfied,'' said Rep. Louis Stokes,
D-Ill.
   But even among some who were putting out the positive ``spin,''
there was at times as much resignation as enthusiasm in the
reaction, and acknowledgement that Jackson's constituency might not
buy into it.
   Rep. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., said the agreement would give
Dukakis ``more credibility'' with Jackson's supporters, but added,
``It remains to be seen whether the people who have been turned off
over the past few days can be turned on again.''
   ``There is nothing really to be happy about,'' said Rep. Charles
Rangel, D-N.Y., a key Jackson adviser. ``The only thing we have
gained is entering an atmosphere where (the two campaigns) can work
out a strategy to win,'' in November.
   Rangel said that was how it should be among members of the same
political party. So the Jackson-Dukakis arrangement really puts
them at what he considers the starting gate. For that reason, he
said he would hardly consider Monday's agreement a victory.
   Jackson has mentioned the agreement only fleetingly in speeches
since he and Dukakis announced it, focusing instead on his future
agenda and the issues he has highlighted throughout his campaign.
   In answer to the question ``What did Jesse get?'' some of his
supporters see only crumbs from the agreement announced with
Dukakis.
   ``The only thing Dukakis gave up was the opportunity to lose,''
without Jackson's support, said Rangel. As to the agreement that
Jackson staff members would be integrated into the Dukakis team,
Rangel said, ``I don't see why if you sacrifice your advisers and
time'' to help another candidate, ``that this is a great
accomplishment.''
   Officially, key advisers say the new attitude and respect shown
by Dukakis is what is most important and specifics can follow from
there.
   The future will tell if the new relationship pans out into real
access and influence by Jackson in Dukakis' politics, they said.
   ``We have to take him for his word that he will include Jesse
Jackson in a very substantial and meaningful way,'' said
Assemblywoman Maxine Waters of California.
   An aide to one Jackson congressional adviser said his boss was
``very disappointed'' and felt the concessions to Jackson were not
particularly meaningful.
   Dukakis agreed to push for legislation on a number of issues he
already supports _ tougher sanctions against South Africa,
statehood for the District of Columbia, simplification of voter
registration, and greater commitment to minority business set-aside
programs.
   Jackson also won party rules changes so he can get nearly half
the 25 at-large members of the Democratic National Committee, and a
new DNC vice chair.
   ``So what?'' said the congressional aide to all of the above.
   Mayor Andrew Young noted, however, that, ``People don't realize
you don't get anything at a convention unless you win.''
   And, he added, Jackson ``didn't really need anything,'' because
he has an enthusiastic following and can go his own way outside of
traditional political bargains.
   A close Jackson confidant, former Carter administration official
Bert Lance, refuses to entertain talk of Jackson losing anything in
light of what he has accomplished with his campaign.
   Looking out on a street lined with about 250 cheering people who
gathered Tuesday to wait for Jackson outside a small, unannounced
breakfast speech, Lance insisted, ``He won. There are no advance
people putting this on.''
   And he said of the convention, ``They don't give out door prizes
down there.''
</TEXT>
