<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TwelfthMan     07-19 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Twelfth Man,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Of World War II Veteran Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of a soldier believed to be
an American missing since World War II have been discovered on a
remote Aleutian Island, the U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service says.
   ``Our records show that 12 American soldiers were stationed
there during World War II, and only 11 came home,'' Walt Steiglitz,
the service's regional director, said Monday. ``After 45 years of
missing in action, the 12th soldier is finally coming home too.''
   Fish & Wildlife biologists on Buldir Island found a skull, leg,
arm and pelvic bones a few yards from their camp earlier this
month. The biologists are studying seabirds on the tiny, rocky
island about 1550 miles southwest of Anchorage.
   Chuck Diters, an archaeologist at the agency's Anchorage
headquarters, said American military boots, an M-1 rifle with
bayonet, an American coin and a pocketwatch inscribed with ``U.S.''
were found with the bones.
   A wallet also was recovered, but Diters said its contents were
deteriorated too much to make an immediate identification of the
owner.
   ``The body was wedged into some large boulders, as if the
soldier may have been trying to escape from the weather,'' said
biologist Mike Boylan. ``The terrain is very rough and disorienting
there. He probably got lost and died of exposure.''
   The remains were found about four miles from what is left of a
military camp on the northwest corner of the island. The remains
and personal effects were being taken by boat to the U.S. Naval
Base at Adak.
   Military spokesmen in Anchorage said Tuesday they did not know
the name of the missing soldier or what would be the next step in
identifying the remains.
   A Fish & Wildlife spokesman said the remains were found July 12
or 13, but radio communications with Buldir are difficult and he
was not sure of the date.
   The 5,000-acre island is halfway between Attu and Kiska, two
islands occupied by the Japanese from 1942 to 1943. An American
invasion drove the Japanese from Attu, and they abandoned Kiska a
short time later.
   No battles were fought on Buldir, which became the site of a
12-man U.S. military weather station.
</TEXT>
