<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CoinShow     07-19 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coin Show,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Competing Olympic Designs to be Displayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All 84 designs submitted for the U.S. 1988
Olympic coin will be among the displays this week at the American
Numismatic Association's convention.
   The entries were submitted to Treasury Department officials by
the staff of the U.S. Mint in Philadelphia and nine outside
artists, convention officials said. Mint sculptors had the winning
entries for two of the four sides of the gold and silver coins.
   The five-day convention begins Wednesday, and is expected to
draw 15,000 people, said Deborah J. Muehleisen, spokeswoman for the
coin association, said.
   The convention offers coin collectors an opportunity for buying
and trading, as well as educational sidelights. One display will be
on the scarcity of pocket change during the Civil War.
   A Liberty bust by Elizabeth Jones, chief sculptor and engraver
for the U.S. Mint, was picked for the obverse of the $5 gold 1988
Olympic commemorative coin. An eternal flame design by Marcel
Jovine of New Jersey is on the back of the gold.
   The $1 silver coin's obverse, which shows the Olympic flame
passing between two torches, is by Patricia Lewis Vernani of New
Hampshire. Mint sculptor-engraver Sherl J. Winter submitted the
winning reverse design for the silver _ five Olympic circles in a
wreath.
   Among the mints represented will be the United States, British
Royal, Royal Canadian, China, the Netherlands, Italian State,
Mexico, Portuguese State and Singapore, and the Bermuda Monetary
Authority.
   The Dutch Mint has chosen the convention to introduce its first
double ducat since 1867. The new double ducat, priced at $185, is
slightly larger than a quarter and of 0.983 fine gold.
   Australia, like Cincinnati, is celebrating its bicentennial, and
will introduce the 1988 Australian Nugget Proof issue. The Royal
Canadian Mint will offer new commemorative coins.
</TEXT>
