<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--MsVsMrs     07-19 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ms Vs Mrs,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bar Association Launches Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Allegheny County Bar Association will
investigate the treatment of women by the judicial system following
a federal judge's order that an attorney use her married name in
court, the association president said.
   But Thomas Hollander said plans for the investigation were in
place before the dispute erupted July 8 in the courtroom of U.S.
District Judge Hubert Teitelbaum.
   ``Women have made a lot of progress, but there is still a lot of
ground to gain,'' Hollander said Monday, the same day several
women's groups called for Teitelbaum's resignation.
   Fueling the formation of a bar association committee on women
and the courts was Teitelbaum's threat to jail attorney Barbara
Wolvovitz for refusing to use her husband's surname while
practicing in his courtroom.
   Teitelbaum later apologized to Ms. Wolvovitz and acknowledged
she was legally entitled to use the name she chose.
   Hollander said the bar association has 53 committees and
sections, staffed by members of the bar and bench. But he said he
would be willing to have representatives from outside the legal
profession serve on the new committee.
