<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrailsideSlayings     07-19 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trailside Slayings,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Deathy Penalty Imposed In `Trailside Slayings'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted in the ``Trailside Slayings''
was sentenced to death for the second time Tuesday for murdering
five hikers in 1980.
   David J. Carpenter, 58, of San Francisco, had already been
sentenced to death for murdering two women in 1981 in Santa Cruz
County state parks.
   Superior Court Judge Herbert Hoffman on Tuesday imposed the
sentence recommended June 27 by the jury that convicted Carpenter
of first-degree murder.
   Hoffman could have sentenced Carpenter to life in prison without
parole. He refused to do so, however, after recounting Carpenter's
criminal history since 1960, which involves at least eight violent
attacks on women.
   ``Mr. Carpenter is, without question, a serial killer ... and a
habitual criminal likely to commit violent acts against others,''
Hoffman said. ``Two previous periods of incarceration, from 1960-69
and 1970-79, had no effect on his criminal activity.''
   All appeals in capital cases go directly to the state Supreme
Court.
   Marin County Public Defender Frank Cox had asked that
Carpenter's life be spared, arguing that he committed the crimes
during moments of rage arising from a lifetime of abuse and
rejection.
   Deputy District Attorney John Posey contended that Carpenter
shot the hikers execution-style after his sexual advances were
rejected, and said Carpenter deserved to die for the crimes. Four
of the five 1980 victims were women.
   Carpenter also was convicted of raping two victims and trying to
rape a third during his six-week killing spree, which left many of
northern California's popular hiking areas nearly deserted until
his May 1981 arrest.
   His trial was moved to San Diego after a judge ruled extensive
publicity about the case prevented him from receiving a fair trial
in northern California.
</TEXT>
