<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lyng-FarmVisits     07-19 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lyng-Farm Visits,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Get Help from Nature; Hope for More from Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng, beginning a 10-state
inspection of drought damage, met Tuesday with farmers in Ohio and
Indiana who got some relief from nature but are hoping for more
from Washington.
   As much as 2{ inches of rain fell in the two states on Monday
and Tuesday. But at Lyng's first stop, John A. Scherer's farm near
Shelby, Ohio, the cornfields were still bone dry only a half-inch
below the surface.
   In Indiana, Lyng said his department has received all the crop
data required to assess requests for disaster declarations, but
gave no indication what assistance would be offered.
   ``I don't think it will take very long for us to do an
evaluation,'' he said at Avery Sheets' farm near West Lafayette,
Ind. ``I would say in days rather than weeks or months.''
   At best, Sheets said, he may harvest 30 percent of a normal crop
from the 1,000 acres he planted in corn. ``It might be just all cob
and no kernels,'' he said, showing an ear to Lyng.
   While the agriculture secretary expressed concern about the
plight of farmers, whose crops have withered under 100-degree
temperatures and a months-long rainfall shortage, several of the
farmers said interest and aid might be too late.
   Lyng ``came knowing there weren't any answers,'' said Jim
Rieman, a farmer from Crestline, Ohio.
   In Ohio, Lyng said he anticipated heavier losses than the
national average.
   ``This has always been a reliable production area,'' Lyng said,
and that might account for the low percentage of farmers with
federal crop insurance. The insurance is required to benefit from a
disaster declaration Lyng signed last week for farmers in Ohio and
Missouri.
   Gov. Richard Celeste, who left the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta to join Lyng, said Ohio's corn crop could be
all but wiped out. But he said rain may help some soybean fields
recover.
   ``We could lose two-thirds or more of our corn crop,'' Celeste
said. ``There's nothing the rain can do, except maybe for the
soybeans.''
   Lyng is also visiting farms in Tennessee, Missouri, Iowa, South
Dakota, North Dakota, Minnesota, Wisconsin and Michigan.
</TEXT>
