<DOCNO> AP880719-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1647EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--ThisSpaceAvailable     07-19 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--This Space Available,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Podium Time Goes Begging At Demonstration Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN--Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What if they gave a protest rally and nobody came?
   It's been happening a lot at the Democratic National Convention,
where the city took over a two-acre parking lot across the street
from the convention site for use by demonstrators.
   Demonstrators with a tub to thump are finding that causes dear
to their hearts are sometimes of little interest to just about
anyone else.
   Sometimes even the demonstrators don't show up.
   Weeks before the convention, groups requesting time at the lot
were assigned two-hour time slots for use of a city-provided stage
and sound system.
   The lot holds some 35,000 people, but Alternative `88, an
umbrella organization for a number of protest groups, went to U.S.
District Court just before the convention, seeking additional lots
for demonstrators. They lost, and lost an appeal.
   Despite the court fights, many of the scheduled demonstrators
are not showing up and most who appear do so to an audience of only
a few spectators, many of them journalists.
   An Atlanta-based conservative group didn't show up Monday, nor
did a New York City-based group backing the independent
presidential campaign of Lenora Fulani.
   When Fulani, who had said she would bring 10,000 supporters to
Atlanta, appeared later Monday there was a crowd of only about
1,000, many of whom were part of a march organized by civil rights
leader Hosea Williams.
   That was one of the larger crowds so far to occupy the lot.
LEGAL, a gay and lesbian rights organization, brought about 2,000
on Sunday.
   About 15 people, easily half of them journalists, turned out
Tuesday morning to watch Eugene Delguardio, complete with judicial
robes, stage a ``trial'' of House Speaker Jim Wright.
   About a dozen onlookers and reporters watched when the family of
Darrell Alexander took the podium to urge that he be released from
a jail in Ghana. He has been accused of trying to export parrots
illegally from that west African nation.
   Several other groups drew tiny crowds and often were outnumbered
by police assigned to the sweltering lot to ensure order.
   There have been minor face-offs between demonstrators and police
at the lot, and a demonstration by white supremacists was called
off by the city when the marchers were outnumbered by angry
counter-demonstrators. Police also canceled the group's rally on
the steps of the Capitol, saying they wanted to avoid possible
bloodshed.
   Many of the larger demonstrations have taken place away from the
designated demonstration area.
   Police arrested 134 anti-abortion protesters at the Atlanta
SurgiCenter about two miles from the convention hall on Tuesday. On
Monday about 1,200 protesters went through downtown Atlanta to
protest alleged discriminatory lending policies for residents of
poorer neighborhoods, but the demonstrators but did not go to the
demonstration lot.
   Tuesday morning, when a scheduled demonstration by AIDS patients
failed to materialize, one group of officers passed the time ogling
a scantily clad young woman who seemed to enjoy posing in the
window of the Omni Hotel across the street from the demonstration
lot.
   ``Doesn't anybody have any binoculars?'' asked one. ``The ...
(Georgia Bureau of Investigation) is never around when you need
them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
