<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-VOACensorship     07-19 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-VOA Censorship,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says Security at Stake in Voice of America Article</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government contended Tuesday that
foreign policy and national security interests require a Voice of
America employee who wrote an article critical of the agency to
submit the article to a censor before publication.
   William Dempster, an assistant U.S. attorney, told a U.S.
District Court judge that the State Department's pre-publication
regulations are designed to help keep employees from violating the
law.
   ``Substantial foreign policy and national security interests
support the pre-publication regulations,'' he told the court.
``Such activity (writing an unauthorized article) could jeopardize
security, disrupt foreign relations and impair the mission of the
agency.''
   At issue in the case is an article written by Voice of America
employee Carolyn Weaver that is scheduled to appear in the
September-October issue of the Columbia Journalism Review. Ms.
Weaver said in an affidavit that the article details political
abuses by the VOA, including ``the apparent illegal use of VOA
programs for covert activity.''
   Ms. Weaver's attorney, Stephen M. Kohn, told the court that the
regulation ``is too broad ... goes too far.''
   ``Ms. Weaver is a part-time worker ... a script writer ... for
the VOA. She doesn't deal with secrets.'' he said. ``What they (the
government) want to do is take regulations that cover the CIA
(Central Intelligence Agency), expand the coverage and apply them
to all employees who work in anything to do with foreign policy.''
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson took the case under
advisement. He said, however, he could not guarantee he would make
a decision on issuing a preliminary injunction declaring the
regulations unconstitutional in time for Ms. Weaver to make her
deadline of July 20 with the Columbia Journalism Review.
   Kohn said afterward that if Jackson rules against Ms. Weaver, he
would seek an expedited review before the U.S. Court of Appeals in
Washington.
   Ms. Weaver challenged the State Department rules after she was
ordered to submit the article to a censor.
   Under State Department regulations that also apply to the VOA,
employees of the U.S. Information Agency and the Agency for
International Development are required to submit their writings,
speeches or teaching materials ``on matters of official concern''
for clearance prior to publication.
   According to the department's Foreign Affairs Manual, an
employee's work can be denied clearance if it discloses classified
information or is inaccurate or ``inconsistent with current foreign
policy or can reasonably be expected to affect adversely U.S.
foreign relations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
