<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1829EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlcoholTests     07-19 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alcohol Tests,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Say Machine Results Illegal; 1,200 Drunk-Driving Cases
Imperiled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judicial panel invalidated the results of
five alcohol breath-testing machines, casting doubt on more than
1,200 drunken driving arrests made over the last two years.
   Orange County's six traffic judges ruled Monday that a state
agency violated the law by not testing and re-certifying the
machines after they were sent back to the manufacturer for
modifications two years ago.
   About 4,400 people have been arrested on drunken driving charges
in the county in each of the last two years, but the unusual mass
challenge by defense lawyers only covered undecided cases.
   Prosecutors and defense attorneys disagree on how much the
ruling will hurt the more than 1,200 outstanding cases.
   Assistant State Attorney Pam Smith had said earlier that the
state could use other evidence such as videotapes, field sobriety
tests and officers' testimony in many of the cases.
   But Stuart Hyman, one of two defense attorneys to argue the case
last week, said the machines were crucial to most cases.
   ``Unless a guy is falling-down drunk on a videotape, they (the
prosecution) are hurting,'' he said. ``It's one of their big pieces
of evidence.''
   Hyman predicted the state would be forced to allow many
defendants to plead guilty to reduced reckless driving charges, or
that many more cases would go to trial.
   Sheriff's attorney Bill Vose said he did not expect the
sheriff's office to stop using the machines. ``I would expect that
we would keep testing and ask the state to expedite its
certification procedure,'' he said.
   But Hyman said, ``If they go out tonight and start testing
people, it's unapproved.''
   The state Health and Rehabilitative Services Department
certified the Intoxilyzer 5000 machine for use in 1984, according
to testimony at last week's hearing. About 60 are in use around the
state, and similar challenges have been filed in other counties.
   However, the Orange County ruling is not binding on cases in
other counties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
