<1ST_LINE>r p EarlyConventionOpeningFoiledbyAbsentSpeakers     07-19
0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Early Convention Opening Foiled by Absent Speakers</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic National Convention was supposed
to open early Tuesday to allow for protracted debate on the
platform. But when the starting time came, the speakers weren't
there.
   As a result, the session opened only four minutes ahead of
schedule, at 4:11 p.m.
   ``Unfortunately, some of those members who desire and deserve be
heard on these issues have not been able to arrive at this time,''
said chairman Jim Wright at 3 p.m.
   In the next hour, he suggested twice that anyone who wanted to
address platform issues could come up to the podium microphone and
do so. Nobody took him up on it.
   He assured the convention that there would be no vote before the
original starting time, so that no advocate could steal a march on
opponents.
   Convention officials, with the concurrence of the Michael
Dukakis and Jesse Jackson camps, had decided earlier in the day to
open at 3 p.m. to accommodate what Wright called ``an ad hoc
discussion.''
   The hall was only one-third full when Wright made his first
announcement. By starting time, about three-fourths of the
delegates were in their seats.
