<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BankFire 1stLd-Writethru a0725 07-19 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0725,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skyscraper Blaze Blamed On Refinishing Chemicals</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS graf 5, `The flames...' with 2 grafs to update with
report of injury to one worker and update damage estimate to
$500,000; picks up graf 6, `Officials said...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vapors from chemicals being used in a
furniture refinishing project caused the fire that gutted two
office suites in the 38-story Union Bank building, fire officials
said Tuesday.
   ``It was accidental,'' said Fire Department spokesman Jim Wells.
``Chemical vapors made contact with an electrical outlet,'' causing
a flash fire.
   Monday night's blaze was a haunting reminder of the May 4 fire
that killed one man and ravaged five floors of the city's tallest
building, the 62-story First Interstate Bank building.
   There were no deaths in the Union Bank fire, but two of the 150
firefighters called to battle flames on the 34th and 35th floors
were treated by paramedics for exhaustion and heat.
   A worker who was refinishing a bookcase on the 34th floor
sustained minor burns, said Fire Chief Donald O. Manning.
   The flames destroyed two office suites and caused slight damage
to the surrounding area, causing $500,000 damage, officials said.
   Officials said lessons learned in fighting the earlier fire
helped fight Monday night's blaze, even though the Union Bank
building, like First Interstate, has no fire extinguishers.
   Manning said the fire was put out in less than 45 minutes
because the alarm was sounded quickly. Also, water was available
and better communications were set up.
   In the First Interstate fire, radios between fire floors and
command officials outside failed to work, but new, more powerful
radios prevented a communication problem Monday night.
   The Union Bank blaze gave new impetus to the move to hasten
implementation of a law requiring sprinklers in high-rises. The
Union Bank tower was built in 1966, prior to the 1974 city
ordinance requiring sprinklers.
   Last Friday, the City Council voted to mandate sprinklers within
four years in 343 pre-1974 high-rises, and sprinklers were actually
in the process of being installed at Union Bank.
   ``It is unconscionable to build high-rises without sprinklers in
them,'' Councilman Marvin Braude said after the Monday blaze.
Councilman Nate Holden agreed, saying ``dragging our feet has
already caused two major fires in L.A.''
   Eighty-three people in the Union Bank building escaped down
stairwells. Most tenants were back inside on Tuesday and operations
were described as normal by bank officials.
   ``I was jumping three steps at a time,'' said Bradley Franks, an
asbestos removal worker who was on the 28th floor when he heard an
evacuation call over the building intercom.
   ``A few people were following and some stumbled and fell. I was
on the 16th floor when I saw firefighters coming up the stairs.''
   Firefighters lugged hoses and others carried equipment weighing
up to 100 pounds up 34 flights of stairs.
   At midnight, the building changed ownership: The Union Bank
tower became property of California First Bank, which acquired
Union Bank in a $750 million transaction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880719-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1750EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Vendors     07-19 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Vendors,480</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of vendors who paid up to $1,500 for
booths at the Democratic National Convention held a news conference
Tuesday to protest their locations in an exhibit hall far away from
foot traffic in the World Congress Center.
   ``We were told 40,000 to 50,000 people would be coming
downstairs. They don't even know we're here,'' said Dr. Penny Rich,
a California physician trying to sell copies of a book she wrote
about drug abuse.
   She and others demanded refunds and said they should be moved to
high-traffic areas in other parts of the sprawling complex across
from The Omni convention hall.
   Mark Weiner, marketing manager of the convention, said vendors
would be offered full refunds if they wanted to leave or 50 percent
refunds if they wanted to move to a more centrally located ballroom.
   Weiner, president of a Cranston, R.I., company called Financial
Innovations, said there were about 180 booths at the convention,
with some companies operating more than one. Licenses cost from
$750 to $1,500 per booth.
   Weiner said he ``never made any guarantees about how many
people'' would find their way to exhibit hall, which is in the
basement of the building in a different wing from the press and
Democratic party operations.
   Don Fowler, chief executive officer of the convention, issued a
statement saying the party would try to encourage delegates and
guests to purchase souvenirs from small-business vendors in the
exhibit hall. ``The party will do everything possible to publicize
their location and also relocate some vendors to areas... that are
heavily trafficked,'' Fowler said
   A member of the Democratic National Committee from West
Virginia, who didn't identify himself, told the protesting vendors
he was sure other DNC members would sympathize with their plight.
``I knew you were there _ it took me over an hour to find you last
night,'' he said.
   Rich said she had sold three copies of ``The Cracked Pipe,'' her
book, at $5 apiece, since the convention began. ``It cost me $500
to get them printed,'' she said.
   The vendors said they were losing up to $1,000 a day in expenses
and charged that Weiner, who gets a cut of whatever they make, set
aside 10 souvenir booths for himself in the most heavily traveled
part of the World Congress Center.
   Weiner said those booths are operated jointly by his company and
Atlanta '88, the city's convention host committee. ``We have always
told everyone that we would have official booths at the congress
center and around town,'' he said.
   A labor dispute may be an embarrassment to the Democrats, but at
least one vendor said she disagreed with a protestor's threats to
vote Republican this fall.
   ``It wouldn't make me vote for George Bush,'' said cartoonist
Susan Denison of Orlando, Fla. ``That would be a little drastic.''
</TEXT>
