<DOCNO> AP880719-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1752EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HelicopterExplosion     07-19 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helicopter Explosion,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Begins Investigation of Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Anderton is cq in 4th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers found no sign of eight missing
Navy helicopter crew members on Tuesday, more than 24 hours after
their Sea Dragon crashed outside the Golden Gate.
   A five-member investigation board began going over pieces from
the MH-53E Sea Dragon, which went down during a mine-sweeping
exercise on Monday.
   The wreckage was recovered by Coast Guard cutters searching for
debris and survivors, though officials said there was virtually no
hope left for the crew.
   ``Yesterday (Monday) afternoon they were searching about 10
square miles, and today they'll expand the search, going farther
out because of the wind and currents,'' said Coast Guard Petty
Officer Dave Anderton.
   Although the Coast Guard said Monday it expected to find no
survivors, Anderton said the search would continue as long as there
was a chance anyone was alive.
   Navy divers were preparing to explore the chilly, 60-foot-deep
water 11 miles west of the Golden Gate for wreckage of the
helicopter, one of four MH-53E aircraft based at the Alameda Naval
Air Station on the east side of San Francisco Bay.
   The aircraft is a mine-sweeping version of the CH-53E Super
Stallion, a cargo and troop-carrying chopper that twice has been
the object of congressional inquiries.
   Twenty servicemen have died in previous crashes of CH-53E
copters, according to Andrew Lightbody, editorial director for
International Defense Images Magazine in Irvine.
   Louis Franecke, a San Francisco lawyer representing families of
service people killed in crashes of the 53E helicopters, said in
Tuesday's editions of the San Francisco Examiner that family
members have told him crewmen are often asked to sign legal waivers
``before they go up.''
   A Navy spokesman in Washington, D.C., said the allegation was
``absolutely false.'' Lt. Bruce Cole also said crewmen are not
asked to sign waivers before going up in any kind of helicopter.
   Lt. Elizabeth Kerstens, a spokewoman for the Marine Corps, which
also uses 53E helicopters, said there was no such requirement.
   The captain of the salmon-fishing boat Lovely Martha said he
heard two distinct explosions several moments after he saw three
puffs of smoke rise over the fog bank.
   ``There was a tremendous explosion. There were a lot of pieces
of the helicopter .... pontoons, wheels, all kinds of things
floating around. It was total annihilation,'' skipper Frank Rescino
said.
   The captain of another fishing boat, Northern Light, said the
noises didn't sound like a fire or fuel explosion.
   ``It sounded like it hit and bounced and then hit again,'' said
skipper Jim Koskela. ``I called it impact, it wasn't an explosion.
Like wood hitting water, just magnified.''
   Navy spokesman Valente would not confirm or deny whether there
were explosions, saying it could be detrimental to the
investigation.
   In February 1987, the Navy and Marine Corps grounded all CH-53E
and MH-53E helicopters. Cole said all those models were inspected
because of problems with part of the power train and then returned
to operation.
   Cole said the helicopters, described as the largest in the
Western world, did not have an ``abnormally high'' accident record.
   The Orange County Register, using documents obtained through the
Freedom of Information Act, reported in 1987 that in its first five
years of service, the CH-53E had the worst safety record of any
helicopter in the Navy or Marine Corps.
   Last May, the House Armed Services Committee began a special
inquiry into the aircraft at the request of Rep. Robert Badham,
R-Calif.
   Badham said Monday the investigation showed ``there is no
inherent design or mechanical flaw in the manufacture or design.''
The investigation found that the accidents were caused by pilot
error or a broken piece of equipment not common to the crashes,
Badham said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880719-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1849EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Bankers     07-19 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Bankers,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Group Says It Supports Drought-Aid Legislation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major association of country banks said
Tuesday it supports drought-aid legislation in Congress that would
pour up to $7 billion into stricken areas to help farmers recover
from crop and livestock losses.
   The Independent Bankers Association of America, which says that
half its members are agricultural banks, sent letters to members of
the Senate and House agricultural committees in support of bills
awaiting final action when Congress returns to work on July 26.
   A version approved by the Senate committee would provide
payments of up to $100,000 to drought-stricken farmers. President
Reagan has indicated he would sign such legislation.
   Association President-elect O. Jay Tomson, Charles City, Iowa,
said a special committee concluded that ``the legislation deserves
our full support and prompt enactment.''
   The legislation would replace a major portion of the income lost
by crop farmers in 1988 due to heat and drought by reallocating
money that would otherwise have gone to farmers as ``deficiency''
payments to compensate them for low commodity prices.
   Drought has cut production and forced up prices, meaning the
payments will be less. Thus, the ``savings'' would be used to
finance the drought benefits.
   In addition, livestock, dairy and poultry producers would be
provided financial aid to help cover higher feed costs and help
them keep their foundation stock.
</TEXT>
