<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ShootingSpree 1stLd-Writethru a0679 07-19 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shooting Spree, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0679,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Different Stories On Attempts To Commit Hayes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to CORRECT that Hayes is accused of four
murders, but formally charged with two; picks up graf 3, ``Sheriff
Preston</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ The stepfather of a man accused of
four murders said the family tried to have Michael Charles Hayes
committed to a mental hospital, but were told by a sheriff's
officer to wait until Monday.
   ``It seems to me, Monday was a little bit late,'' said Garris
Edwards. His stepson, Hayes, is accused of killing four people and
wounding five others in a roaming, 12-minute shooting spree on
Sunday. So far, Hayes has been charged with two counts of
first-degree murder.
   Sheriff Preston Oldham refused comment Tuesday, pending
completion of the investigation.
   Hayes was shot and critically wounded after allegedly opening
fire on sheriff's deputies.
   Edwards said Monday that family members also tried to have Hayes
committed when he was taken to a hospital earlier Saturday. Hayes
reportedly injured his hand beating a wall.
   However, Roger Rollman, a spokesman for North Carolina Baptist
Hospital, said Tuesday that there was no apparent effort to seek
involuntary commitment for Hayes. Rollman said he interviewed all
medical personnel who came in contact with Hayes and his stepfather
Saturday night.
   Rollman said Hayes came to the hospital Saturday night with a
finger injury on the left hand. About an hour later, Rollman said,
``he left the emergency room against medical advice and without
getting his finger treated. There was no indication in the record
that anything was said about having the man committed.
   ``It is routine for us in the course of a year to have people
come in and say they need to have someone committed on an
involuntary basis,'' Rollman said.
   Friends and family of Hayes told The Dispatch of Lexington that
his behavior had changed drastically several days before the
shootings.
   Hayes, who had been living in a trailer, had financial and
personal troubles, friends told the newspaper. He moved into his
moped shop about a week ago after he and his wife, who is nine
months pregnant, separated.
   Edwards told WSJS-WTQR radio on Monday that he had told hospital
workers Saturday that Hayes had ``cracked up and lost it,'' but
they declined to commit him.
   Edwards said he also talked to a lieutenant at the Forsyth
County Sheriff's Department on Sunday morning, and was told the
commitment process would take eight hours. The lieutenant told
Hayes' family members that the commitment could wait until Monday,
according to Edwards.
   Rollman said to begin the process for involuntary commitment, a
person would undergo a psychiatric examination, followed by
paperwork detailing the results. A clerk of court would review and
then sign papers if commitment was deemed appropriate.
   Sheriff's deputies would pick up the person to be committed and
take him to the specific facility, Rollman said.
   Hayes, who was shot six times in the back, groin and leg, was
listed in critical condition Tuesday. A hospital spokesman said the
chances for his recovery was good.
   The dead were Thomas Walter Nicholson, 24, of Winston-Salem;
Crystal Susan Cantrell, 16, of Winston-Salem; Ronald Lee Hull, 32,
of Winston-Salem, and Melinda Yvonne Hayes, 21, of Lexington.
Oldham said Miss Hayes was not a relative of Hayes.
</TEXT>
