<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Dukakis-Pepper     07-19 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dukakis-Pepper,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seniors Rally For Long-Term Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' 84-year-old mother and Rep.
Claude Pepper, the oldest member of Congress, led senior citizens
in a rally Tuesday for long-term health-care legislation that
Pepper promises to make a national campaign issue.
   ``Unfortunately, our present administration has wanted to do as
little with government applied to people's needs as possible. That
is not what Michael Dukakis is going to do,'' said Euterpe Dukakis.
   Mrs. Dukakis, who said she had required home care three times
herself, predicted that if her son is elected president he would
push for passage of legislation for long-term care, sponsored by
Pepper, that failed in the House this year.
   Pepper, 87, the Miami Democrat who's attending his 13th
convention _ he gave a nominating speech for Franklin D. Roosevelt
at the 1940 national convention _ recounted how his bill was
defeated because of concerns over its costs and a jurisidictional
battle among committee chairmen.
   ``Of course, they're going to have answer to the people this
fall, those who voted callously against the needy American
people,'' said Pepper. He has no opposition for re-election to the
House this year and plans to campaign nationally for his
health-care bill.
   The bill, estimated to cost $27 billion in its first five years,
would provide federally assisted home health care to the
chronically ill of all ages. It would be funded by requiring about
8 million workers who make more than $45,000 a year to pay Medicare
taxes on all their wages _ not just the first $45,000, as under
present law.
   Accompanying Pepper and Mrs. Dukakis at the news conference were
two 5-year-old Atlanta children who would benefit from such
legislation. They were Michael Perry, who has been comatose since
nearly drowning more than a year ago, and Coley Cooper, who
suffered brain damage in a near-drowning two years ago.
   ``I can't believe the heart of America is unconcerned about
these children,'' Pepper said.
</TEXT>
