<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-US-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0681 07-19 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-US-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0681,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Missile Inspector Says Superpowers Adhering To Treaty</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th pvs, Lebedev said ... to CORRECT site of INF treaty
signing to Washington sted Moscow; pickup 7th graf pvs, The
experience ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENHAM COMMON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet official said on
Tuesday that inspections in the United States and Europe show a
superpower treaty scrapping intermediate-range nuclear missiles is
being implemented without cheating.
   Vyacheslav S. Lebedev made the remark after he and 19 other
Soviet inspectors landed at this air force base to start counting
U.S. cruise missiles in Britain in accordance with the treaty.
   The Soviet inspectors arrived at Greenham Common, 50 miles west
of London, aboard a blue-and-white Aeroflot Ilyushin jet. They were
welcomed by a delegation of U.S. and British officers.
   Greenham Common is one of two U.S. cruise missile bases in
Britain. The other is at Molesworth, 50 miles north of London. Both
bases are run by U.S. Air Force personnel, but are technically
British Royal Air Force bases.
   The base has 96 operational missiles and five back-up missiles,
while there are another 16 operational missiles at Molesworth, the
U.S. military says.
   Lebedev said that, based on similar inspections this month in
the United States, the Soviet Union and West Germany, no one seemed
to be cheating on the terms of the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces treaty signed in Washington on Dec. 8 by Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev and President Reagan.
   ``The experience of the inspections has shown that the U.S.S.R.
and United States strictly implemented the treaty signed by them
and the first steps as to its realization are successful,'' said
Lebedev.
   Soviet inspectors arrived in the United States July 16 to
inspect some of the 14 U.S. missile sites, training facilities and
industrial plants. These include Fort Sill in southwestern
Oklahoma, which has 37 Pershing 2 missiles and Redstone Arsenal in
Huntsville, Ala., home of the Army Missile Command that manages the
Pershing 1A and Pershing 2 nuclear missile programs.
   The treaty provides for the elimination within three years of
all nuclear missiles with ranges of 340 miles to 3,000 miles and
includes stringent inspection provisions to guard against cheating.
   At Greenham Common, a customs and immigration post was set up to
receive the Soviets and check the cameras, Geiger counters and
other equipment they were allowed to bring for the inspection.
   They are to stay at the base overnight in converted servicemen's
accommodations, and are to eat meals at a cafeteria on the base.
   Under the treaty, the inspectors may check the missiles and
their 55-foot mobile launchers _ which are to be taken back to the
United States and destroyed _ but not the warheads.
   The Soviets were to declare Wednesday exactly what they want to
see at the bases. They may also place security men at all entry and
exit roads to ensure no missiles are surreptitiously moved out, the
Defense Ministry said.
   ``We're entirely in the Soviets' hands,'' said Defense Ministry
spokesman Martin Helms. ``They will say where they want to go.''
   The inspectors, who will be flown to Molesworth from Greenham
Common, will not be allowed to step outside the bases during their
stay, which is expected to last up to 4{ days, or until the
inspection is completed.
   U.S. officers, mostly from an on-site inspection agency based in
West Germany, will accompany the Soviets as they examine the
missiles and launchers. Soviet inspectors first checked missiles in
Western Europe on July 1 at two West German sites housing
Pershing-2 rockets.
   The current inspections are part of a 60-day period of
``baseline inspections'' to determine the accuracy of data
exchanged by the two sides. The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in
the United States and Western Europe while U.S. inspectors are
visiting 133 Soviet sites.
   So far, no violations have been discovered, U.S. officials say,
and the inspections are about 25 percent complete.
   The Soviets notified the British of their visit on Monday,
officials said, under the 16-hour notice-of-inspection rule.
   In November 1983, Greenham Common was the first Western European
base to accept U.S. cruise missiles under a December 1979 NATO
alliance accord.
</TEXT>
