<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1945EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--LaRouche     07-19 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--LaRouche,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extremist Gives ``Mild'' Speech to Maine Delegation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS X. QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maine delegates to the Democratic National
Convention shrugged off a Tuesday visit by extremist Lyndon
LaRouche, with one terming his presentation ``a very mild speech _
mild for him.''
   Charles O'Leary, the president of the Maine AFL-CIO, said
delegation leaders had been asked to allow LaRouche's views to be
put before the caucus and had agreed.
   ``We were all waiting for some representative to come in, and he
came in himself,'' O'Leary said.
   Members of the group said LaRouche, who was sporting a beard,
spoke for less than five minutes and left after receiving little
response.
   LaRouche warned delegates that ``America's headed for another
depression,'' said Bill Meserve, the local president of striking
paperworkers at the International Paper Co. plant in Jay, Maine.
``They let him talk and get out.''
   O'Leary said the reaction among Maine Democrats ranged from
bemusement to shock. ``Everybody's jaw sort of dropped,'' he said.
   Another Maine delegate, John Martin, the speaker of the state
House of Representatives, said he had heard of similar requests
made of other delegations, but knew of no other appearances by
LaRouche himself.
   ``Other states just flatly refused to let him speak,'' said
Martin, ``but we're open. And he came and he spoke and he left.''
   LaRouche, who is running for president, espouses a variety of
bizarre views, advocating an effort to start settlements on Mars
and accusing the Queen of England of drug trafficking.
   He, along with six aides and five LaRouche organizations, has
been charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury
investigation into allegations that LaRouche's 1984 presidential
campaign reaped more than $2 million through credit card and loan
fraud.
   They went on trial in December 1887, but a mistrial was declared
in May in U.S. District Court in Boston. Prosecutors want to retry
the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
