<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DefenseProbe-GrandJury 1stLd-Writethru a0747 07-19 1098</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Grand Jury, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,1,040</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Begins Taking Testimony In Pentagon Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 3 grafs with Unisys shakeup, picks up 2nd graf pvs,
Meanwhile, an; ADDS 10 grafs on Unisys actions</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury began hearing
witnesses on Tuesday in the massive Pentagon bribery investigation,
while a major contractor fired all its defense-contract consultants
and shook up the management of one division.
   Unisys Corp., whose offices on Long Island, N.Y., have been
searched by federal agents, announced that its own, independent
investigation begun last fall by former Watergate special
prosecutor Henry Ruth had uncovered activity contrary to company
policy.
   Unisys chairman W. Michael Blumenthal, a former Treasury
secretary, placed a Long Island division under new management, put
some employees on administrative leave and terminated ``all
consulting contracts with those who represented the company before
the federal government on defense-related matters.''
   Meanwhile, an attorney for defense consultant and former Navy
official Melvyn Paisley filed motions to quash 11 subpoenas from
the grand jury and to be advised if the government conducted any
illegal electronic surveillance of his client.
   In all, 275 subpoenas, mostly for documents and records, were
due to be answered in Alexandria on Tuesday. Sharon Dibbley,
spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Henry Hudson, said the government had
arranged a location, which she would not identify, where lawyers
and those under subpoena could deliver records without being
observed by reporters.
   Many of the subpoenas are to persons who are only potential
witnesses in the investigation and not targets of it.
   Ms. Dibbley had no comment on the Paisley motion to quash his
subpoenas and said she knew of no objections filed to the other
subpoenas.
   The only recognizable figure to arrive for the morning session
of the grand jury in the U.S. Courthouse was Jack A. Sherman, a
civilian employee of the Marine Corps who supervised equipment
purchases. Sherman's office was searched by federal agents in a
series of coordinated raids on June 14 which brought the nearly
2-year-old probe to public attention.
   No one has been charged yet in the probe of the
$150-billion-a-year Pentagon purchasing system. But government
documents show that investigators are looking allegations that
defense contractors and consultants, many of them former military
men, bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details that could
be vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   Sherman, who has been transferred to other duties pending the
outcome of the investigation, was a supervisory negotiator for the
contracts division of installation and logistics office of the
Marine Corps. He has been a civilian employee of the Marine Corps
since 1971 and was a civilian Navy employee from 1957 to 1971.
   According to Pentagon records, Sherman is a GS-14, making
between $46,600 and $60,683.
   Neither he nor his attorney would comment on his appearance at
the courthouse. It could not be determined if he was actually
brought before the grand jury.
   Other witnesses, however, were seen entering and leaving the
grand jury room later in the day. At a lunch break, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Joseph Aronica, who is in charge of the grand jury, told
reporters ``there won't be any luminaries'' during the first day.
   The grand jury is expected to be back in session Wednesday.
   Paisley's attorney, E. Lawrence Barcella, said he filed a motion
to quash the 11 subpoenas issued for Paisley, who served as
assistant Navy secretary for research, engineering and systems from
December 1981 to April 1987 when he became a consultant.
   In addition, Barcella said, ``We asked the government to affirm
or deny whether they used illegal electronic surveillance. Even the
fact that they may have gotten authorization does not mean their
wiretap was applied for and carried out in a legal matter. Before
we comply with a subpoena, we want to insure that the government
has carried out its responsibilities under the wiretap statute in
an appropriate and accurate manner.''
   Earlier, the government released the search warrant for Paisley,
which indicated that FBI agents were investigating whether he
received payments from General Dynamics, McDonnell Douglas and
Pratt & Whitney while he worked for the Pentagon. The warrant also
showed the government is investigating consulting work he has done
since leaving the government for 10 different defense contractors.
   At Unisys, Blumenthal said in a letter to company employees that
the giant computer company, formed by the merger of Sperry and
Burroughs, had pledged full cooperation with Hudson's investigation.
   ``We expect and encourage each of our employees also to
cooperate fully in responding to the government's inquiries,''
Blumenthal wrote.
   The new management was installed at the former Sperry
Surveillance and Fire Control Division in Great Neck, N.Y.,
Blumenthal said. The government searched Unisys offices in Great
Neck on June 14.
   Federal agents also searched offices or homes of Charles
Gardner, consultant and former general manager and vice president
at the Unisys Great Neck plant; Dennis Mitchell, administrative
aide at the plant; Armtec, a Florida company owned by consultant
William W. Roberts who retired after 30 years with Sperry; William
Galvin, a consultant who worked for Unisys among other companies;
James Kane, founder of the Long Island Aerospace Political Action
Committee; and Paisley, who also did some work for Unisys.
   Mitchell is reported by several newspapers to have handed checks
to Rep. Roy Dyson, D-Md., as campaign contributions during a tour
he made of the Unisys plant a year ago. Those checks and others
later mailed totaled $14,000, the reports have said. The government
has searched the offices of Richard Seelmeyer, a former
congressional aide and Maryland air charter pilot who is reported
to have arranged Dyson's flight to Long Island.
   Blumenthal said he was establishing a senior management approval
process for all consulting agreements and congressional honoraria.
   He also announced the hiring of the Washington law firm of
Covington & Burling to aid the company in enforcing an ethics
program introduced a year ago.
   ``Although our internal investigation is not concluded,''
Blumenthal said. ``to date it indicates that certain division
employees and consultants appear to have had a history of engaging
at Sperry in activities which are contrary to the policies and
procedures put in place by Unisys. These practices appear to have
continued in the new company.''
   The division employes 2,500 of Unisys' 90,000 employees and had
1987 revenue of $300 million with before-tax profits of $18 million.
   Blumenthal said the internal inquiry, begun without knowledge of
the government's investigation, ``focused on the use of outside
consultants and whether any division funds had been diverted for
improper use.''
</TEXT>
