<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-19 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers, Thunderstorms From Plains To Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Widespread showers, thunderstorms and cloudiness moderated
temperatures across much of the nation Tuesday, while parts of
inland California baked.
   Showers and thunderstorms reached across the Gulf Coast states,
the Tennessee and Ohio valleys and portions of the Plains states.
Light rain fell from western Pennsylvania to parts of New England.
   Serious street flooding occurred at Lake Charles, La., Tuesday
morning during heavy thunderstorms.
   Thunderstorms also kicked up high winds, including gusts up to
40 mph at Edmond, Okla., and a tornado just south of Wichita, Kan.
No damage or injuries were reported.
   Widespread rains of 2 to 5 inches Monday night and Tuesday
morning across south-central Nebraska caused lowland flooding of
many small streams in the Republican River basin.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT
included more than 3 inches at Enid, Okla.; about 1{ inches at Lake
Charles, La., Cincinnati and Dyersburg, Tenn.; and more than a
half-inch at Baton Rouge, La., Dothan, Ala., Lincoln, Neb., and
Colorado Springs, Colo.
   Temperatures were mostly in the 80s and 90s across much of the
West including the Pacific Northwest. Portland, Ore., reached 94
degrees by noon local time.
   A strong upper-level high pressure system anchored over Northern
California pushed inland temperatures well above 100 degrees.
Redding, Calif., reached 105 degrees by noon.
   Much of the Northeast, Midwest and the northern and central
Plains had relatively moderate temperatures, with the help of some
cloudiness and scattered showers. Readings were in the 70s and 80s,
with some 60s in southwestern Minnesota, northwestern Iowa and most
of Nebraska. Temperatures in eastern Colorado were mostly in the
50s.
   In the humid south, temperatures were in the lower 90s in
between the showers, from North Carolina across the Gulf Coast
states to much of Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Denver and Limon, Colo., to 105 degrees at Redding,
Calif. The nation's low Tuesday morning was 35 degrees at West
Yellowstone, Mont.
   Wednesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in the
Arizona mountains and from the central and southern Rockies across
the southern Plains; Mississippi, Ohio and Tennessee valleys;
southern Great Lakes; and Gulf Coast to the mid- and south-Atlantic
Coast.
   High temperatures should be in the 80s and 90s, except 70s from
the upper Great Lakes to the northern and central Plains and along
parts of the Pacific Coast, and 100 or more in parts of Texas and
in lower elevations of the interior Northwest and California and
the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
