<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     07-19 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Political Leader Postpones Return After Arrest Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist political leader Mario
Aguinada Carranza says he has canceled his planned return to El
Salvador because of government threats that he will be arrested.
   Aguinada, secretary-general of the Nationalist Democratic Union
Party, told The Associated Press by telephone from Mexico that the
threats ``clearly show the lack of guarantees in the country.''
   When party leaders last week announced plans to return,
Information Minister Roberto Viera told reporters that military
authorities should take Aguinada into custody because ``there are
national and foreign press reports saying he is a leader of the
FMLN.''
   The FMLN is the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the
coalition of five leftist guerrilla groups that have fought the
U.S.-supported government since 1980. It is allied with the
Democratic Revolutionary Front, or FDR, the left's legal political
umbrella organization.
   ``It is one thing that leaders of the FDR can enter the country
to seek legitimacy and political legality and another that a member
of the FMLN wants to enter the country,'' Viera said.
   Aguinada, interviewed Monday, denied he was ever a guerrilla
commander. He helped found the Democratic Revolutionary Front in
1980.
   He said one reason leaders of his Nationalist Democratic Union
Party want to return is to reactivate its 1969 registration as a
legal political party.
   Government officials have described his organization as a front
for the Salvadoran Communist Party.
   Aronette Diaz de Zamora, a leader of the party who is in El
Salvador, denied the accusation.
   ``That is what they have always said, but we are people of
progressive thought and in our party there have been people from
all the political spectrum and we do not deny there may have been
someone from the Communist Party,'' she said.
   Aguinada said Mrs. Zamora and Tirso Canales, who was due to
arrive shortly, would work to revive the party.
</TEXT>
