<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeachWaste     07-19 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Waste,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say No Risk Associated With Washed-Up Hospital Waste;
Cartter is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small amounts of medical debris were
found on beaches in Rhode Island and Massachusetts on Tuesday, more
than 100 miles from the New York and New Jersey shores, where
larger quantities of medical waste have washed up in past weeks.
   The waste poses no specific health risk, officials said. But
some states closed the affected beaches.
   Rhode Island officials said they had little doubt the needles
and syringes, catheter bags, rubber tubing, and respirator parts
were related to the other finds. Some waste also was found on
Connecticut beaches last week.
   The waste likely is ``part of a sweeping arc of medical garbage
that someone has dropped off the Eastern shore,'' said Rhode Island
Health Director H. Denman Scott.
   Health officials in Rhode Island and Connecticut said tests
revealed little health risks associated with the debris, even
though a handful of vials found in New Jersey and New York earlier
this month contained blood that tested positive for the AIDS virus.
   ``Aesthetically, it's a problem. Nobody wants to swim in
garbage,'' said Dr. Matthew Cartter, coordinator of the Connecticut
Health Department's epidemiology program.
   ``But from an epidemiological point of view, there has never
been an outbreak because of disposal of infectious waste,'' he said
Monday.
   Dr. Barbara Debuono, chief of disease control for Rhode Island's
health department, said Tuesday that sun and salt water should have
effectively removed any infectious material from the items.
   It's highly unlikely a person stepping on a needle would
contract hepatitis or the deadly acquired immune deficiency
syndrome, she said.
   Tests on three syringes found at southern Rhode Island beaches
turned up no signs of blood or contaminants, the state health
department said. Those beaches will stay open, officials said.
   Peter Look, a health official in Edgartown, Mass., said Martha's
Vineyard beaches would also stay open, despite discovery of some
empty medical vials and several syringes.
   New York City officials, meanwhile, were waiting for two
consecutive clean tides before lifting the swimming ban at several
city beaches shut when medical waste washed ashore, said Parks
Commissioner Henry Stern.
   About 90 items, including syringes and bottles, were found on
beaches in the New York city area Monday.
   In New Jersey, a swimming ban remained in effect for some
beaches in Asbury Park and Ocean Grove after water samples
continued to show high levels of fecal coliform bacteria, usually
associated with human waste.
   ``It's coming from somewhere, and it's very frustrating not to
know where because we're very concerned it will happen again,''
said Anthony Del Pizzo, head of beach operations in Asbury Park,
where a five-day ban on swimming was lifted Sunday on all but one
beach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
