<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Dukakis-BodyLanguage 1stLd-WritethreamandcontributethebestIcan.''
  07-19 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dukakis-Body Language, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0672,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates grafs 10-12 with TV interview cancellations and
cacucus visit, picks up 11th graf pvs... All business.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most precious commodity in a political
campaign _ more than money or endorsements or straw hats with red,
white and blue bunting _ is what insiders refer to as ``the body.''
This week, the body belongs to one Michael Stanley Dukakis.
   To see what the Democrats want to achieve during convention
week, it's instructive to consider how the governor is spending his
time here. His schedule reveals a sharp departure from the strategy
of nominees past.
   The Dukakis campaign has junked the nominee's ritual
convention-week meetings with delegates. In the past, a fellow like
Walter Mondale or George McGovern would begin his convention day
with breakfast remarks to, say, the Oklahoma delegation, and then
go on to a brief appearance before, for example, the Upper Midwest
Hispanic Agricultural Caucus.
   The Dukakis people have changed all that. The plans for Gov.
Dukakis this week have taken the nominee out of his party's
smoke-filled buffets and instead into the community for some
well-publicized, and carefully considered, public events.
   Ranging from his Sunday night family reunion at cousin Pano's
restaurant in Buckhead to the Monday morning unity meeting with
Jesse Jackson, the Democratic nominee-to-be is balancing political
duties with the developing imagery of a common man.
   Dukakis' main events were plotted in advance as symbols of three
issues he hopes to pursue in his fall campaign against George Bush:
His concern with drug abuse, his endorsement of plant closing
legislation, and his support for civil rights enforcement.
   An event-a-day was scheduled to demonstrate the Democratic
position on these issues.
   For example, on Tuesday Dukakis traveled over to Sweet Auburn
for a tour of the Martin Luther King Center. This is a man who
during his 17-month primary campaign traveled to hundreds of cities
in 40-odd states, who did events morning, noon and night, and it
was rare that he would make his way into the black community.
   Right or wrong, Dukakis simply conceded the primary black vote
to Jesse Jackson. Against Bush, he is conceding nothing, so there
he was with Coretta Scott King, talking about the link between
Greek immigrants and American blacks.
   The other major element of Dukakis' carefully crafted Atlanta
day may be even more significant. His schedulers have allotted as
much as 90 minutes a day for the governor to conduct television
interviews with local TV stations around the country. This is a
huge chunk of time, considering the number of party officials, fat
cats and humble print journalists who would kill for a minute of
the nominee's convention-week time.
   At the Hyatt Regency, a hotel room has been wired for video and
sound; Dukakis merely has to walk down the hall from his suite
while interviewers are shuttled in and out.
   Of course, the best laid plans ... many of the TV interviews
have been canceled as other events crowded in, and on Monday
Dukakis had to scrap a factory gate appearance to find time for the
Dukakis parlay with Jesse Jackson. And at least one special
interest caucus got a Dukakis visit _ Hispanic congressmen.
   All business and no pleasure would make Mikey a dull boy. And so
interspersed amongst his convention events, Dukakis has found time
for his daily power walk (an exercise routine, no press coverage)
and for late-night family dinners.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Of course Dukakis hasn't got the only body in town. Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, the designated running mate, has a full plate of
delegation breakfasts and special interest caucuses.
   This is how Bentsen's body was being deployed on Tuesday:
   8 a.m. Salute to civil rights at Commerce Club.
   10:20 a.m. Meet with Texas Black Congressional Caucus.
   10:45 a.m. Brunch with Texas delegation.
   11:45 a.m. Tour Martin Luther King Center with Coretta Scott
King.
   7:30 p.m. Finance twilight supper.
   9:30 p.m. Network interviews at Hyatt.
   Presumedly, Bentsen doesn't mind pulling these chores. After
all, it's perfect training for the vice presidency.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jonathan Wolman is assistant bureau chief for
The Associated Press in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
