<DOCNO> AP880719-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 2006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     07-19 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wage Dispute Disrupts Mine in Silesia, Inflation Hits 56 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pay dispute disrupted a coal mine's
operations for two days, authorities said Tuesday, and the
government said retail price inflation reached 56.7 percent in the
first half of the year.
   Wages went up even more, by 63.8 percent, said the report
published in the government newspaper Rzeczpospolita. The increase
would put the national average wage on July 1 at the equivalent of
about $106 a month compared to $91 on Jan. 1.
   Workers in some plants struck in April and May for higher wages
to offset 27 percent price increases imposed in February. Since
then, both prices and wages have gone higher than the government
had planned.
   Official say they want to analyze economic statistics for the
first half of 1988 before starting new talks with official trade
unions on adjusting wage-and-price policy.
   In one instance of wage pressure, the state news agency PAP said
Tuesday that two days of labor-management talks over pay affected
output at the Boleslaw the Bold coal mine at Laziszka, near
Katowice in southern Poland.
   An official statement issued Tuesday after a Cabinet meeting
said: ``The principal goal for next year is to be the radical
reduction of inflation, which is now the most important single
factor standing in the way of increasing the efficiency of
industrial production in Poland.''
   Next to the statement, Rzeczpospolita published an interview
with government economist Erwin Plichcinski, in which he gave new
inflation figures.
   Plichcinski said the growth of wages faster than prices has set
off a ``worrying inflationary gap.''
   The 56.7 percent inflation for the first six months of 1988
exceeds initial projections for the entire year. Poland's central
annual plan projected growth in prices of 40-44 percent in 1988,
with wages planned to rise 36 percent. Prices rose 42 percent in
the first quarter alone.
   At Laziszka, some miners refused to work Saturday, prompting a
round of talks with management that evening, and the talks
continued Monday, PAP said.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said 800 of 980 miners refused
to work for several hours Monday. He said he had no details on the
number involved Saturday.
   He referred reporters to the PAP report when asked if the miners
received raises. The news agency said only that miners resumed work
after having ``accepted explanations and information presented to
them in the course of the meetings.''
   A spokesman for the state mining monopoly Polish Coal, speaking
on condition of anonymity, said the workers were promised higher
pay although negotiations were still going on. Miners now earn the
equivalent of $111-$133 a month.
   Urban also said a newspaper report on secret U.S. assistance to
Solidarity proves the banned trade union movement is not ``a Polish
force,'' and accused the United States of interfering in Polish
affairs.
   A July 10 report in the New York Times said the U.S. government
has secretly supported emigre efforts to smuggle printing
equipment, radio systems and video cassettes to opposition groups
in Poland. It said this was in addition to $2 million to Solidarity
openly appropriated by Congress.
   ``We view both these overt and covert actions by the U.S.
authorities as a significant manifestation of U.S. policy toward
Poland which stands in glaring contrast with the professed U.S.
principle of non-intervention in our internal affairs,'' Urgban
said.
   As for Solidarity, he said: ``Whoever receives a soldier's pay
from an alien power can neither define itself as an independent
force nor a Polish force.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
