<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-SAfrica     07-19 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-SAfrica,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Rejects Labor Leader's Call For South Africa Sanctions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mandela, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher affirmed her
opposition to sanctions against South Africa during an exchange
Tuesday in Parliament where shouting opponents labeled her a racist.
   ``If there were ever to be comprehensive sanctions on South
Africa, the number of people who would suffer, including children,
would be significantly greater,'' Mrs. Thatcher said to the
650-member House of Commons.
   The exchange came in a session of the twice-weekly Question
Time, where the prime minister fields questions and often insults
from legislators. Mrs. Thatcher said sanctions would devastate the
economies of the countries near South Africa.
   Those countries _ Angola, Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Botswana and
Zambia _ are dependent on South Africa to transport their goods and
have not imposed economic restrictions themselves, she said.
   Replying to a question from opposition leader Neil Kinnock, Mrs.
Thatcher said Britain already has invested $84 million in foreign
aid to the surrounding states and has further plans to reduce their
dependence on South Africa.
   Kinnock, leader of the Labor Party, said his visit to southern
Africa last week showed him that ``strong sanctions'' were needed
to end South Africa's system of apartheid.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks cannot vote on
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   Kinnock did not visit South Africa.
   ``The leaders of the front-line states call for sanctions,''
Kinnock told Mrs. Thatcher amid cheers from his party and jeers
from her governing Conservatives.
   ``Do you really think you know more about what needs to be done
than those who live daily with apartheid and its oppression? This
is not only a question of sense but a question of morality,''
Kinnock said.
   As rank-and-file Labor legislators shouted ``racist!'' and
``Nazi!'' at Mrs. Thatcher and the Conservatives, she replied:
   ``I totally disagree with you about sanctions, and unlike you
I'm not prepared to stand here comfortably in this house and impose
starvation on millions and millions of black South Africans and
black children.''
   South Africa's ambassador to Britain meanwhile defended the
imprisonment of Nelson Mandela, leader of the African National
Congress, who turned 70 on Monday.
   Speaking to a meeting of the Diplomatic and Commonwealth
Writers' Association in London, Ambassador Rae Killen said Mandela
could be released if he renounced violence. Mandela says South
Africa must first renounce apartheid.
   He has been imprisoned since 1962, first for inciting unrest and
later for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
