07-19 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Controller Election, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Traffic Controllers Elect First Union President Since 1981
Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Restores omitted time element 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air traffic controllers have elected their
first union president since the 1981 strike in which 11,400
controllers were fired and their old union destroyed.
   In balloting that stretched over several weeks, R. Steve Bell, a
controller from New York, was elected president of the new National
Air Traffic Controllers Association, according to an announcement
Tuesday.
   Bell, who was hired as a controller after the 1981 strike,
received 1,948 votes compared with 1,138 for his chief rival, Fred
Gilbert of Chicago. The union also selected a group of regional
representatives and other officers.
   All of the officers, including the president, were elected to
three-year terms.
   The National Air Traffic Controllers Association was formed last
year as a successor to the Professional Air Traffic Controllers
Association (PATCO), which went backrupt after its unsuccessful
1981 strike.
   The new union claims about 5,000 members, about 40 percent of
those eligible to join.
</TEXT>
