<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Hijack     07-19 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Hijack,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Concluded; Case Sent to Court for Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two surviving members of a family that tried to
hijack a passenger jet to the West were charged at the conclusion
of an investigation into the incident in which nine people were
killed, it was reported Tuesday.
   Igor Ovechkin and his sister, Olga, were charged with planning
and executing the March 8 hijacking during which a flight attendant
and three passengers were killed, the official Soviet news agency
Tass said.
   The family of hijackers originally included five brothers, Olga,
and their mother, Ninel Ovechkin. There were also at least four
children accompanying the adults, according to earlier press
reports.
   The hijackers seized an Aeroflot TU-154 en route from the
Siberian city of Irkutsk to Leningrad, via the Ural Mountain city
of Kurgan. The crew was ordered to fly to a West European city.
   The plane landed at a small airport near Vyborg, on the border
with Finland, and the hijackers set off an explosive device when
they realized they had landed within Soviet territory.
   ``Four of the brothers then committed suicide after first
shooting their mother dead at her request,'' Tass said.
   Security troops stormed the plane and arrested the survivors.
   Tass said that in addition to the loss of life, the Soviet state
suffered material damage amounting to nearly $2.2 million.
   Tass said the case was sent to court for trial.
</TEXT>
