<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Congress-Convention     07-19 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Congress-Convention,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Leaders Take Shots At Bush, Tout Own Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic congressional leaders took shots
Tuesday at Republican presidential contender George Bush, touted
their legislative record and promised an ``all-out war'' against
drugs.
   ``I want to show you what your Democratic Congress has done, and
how much more we can do with Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen in
the White House,'' House Speaker Jim Wright said in prepared
remarks to the Democratic National Convention.
   Democrats have dominated Congress for most of the past 35 years.
They last controlled both the White House and the legislative
branch in 1980. Reagan won the presidential election that year, and
the Republicans gained control of the Senate. The Democrats
reclaimed the Senate six years later.
   Wright rattled off a list of bills enacted by Congress over the
past 18 months, noting that two _ the clean water act and a highway
bill _ were passed over President Reagan's veto.
   He also pointed to legislation to give American workers 60 days'
notice of impending plant closings, the provision which Reagan
cited in vetoing a trade bill. Congress separated the plant
closings from the trade bill and sent both issues back to Reagan as
separate bills.
   ``Before this summer ends, we shall lead a strong initiative
against our most serious national problem _ illegal drugs,'' Wright
said, sounding a theme that has shown up in national polls as the
most ripe for political appeals. ``The Democratic Congress will
declare an all-out war on drugs.''
   Reagan's response to the drug problem has been the slogan,
``Just say no,'' Wright observed. ``It does little good ... when
the administration is unwilling to say `yes' to the funding
necessary to carry on the war.''
   House Democratic Whip Tony Coelho of California turned his guns
on Bush, seeking to emphasize what Democrats have come to call the
GOP nominee's ``wimp factor.''
   ``We're prepared to give George Bush the licking of his
political life,'' Coelho said, noting that Bush has spent most of
the Democratic Convention week a fishing spot in Wyoming with
Treasury Secretary James Baker III.
   Baker, who is expected to resign later this summer to head the
Bush campaign, is there ``just in case George is too squeamish to
bait his own hook,'' Coelho said.
   And he drew distinctions between the Democrats' Dukakis-Bentsen
ticket and Bush's candidacy.
   ``It is a race between two vastly different profiles in
leadership,'' he said. ``A race between a man of action and a man
of absence. Between a man with a noble purpose, and a man with a
noble pedigree. Between a miracle from Massachusetts with a real
Texas accent, and a fellow who wears cowboy boots over argyle
socks.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd of West Virginia took a more
philosophical tone, asserting that the Reagan administration
brought ``greed and arrogance'' to government and called for a
restoration of confidence.
   ``We must ... roll back the shadows that have gathered over this
administration _ the mistrust, the arrogance, the dark dealings,''
Byrd said. ``National policy cannot be made by wisecrack and
blunder.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
