<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Hightower scorns Bush, EMBARGOED for 9:30 pm EDT; Kennedy
remarks EMBARGOED for 9 pm; updates throughout this take</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis won the platform of his design
Tuesday at the Democratic National Convention while a parade of
Democrats ridiculed George Bush as a ``toothache of a man,'' and
worse. Jesse Jackson promised an emotional, late-night finale to
his remarkable primary campaign.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy said it was about time for another
president from Massachusetts and scorned Bush as a ``hear-nothing,
see-nothing, do-nothing vice president'' who ``wasn't there, or
can't recall, or never heard'' of the Iran arms sale.
   On that and other issues, Kennedy said, ``I think it's fair to
ask, where was George?''
   ``George Bush is the man who is never there _ and he won't be
there after the clock strikes noon on Jan. 20, 1989,'' the senator
said in a prepared address that kicked off the prime-time
speechmaking.
   Jim Hightower, the tart-tongued Texas agriculture commissioner,
called Bush a ``perpetual preppie,'' and said, ``He's a toothache
of a man, telling us to stay the course and threatening to lead us
from tweedledum to tweedledummer.''
   ``He is a man who was born on third base and thinks he hit a
triple,'' he said for good measure during what was billed as a
presentation of platform material.
   The verbal abuse came after an afternoon of platform work in
which Dukakis sought to shed the ``tax and spend'' Republican
taunt. He easily defeated Jackson's call for higher taxes on
wealthy individuals and corporations. The vote was 2,499 to 1,091.
   Dukakis prevailed as well on Jackson's call for a ``no first
use'' pledge of nuclear weapons. Jackson's call for
self-determination for Palestinians was debated and withdrawn.
Jackson forces took the inevitable defeats with equanimity; there
was little of the past emotion over Democratic ideals.
   Kennedy was introduced by his 27-year-old nephew, John F.
Kennedy Jr., son of the late president. ``For a long time I have
believed that what this country needs is another president from
Massachusetts,'' said the man who tried but failed to win the party
nomination in 1980.
   ``Now it's going to happen. President Dukakis, it has a nice
ring.''
</TEXT>
