<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CamarenaSlaying     07-19 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Camarena Slaying,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Gets Under Way In Drug Agent Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Mexicans went on trial Tuesday in the
abduction and killing a U.S. drug agent in 1985, and 124 potential
jurors said they could serve for the 12 weeks the judge estimated
the proceedings would take.
   The jurors who said they did not believe the lengthy trial would
be a hardship were from a group of 200 potential panelists crowded
into the courtroom of U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie amid
tight security.
   The potential jurors were handed a questionnaire asking, among
other things, about their exposure to publicity about the slaying
of Drug Enforcement Administration agent Enrique Camarena.
   Camarena was kidnapped and beaten to death shortly after he and
other agents uncovered a drug trafficking operation run by Rafael
Caro Quintero, who along with Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo was one of
Mexico's biggest drug kingpins, U.S. authorities have claimed in
court documents.
   Facing trial in federal court here are Raul Lopez Alvarez, 28,
Jesus Felix-Gutierrez, 38, and Rene Martin Verdugo Urquidez, 36,
who are charged in a seven-count indictment with either
participating directly in the kidnap-murder of Camarena or acting
as an accessory.
   U.S. Marshal Sam Cicchino imposed extra security, having
officers handcuff and shackle the defendants in the courtroom
whenever jurors left. Everyone entering the courthouse, including
federal employees, was required to pass through metal detectors.
   Camarena was kidnapped Feb. 7, 1985, as he left the U.S.
consulate in Guadalajara. Several weeks later his body and that of
his pilot, Alfredo Zavala-Avelar, who was kidnapped separately,
were found on a remote ranch 70 miles away.
   Camarena had been severely beaten, and documents filed on
autopsy reports in connection with the case said Camarena's jaw was
broken in several places and his head was shattered ``like an
eggshell.''
   Also charged in the case are Caro Quintero, 33; Fonseca
Carrillo, 65; Sergio Espino Verdin, 35; Armando Pavon Reyes, 35;
Albino Pazan Padilla, 27; and Ines Calderon Quintero, 33.
   Except for Calderon and Pavon, who remain at large, the other
defendants are being held by Mexican authorities. A trial has begun
in Mexico City, Assistant U.S. Attorney Jimmy Gurule said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
