<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     07-19 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Rebels Kill Seven Indian Soliders In Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil militants exploded a bomb under
a patrol car in northern Sri Lanka, killing five Indian soliders,
military officials said Tuesday. They said two soldiers and a rebel
died in another clash.
   Sri Lankan military officials, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules, said the five died Monday when the
remote-controlled bomb was detonated near the northwestern port of
Mannar. They said two soldiers were injured and five others were
reported missing in the blast.
   An official at the Indian High Commission, or embassy, confirmed
the five deaths. The official also insisted on anonymity.
   A statement issued in the southern India city of Madras by the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam militia claimed 20 soldiers were
killed in the blast. The Tigers, largest of the rebel groups, have
exile headquarters in Madras.
   The conflicting reports could not be resolved independently.
   Indian troops imposed an indefinite curfew on the area to search
for the missing men, the Sri Lankans said.
   Mannar is about 135 miles north of Colombo.
   On Tuesday, two Indian soldiers and a Tamil rebel were killed in
an exchange of fire near the port town of Batticaloa in eastern Sri
Lanka, the military officials said.
   More than 500 Indian soldiers have been killed since India sent
an estimated 50,000 soldiers to this island nation to enforce an
Indian-sponsored peace accord signed in July 1987.
   The accord was aimed at ending a five-year guerrilla war by the
Tamils for an independent homeland in the north and east of the
island.
   India became involved because 60 million ethnic Tamils in
southern India are sympathetic to the Tamil cause in Sri Lanka.
   Tamils, mainly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million population. They claim they are discriminated against by
the majority Buddhist Sinhalese. The Sinhalese control both the
military and the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
