<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Paraquat-Marijuana     07-19 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraquat-Marijuana,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Spray Paraquat on Wild Marijuana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEELER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials sprayed the herbicide paraquat
Tuesday to destroy marijuana on about 16 acres of private land, an
escalation in the federal drug war that environmentalists attacked
as dangerous.
   A Drug Enforcement Administration agent supervised spraying of a
remote area about six miles east of this small Panhandle town,
about 100 miles northeast of Amarillo, said Wheeler County Sheriff
Lonnie Miller.
   ``This is the first time that the DEA has been involved in a
spray'' on private land, said Phil Jordan, a Dallas-based DEA
supervisor. ``From what I understand, there have been some state
authorities that have eradicated before, but never with DEA.''
   Using four-wheel-drive vehicles and backpacks, authorities
sprayed paraquat on about 50,000 plants growing wild on six private
tracts, Miller said. The spraying was not done by aircraft to
protect the environment, Jordan said.
   The spraying was the beginning of a three-day federal Operation
Stop Crop, Texas Department of Public Safety spokesman Mike Cox
said.
   Last week, U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese said marijuana has
become the No. 1 cash crop in the United States and called for a
vast federal-state effort to eradicate the drug.
   Cox said the owners of the land involved had not cultivated the
marijuana and have cooperated fully with authorities. But he said
the county's wild marijuana, which apparently was planted years ago
to produce hemp for rope, had been discovered by ``entrepreneurs.''
   He said signs were posted to warn people of sprayed areas.
   Hank Graddy, national chairman of the Sierra Club's agricultural
committee, said spraying paraquat is risky even when done manually.
   ``If they are going to go to the trouble of walking the land, it
would seem to me that using a hatchet ... would be just as easy,''
Graddy said from his home in Midway, Ky.
   The Sierra Club, a private environmental group, maintains that
spraying paraquat is dangerous to humans and animals in the
vicinity. But much of the debate over paraquat has focused on
evidence that it poses serious health risks to marijuana smokers.
   The DEA issued a report in 1986 calling the toxic herbicide's
use to kill marijuana safe and reasonable as long as guidelines are
followed to avoid spraying in the rain or high wind or near
buildings, and to make sure the pot is not harvested before the
paraquat destroys it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
