<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Afghan 1stLd-Writethru   07-19 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Afghan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0697,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Deserter Returns to Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with Tass report arriving deserter in
Moscow. Picks up 4th pvs, ``I want ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Red Army deserter from the war in Afghanistan
went home to the Soviet Union after complaining in Canada of
homesickness, the Soviet Embassy in Ottawa said Tuesday.
   Nikolai Golovin, 25, left Montreal for Moscow on Monday on an
Aeroflot flight.
   Tass said he held a news conference after arriving in Moscow
Tuesday. The offical Soviet news agency quoted him as saying he
wanted to show ``nothing has happened to me after my return home.''
   Golovin was one of five Soviet soldiers who were captured and
held by Afghan rebels, then spirited out of Afghanistan by Canadian
officials in November 1986.
   Tass quoted Golovin as saying ``fear of possible punishment'' in
the Soviet Union is keeping his colleagues in Canada.
   He had been working part-time at a meat processing plant in
Kitchener, Ontario, but complained that he never felt at home in
Canada.
   ``I want to go back to where everyone speaks Russian,'' Golovin
said in an interview with the Kitchener-Waterloo Record. ``I just
can't get used to life here,'' he said in the interview published
Tuesday.
   Golovin said he wants to see his sister and ailing mother and to
find work as an electrician in his home town of Ulyanovsk, a city
on the Volga River 500 miles east of Moscow. He said his mother had
written to him begging him to come home, the Record said.
   When he first reached Canada, Golovin told reporters he could
never go back home. ``It would be Siberia or the firing squad,'' he
said.
   The five Red Army soldiers earlier rejected an initial offer to
return to the Soviet Union extended by Gennadi Samsonov, second
secretary of the Soviet Embassy. But the deserters received letters
from the embassy last month offering an amnesty, the Record
reported.
   Golovin's decision left his four comrades ``horrified'' and too
upset to talk, said Maria Blagoveshchensky of the Russian Aid
Society, which spent years working to secure their release.
   She said Vladislav Naumov, Vadim Plotnikov, Igor Kovalchuk and
Sergei Busov are working in Toronto and don't plan to leave Canada.
``It's very hard to believe a deserter will be welcomed with open
arms,'' she said.
</TEXT>
