<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 2128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Armada 1stLd-Writethru   07-19 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Armada, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0686,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>England's Beacon Party Remembers The Armada</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-8 UPDATE with beacons lighted, details. Picks up
9th graf pvs, Queen Elizabeth ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chain of beacons burst into flame across England
on Tuesday night in memory of the fiery warning to the nation when
the Spanish Armada was sighted exactly 400 years ago.
   Spanish Ambassador Don Jose de la Bellacasa, letting bygones be
bygones, used a long-handled, flaming torch to fire the first
beacon on a damp and drizzly night.
   ``Two old countries like ours have to build, on our history,
better understanding and friendship in the future,'' he told The
Associated Press.
   The event was shown live on national TV as the ambassador lit
the fuel in a big iron brazier atop an oak pole at the Kynance
headland. The area near Lizard village in the southwest tip of
Cornwall is where local people say the Armada was first sighted.
   The lighting was followed swiftly by the chain of beacons and
wigwam-shaped bonfires that extended to the Scottish border, 430
miles away.
   ``I invited the ambassador to light the first beacon because I
thought it was about time, after 400 years, that we buried this old
hatchet in a symbolic way,'' said Bruno Peek, who organized the
event and called it ``Fire Over England.''
   The Spanish Armada's 125 ships carried 19,000 soldiers, 8,000
sailors, 2,000 galley slaves and 180 monks and friars, sent by
Philip II, the Roman Catholic king of Spain, to overthrow England's
Protestant Queen Elizabeth I.
   Legend has it that Elizabeth's favorite captain, Sir Francis
Drake, was involved in a lawn-bowling game in Plymouth as the great
fleet approached and was so unflustered that he insisted on
finishing the game before going to his ship.
   Queen Elizabeth II is to visit Plymouth on Thursday to join
Armada festivities in the city from which Drake sailed into action.
   Everyone seemed to be in on the fun _ even the Post Office,
which issued 40 million stamps depicting galleons and cannon smoke.
   A breakfast cereal company offered ``Armada Treasure Replica
Coins.'' The replicas are copied from coins found in Armada ships
wrecked by gales as the great fleet struggled home after failing to
link up with a Spanish invasion army waiting in the Netherlands.
   Historians have argued long over whether the English or the
gales defeated the Armada.
   ``The weather did help but the defeat was a great victory for
England because it raised the hearts of men in dark hours,'' said
James Mildren, a historian specializing in Armada lore.
   Tamsin Thomas, responsible for 10 of Cornwall's 20 fires, said
the villagers in Lizard had been celebrating all day, as they have
done every anniversary for four centuries.
   She said the Kynance beacon, mounted on a 30-foot oak pole, had
a trial firing Tuesday morning and burned for an hour with a bright
orange flame.
   ``We are also having 2,000 pounds ($3,360 dollars) worth of
fireworks and I was astonished to find when we opened the boxes
that they were made in Spain,'' Mrs. Thomas said.
   Frank Kitchen, a schoolmaster who has studied the matter, said
the early-warning system of beacons and fires was unique to England
and could muster up to 30,000 men within two hours.
   He said the procedure lasted to the 19th century, when there was
a threat of invasion by Napoleon's armies, and there is a record of
one sentinel setting his beacon alight and frying sausages.
   ``In setting up the new beacons, we worked from secret
Elizabethan diagrams which showed pitch at the center, covered by
anything dry and combustible, topped by a thatch to keep out rain
and the whole thing covered with brushwood,'' said Warren Davis of
the National Trust, which looks after historic sites and buildings.
   ``The trick was to build a fire that would quickly produce a
flame at night and a lot of smoke in the daytime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880719-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 2136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0823 07-19 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0823,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Wounded, 270 Arrested as National Strike Turns Violent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Two grafs SUB for 3rd graf pvs, Also on ... UPDATING with
police confirmation of attack, CORRECTING attack site. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, The 48-hour ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police wounded five people and arrested
at least 270 protesters Tuesday when a nationwide general strike
flared into street clashes and induced leftist guerrilla violence,
officials and strike leaders said.
   Three of the wounded were strikers and two were children,
reports said.
   Also on Tuesday, rebels of the Maoist-oriented Shining Path
organization killed six police defenders and wounded five in an
attack against a police post in Pozuzo, a jungle town 170 miles
east of Lima, police said.
   The night before, officers reported, guerrillas shot dead a
policeman in the nearby town of Tochache.
   The 48-hour general strike began on Tuesday to protest
government economic policy.
   Strikers and student sympathizers blocked main arteries leading
into Lima with bonfires and rocks but were driven off by police
using tear gas and firing water cannons, reporters said. Police
quickly reopened the roads.
   Officers said a train carrying workers to their jobs in Lima
from Chosica, 25 miles away, was halted midway when saboteurs blew
up a small section of track. The train stopped in time and no one
was hurt.
   The communist-led General Confederation of Peruvian Workers said
80 percent of factories, stores and businesses in this capital city
were closed Tuesday.
   Lima Mayor Jorge del Castillo called the strike a failure and
said business activity was almost normal.
   Most banks and government offices in downtown Lima opened late
with about half their workers, the government said, and school
attendence was low. It blamed the absenteeism on an estimated 50
percent cut in bus transportation.
   About half the shops and stores in downtown Lima remained
shuttered.
   The confederation claims 90 percent of this Andean nation's 1.6
million unionized workers as members. It called the strike to
protest government austerity measures imposed this month that
include food price increases ranging from 20 percent to 100 percent.
   It is the third general strike against the 3-year-old government
of President Alan Garcia, a Social Democrat. The development comes
with the economy in a tailspin, a steep fiscal deficit and an
inflation rate estimated to hit 400 percent in 1988.
   The government declared the strike illegal and dispatched 8,000
police and army troops to patrol Lima and ride public buses to
ensure security.
   Police said 220 protesters were arrested in sporadic clashes in
Lima.
   In Huancayo, 125 miles east of Lima, 50 demonstrators were
arrested in a march and a 10-year-old boy was injured by a tear gas
cannister, police said.
   Strike leader Alberto Ramirez said police shot and wounded three
protesters and a child during a march in Juliaca, 600 miles
southeast of Lima. His charges could not be confirmed with police.
   Radio Programas, Peru's leading news station, said business
activity was greatly reduced in the key highland capitals of
Huancayo, Cuzco and Puno, while interstate trucking was virtually
halted nationwide.
   An indefinite strike by miners entered its second day Tuesday,
paralyzing most mining across the nation, strike officials said.
   Police said leftist guerrillas supporting the strike since
Monday exploded a car bomb in Lima, wounding three people, and
launched bomb attacks against buildings in other cities, but no
reports emerged of other injuries.
   Shining Path guerrillas blew up power pylons and blacked out
Ayacucho, 225 miles southeast of Lima.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
