<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Biaggi-Wedtech     07-19 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Ends in Four-Month Wedtech Corruption Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense rested in the Wedtech corruption
trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi and six others, ending 19 weeks of
testimony.
   Prosecutors, who did not call any rebuttal witnesses, were
slated to begin their closing statement to the jury Wednesday
morning at federal court in Manhattan.
   Biaggi, 70, a 10-term Bronx Democrat; former Bronx Borough
President Stanley Simon; and five others, including Biaggi's eldest
son, are charged with turning the Wedtech Corp. into a racketeering
enterprise that paid out millions of dollars in bribes to obtain
no-bid defense contracts.
   A now-bankrupt Bronx defense contractor, Wedtech grew from a
small machine shop into a $100 million concern through a Small
Business Administration program that awarded government contracts
to minority-owned businesses without competitive bidding.
   Prosecutors claimed Biaggi and other defendants extracted cash
or stock from Wedtech in return for political assistance.
   But the defense maintained that four corrupt Wedtech executives,
who testified for the government in exchange for leniency, had
links to Reagan White House insiders like Attorney General Edwin
Meese III and did not need help from Biaggi and Simon, both
Democrats.
   U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley denied a defense
request, however, to call Meese as a witness, saying his actions
had nothing to do with the guilt or innocence of those on trial.
Meese has not been charged with any wrongdoing.
   After the defense called its last witness, prosecutors decided
against putting on a rebuttal case after Motley ruled against them
on their request to present evidence to the jury about Biaggi's
conviction for obstructing justice in an unrelated case last fall
in Brooklyn.
   The trial, which began March 11 with opening arguments to the
jury, generated more than 18,000 pages of transcript from the
testimony of more than 130 witnesses.
   Biaggi, his son, Richard, and Bernard Ehrlich, the congressman's
former law partner, did not take the witness stand in their own
defense, but the other defendants did.
   Biaggi had intended to take the stand himself until Motley gave
prosecutors wide latitude to cross-examine the congressman about
his past including the Brooklyn case, which is under appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
