<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GuatemalanPrisoner     07-19 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemalan Prisoner,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Detained in Guatemala Arrives Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANTOWN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. resident returned safely Tuesday
from Guatemala, where she was imprisoned for 10 days and
interrogated by police as a suspected leftist guerrilla, a Roman
Catholic priest said.
   Maria Elena Gaspar Xuncax, 21, had disappeared earlier this
month after returning to her homeland for a visit.
   A teacher's aide who acted as her school's liaison to the
estimated 1,000 Guatemalan Indians living here, Ms. Gaspar told her
family in a frantic telephone call that she had been accused of
hijacking a bus two years ago even though she had been in the
United States since 1981.
   Her family immediately flew to Guatemala and won her freedom
with the help of the United Nations High Commission on Refugees.
   Ms. Gaspar traveled home alone Tuesday, and her family was
expected to follow her shortly, said the Rev. Frank O'Loughlin,
director of refugee services for the Roman Catholic diocese of Palm
Beach.
</TEXT>
