<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--JerryBrown     07-19 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Jerry Brown,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Says He's Not Left Out, Still Eyes Comeback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former California Gov. Jerry Brown said Tuesday
he still hopes to make a political comeback ``when there's an
opportunity ... (and) if it's appropriate.''
   The 50-year-old former governor made a brief appearance before
the California delegation to the Democratic National Convention to
help launch the 1990 campaign for state treasurer of his sister,
Kathleen.
   But Brown said he would probably make few, if any, other public
appearances this year because he is concentrating on completing a
book on his political experiences and his views of future political
directions of the nation. He has spent much of the last few years
traveling abroad.
   His brief and low-key appearance contrasted sharply with 1976,
when the then-38-year-old governor was the final presidential
contender to withdraw from the race and endorse Jimmy Carter's
successful candidacy.
   Brown, who gave up the governor's office in 1982 after two terms
for an unsuccessful campaign for the U.S. Senate, said ``it's
possible'' he might run for the U.S. Senate in 1992 if Democrat
Alan Cranston retires.
   Asked whether he might run for governor again, he replied, ``you
shouldn't un-expect it,'' but said that shouldn't be construed as a
trial balloon or announcement.
   ``It's kind of hard to be in it (public office) 12 or 13 years,
and be known by 95 percent of the people and know all the players
and be used to that kind of life and not do it. You actually have
to work at it,'' Brown said.
</TEXT>
