<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--JFKJr 1stLd-Writethru a0659 07-19 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--JFK Jr, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0659,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>JFK's Son Makes Political Debut At Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with speech delivered, ovation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John F. Kennedy Jr., who has avoided publicity in
the years since his father's assassination, jumped into the
national political spotlight Tuesday by introducing his uncle,
Massachusetts Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, at the Democratic National
Convention.
   The 27-year-old law student, who is still remembered by many
Americans as the brave 3-year-old saluting his slain father,
received a two-minute standing ovation as he appeared before the
delegates.
   ``So many of you came into public service because of him,''
young Kennedy told the cheering crowd during the prime-time TV
appearance. ``In a very real sense, because of you, he is with us
still.''
   ``I'm not a political leader, but I can speak for those of my
age who've been inspired by Teddy to give their energy and their
ideas to their community and not just themselves,'' Kennedy said of
his uncle. ``He has shown that our hope is not lost idealism but a
realistic possibility.''
   The appearance has prompted speculation over whether the son of
John F. Kennedy will be the next member of the new generation of
Kennedys to enter the family business of politics.
   ``I think he'll be involved in public affairs one way or the
other in the future, not necessarily running for office,'' the
senator said earlier this week. ``I think he'll use his talents to
try to make some sort of contribution.''
   The senator said it was his idea _ not John's _ to have his
nephew speak before the convention. Kennedy said he received ``an
instantaneous positive reaction'' from his nephew.
   John Kennedy, a graduate of Brown University, is a third-year
law student at New York University.
   Young Kennedy has fought to keep his life private _ ``He simply
does not do interviews,'' said Kennedy spokeswoman Melody Miller _
but is often portrayed as a heartthrob in tabloid photos.
   The uncle and nephew are but two of many Kennedys attending the
convention.
   Sen. Kennedy's youngest son, Patrick, a Providence College
student who is running for the Rhode Island House of
Representatives, is a Dukakis delegate from Rhode Island. Also here
are the senator's other two children, Teddy Jr. and Kara, who are
running his re-election campaign in Massachusetts.
   Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, the oldest daughter of the late
Robert F. Kennedy and an unsuccessful congressional candidate in
1986, is a Dukakis delegate from Maryland.
   Her brother, Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II of Massachusetts, is also
here, as are brother Michael and sisters Kerry and Courtney Kennedy
Ruhe. Also on hand: cousins from the Lawford, Smith and Shriver
families.
</TEXT>
