<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0716 07-19 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Tries to Sell Texans on Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs bgng, `Texas is,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with Kemp as favored opponent; SUBS last graf pvs with 2 grafs to
reflect revised travel schedule</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, showing success in selling
himself to Jesse Jackson and other black leaders, switched hats
Tuesday and worked to sell Texans on Michael Dukakis.
   ``Here we have running on the ticket a man from New England, a
governor from New England,'' Bentsen told Texas delegates he hosted
for brunch.
   ``But you know he talks the same language we talk in Texas,
because he talks the language of jobs, and growth, and housing and
health care, and education for all of the people,'' he said.
   Economic growth is a campaign theme of one of Vice President
George Bush's possible running mates, Rep. Jack Kemp of New York.
But Bentsen said Tuesday night he'd rather run against Kemp than
the other lawmaker frequently mentioned for Bush's ticket,
Bentsen's Senate colleague and friend Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   Kemp, a longtime supporter of supply-side economics, was
``extremely vulnerable'' to criticism, Bentsen said in an interview
on CNN Tuesday night.
   Bentsen used the theme of economic growth at length before his
home-state gathering. Texas is considered a major campaign
battleground this year and was a big reason Bentsen was chosen for
the ticket was to win that state.
   Bentsen said Texas has ``taken a hit'' economically during the
Reagan administration, and he said Dukakis was a man who can help
create jobs and who believed that ``government can be of help'' in
restoring the economy.
   The room was filled with people wearing Bentsen buttons,
including many who had supported Jackson. Rep. Mickey Leland,
Jackson's state chairman in Texas, was on the dais with Bentsen and
helped lead the applause.
   But some Jackson delegates were still disappointed that Dukakis
had not chosen their candidate instead of Bentsen. State Rep. Al
Edwards of Houston, invited to sit at the head table, did not
attend.
   ``I have no problem with Senator Bentsen, but right now I'm
campaigning for Jackson,'' Edwards said. ``I'm sure before it's
over we'll sit at a lot of head tables together.''
   Bentsen was not confronted Tuesday by the Jackson placards which
greeted him Monday when he began his series of meetings with state
delegations. And he received his strongest endorsement yet from
Jackson.
   Jackson, Dukakis and Bentsen appeared at a civil rights
breakfast together, and afterward, Jackson told The Associated
Press that Bentsen had demonstrated to him a sensitivity for
minorities. Jackson had not previously spoken much about Bentsen
since Dukakis selected his running mate last week.
   When Jackson and Dukakis made a campaign unity pact Monday,
Bentsen was called in and then joined the others at a news
conference.
   ``What was significant was his perception, his understanding of
what had to be done to broaden the base for inclusion,'' Jackson
said.
   ``Coming out of Texas where you have to reach out to become a
U.S. senator, you necessarily have to deal with the blacks, browns,
the farmers and ranchers, the workers,'' Jackson said. ``Your
orientation becomes inclusive and expansive because it is the only
way to win. And the way he relates ... is indicative of his
experience.''
   Bentsen praised Jackson as someone who ``has acted more on his
own for the cause of freedom and justice, more than the Reagan
administration has been able to achieve in the last eight years.''
   The Texan also received a warm welcome Tuesday at a noontime
rally with Dukakis and Coretta Scott King, widow of slain civil
rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., at the Martin Luther King
Center.
   Dukakis highlighted Bentsen's long civil rights record. ``He was
one of two Southern congressmen who voted against the poll tax in
1949,'' he said.
   Much of Bentsen's day was spent in private meetings, preparing
for his acceptance speech Thursday night and organizing a campaign
staff for the months ahead.
   Dukakis and Bentsen planned to leave Atlanta together Friday for
Houston as the first stop in a three-day cross-country swing to
launch their campaign.
   From Texas, the candidates will travel to California, then to
North Dakota and Missouri on Saturday. They'll visit Missouri and
Pennsylvania on Sunday before Dukakis returns to Boston on Sunday
evening. It was still being decided whether Bentsen would go to
Boston with Dukakis or return to Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
