<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WildfiresRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0821 07-19 0891</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0821,0910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wyoming Fire Close to Yellowstone; Alaska Fires Allowed to Burn</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Calif. crew forced to take
refuge from fire, delete outdated reference to all fires in Oregon
being contained, picking up 4th graf pvs `The northern...'. SUBS
final graf to add detail on new Oregon fire.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SC4, GJ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE BUCKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews used natural barriers to keep a 14,000-acre wildfire in
Wyoming's Teton Wilderness from reaching summer homes Tuesday,
while officials in Alaska left fires that have charred more than a
half-million acres to die on their own.
   Firefighters in northwestern Colorado got a little break in the
weather, which helped contain all but two of 15 fires that consumed
more than 20,000 acres of range and pinon juniper. Fires also
burned Tuesday in California, Utah and Oregon, but none threatened
populated areas and most were small.
   A blaze swept over a firefighting crew near Jackson, Calif.,
about 45 miles southeast of Sacramento, but the workers surivived
by taking refuge in portable fireproof shelters, said Karen
Terrill, a spokeswoman for the California Department of Forestry.
   The northern edge of the lightning-sparked fire in Wyoming was
closing in on Yellowstone National Park, but was allowed to burn
since it's on U.S. Forest Service land and not a threat. However,
550 firefighters used natural firebreaks like streams and rock
formations to keep the southern border of the fire from reaching a
small colony of summer homes in Buffalo Valley, 12 miles away.
   Officials said unless heavy rains fall soon, it's likely the
fire will burn until snow puts it out no later than September.
   In Alaska, five major fires accounted for almost 450,000 acres
of the total. Nearly a third went up in a blaze near Livengood,
about 60 miles northwest of Fairbanks, said U.S. Bureau of Land
Management spokeswoman Sue Mitchell.
   Rugged territory in the Wyoming fire, at an elevation of about
8,500 feet and in prime grizzly bear habitat, has complicated
firefighting.
   ``We're not only shuttling crews (by helicopter) to the
fireline, but during the day we're moving the crews around,'' Fire
Information Officer Doug Huntington said Tuesday. ``Normally they
would be able to walk from point to point, but because of the
rugged terrain and downed timber ... we're moving the crews around.
If we don't do that, they're worn out by the time they arrive on
the spot where they're supposed to be fighting the fire.''
   The crews have little more than picks, shovels and the water
tanks they carry on their backs to fight the flames.
   In Yellowstone, to the north of the Teton Wilderness, officials
monitored several fires covering 11,000 acres.
   While all Yellowstone's roads and front-country campsites were
open, campfire restrictions were imposed throughout the park's
back-country, where fire danger forced the closing of some
campsites.
   Alaska officials generally let the fires burn unless they
threaten lives or property, critical wildlife habitat or commercial
timber, said Tom Frey, fire coordinator for the Alaska Fire Service.
   The fires open up dense stands of unproductive black spruce,
said Frey. Natural revegetation of burned areas with willow, grass
and berries provides food for many of Alaska's big game species.
Animals usually move away from the flames well before they are
endangered, and few die in the fires.
   Yellowstone officials also tend to let fires burn themselves out.
   ``We've had several questions on that, and the majority are
probably coming from some local guides and outfitters,'' said
Yellowstone fire information officer Doug Huntington. ``They're for
a good reason concerned that this fire would destroy some prime
habitat where they take hunters in for big game hunts, and packers
in for some hikes.''
   The Forest Service held a public meeting in Jackson to let the
outfitters and guides discuss their concerns and so the agency can
explain its fire management decisions, Huntington said.
   The low humidity and dry brush fueled the Colorado fires, which
caused no structural damage despite threatening the town of
Dinosaur and the headquarters of Dinosaur National Monument on
Sunday.
   Only one injury was reported, on Tuesday, when a firefighter at
the Flatiron fire near Rifle got cinders in his eyes. Fire
information officer Larry Dove said the man was treated at a local
hospital and released.
   The Colorado fires were being fueled by dry brush, high
temperatures and low humidity, officials said.
   In Northern California, fires that apparently had been set were
contained Monday and early Tuesday, but not before destroying a
home and two other buildings in Jackson.
   And in southern California, an all-out air and ground assault by
1,000 firefighters went a long way toward extinguishing a
3,500-acre wildfire in Los Padres National Forest.
   Five water-dropping helicopters and three air tankers bombarding
flames with fire retardant chemicals helped ground crews in their
extensive effort to halt the three-day blaze, said David Schreiner
of the U.S. Forest Service.
   The Utah fires were reported in Rich County and on the
Uintah-Ouray Indian Reservation and crews were mopping up an
88-acre fire on Diamond Mountain in eastern Utah.
   Oregon firefighters stopped a 27-acre fire on Tuesday, but a new
fire broke out about 20 miles northeast of Prineville and, whipped
by strong afternoon winds, spread across at least 25 acres of pine
forest, said state Forestry Department spokesman Doug Decker.
</TEXT>
