<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 2336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Amnesty     07-19 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Amnesty,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty International Details Egyptian Torture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International called on Egypt Wednesday to
protect political detainees who claim they were beaten with cables
and whips, given electric shocks and burned with cigarettes while
in detention.
   The international human rights organization said evidence it
compiled since 1981 indicated a continuing pattern of torture by
security and other officials working in Egyptian prisons and
detention centers.
   In June, 44 security, prison and police officials accused of
torturing political prisoners from 1981-83 were acquitted after a
trial in Cairo. Former detainees identified some of them as their
torturers, Amnesty International said in a statement.
   The group said in a 50-page report that its evidence of the
beatings, shocks and burns comes from interviews with victims and
from medical reports by the Egyptian Justice Ministry's forensic
medicine department. Doctors examining detainees who said they were
tortured found in many cases physical scarring consistent with the
complaints.
   Many reports of torture followed the arrest of thousands of
political suspects after the attempted assassinations in May and
August last year of two former interior ministers, Maj. Gen. Hassan
Abu Basha and Maj. Gen. Nabawi Ismail, and magazine editor Makram
Muhammed Ahmed, the group said.
   Most of those arrested were supporters of Islamic groups, and
said they were blindfolded and could not identify their torturers ,
it said.
   An Amnesty official attended part of the 18-month-long Cairo
trial.
   The organization said it is still assessing the trial outcome,
but that it did not want the acquittals to signify an end to
efforts by Egypt to end torture of political prisoners.
   The report was written after two missions to Egypt and extensive
talks with government officials there, the group said.
   The report recommended structural reforms within the country,
noting that Egypt's state of emergency has facilitated prolonged
detention.
   The state of emergency began after the 1981 assassination of
President Anwar Sadat by Islamic fundamentalists.
   Egypt was among the first six countries to become party to a
United Nations convention against torture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
