<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Amnesty-Israel     07-19 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty-Israel,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Says Israeli Officials Tolerate Shootings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International said Tuesday that high Israeli
officials have ``tolerated if not encouraged'' the use of firearms
against Palestinian demonstrators and expressed concern that ``so
few'' cases are investigated.
   The London-based human rights group said bullets fired by
Israeli soldiers killed at least 160 Palestinians, including women
and 55 people under age 18, in the occupied territories.
   According to U.N. figures Tuesday, 225 Palestinians and four
Israelis died in the Palestinian uprising in the occupied
territories since it began Dec. 8.
   Amnesty said in a statement released by its Rome office that it
asked Israel for a clarification on its policy and information on
investigations in the killing of Palestinians by the Israeli army.
   ``On the basis of available evidence, Israeli authorities at
high levels tolerated if not encouraged the ill considered and
excessive use of firearms,'' Amnesty said in the statement.
   It also said it was very concerned that ``few cases have been
the object of investigation.''
   Amnesty asked Israel to explain the directives in force on the
use of firearms and to provide the number of cases in which a
serious and thorough investigation was opened into the killing of a
Palestinian.
   The group also asked Israel to explain how it reached its
conclusions in investigations already completed, and to say if or
when members of the Israel army were tried or disciplined for
killing a Palestinian demonstrator.
</TEXT>
