<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HeatRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0755 07-19 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heat Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0755,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steamy Weather Strains Utilities; Death Toll Hits 43</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 10th graf `The two' to UPDATE with West
Coast power shortage, record highs in California, Oregon,
Washington. Picks up 11th graf pvs `The suffering...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Humidity steamed through the South on Tuesday, forcing power
companies to plead for customers to conserve, while residents of
the Midwest and Northeast got some relief from changing weather
patterns and a bank's fan giveaway.
   ``This miserable hot weather has got air conditioners running
full blast,'' said Joseph Maher, a Duke Power Co. spokesman in
North Carolina.
   A cold front moving slowly east from the Great Lakes region and
widespread rain from the Plains to the Gulf Coast moderated
temperatures for much of the nation, the National Weather Service
said. But a strong upper-level high pressure system anchored over
northern California drove inland temperatures well above 100
degrees.
   Detroit officials blamed the weekend deaths of two men on the
heat, bringing the national toll of heat-related deaths to at least
43 since June 1.
   Officials in St. Louis County called off a heat warning after
rain fell and temperatures moderated Tuesday, but not before an
elderly woman and a 63-year-old man were found dead in sweltering
homes.
   Overcast skies and scattered showers brought cooler temperatures
to the Boston area, ending three days of intense heat and stifling
humidity. The high temperature at Logan Airport Tuesday was 77,
compared with low 90s over the weekend.
   Temperatures in the 90s for the past week across much of North
Carolina prompted Duke Power Co. and Carolina Power and Light Co.
to implement conservation programs.
   Duke asked customers to turn up thermostats 4 to 5 degrees, stop
running appliances and otherwise curtail power use until 8 p.m.
Tuesday because the demand for electricity was expected to exceed
the supply.
   ``The company is also reducing voltage throughout its
20,000-square-mile service area today,'' said power supply manager
Walter Campbell in a statement, adding that the voltage reduction
could result in dimming of television sets and slower operation of
appliances.
   The two utilities had cut off service to some industrial
customers for an hour to an hour and a half on Monday amid record
power demand.
   Power demands also reached an all-time high in California's
Central Valley, and Pacific Gas & Electric Co. officials asked
customers to stop running major appliances from noon to 6 p.m. The
temperature in Redding, Calif., reached 116, breaking a 42-year-old
record by 3 degrees, and in Red Bluff, Calif., it was 115, beating
the 1931 record by 1 degree.
   In Eureka on the cool northern California coast, the 71-degree
reading was enough to beat the 5-year-old record by 3 degrees.
   In Washington, Seattle had a record high for the date of 95
degrees, and Quillayute on the Olympic Peninsula hit 97, a record
for the month of July.
   It reached 109 degrees in Medford, Ore., 2 degrees hotter than
the record for the date set in 1946. Other Oregon records included
Astoria, 93, 4 degrees hotter than the 1956 record; and Eugene,
102, 1 degree hotter than the 1946 record.
   The suffering produced by hot weather was brought home to St.
Paul, Minn., bank executive Mark Sheffert when his air conditioner
broke. Now, First Bank System is handing out _ and delivering, if
necessary _ 10,000 fans to the elderly and disabled and people with
young children.
   ``I just kept thinking about the people who had no relief from
the heat,'' said Sheffert, First Bank System's executive vice
president. ``I figured there must be something we can do.''
   He said the bank bought the fans for about $200,000 from Sears,
Roebuck and Co. and had them shipped from Pennsylvania on eight
trucks.
   ``I think this is a wonderful gesture on the part of the bank,''
said Sarah LeMire, 81, who got a fan for her eighth-floor
apartment. ``We've had some awfully hot days.''
   Since June 1, deaths blamed on the heat numbered at least 5 in
Kentucky, 4 in Kansas, 2 in Michigan, 24 in Missouri, 3 in Illinois
and 5 in Georgia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
