<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, July 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Leaders Seek To Safeguard Religious Liberty Guarantees</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broad cross-section of American leaders says a
distinctive hallmark of the nation _ free, non-established religion
_ is threatened by modern battling over it.
   They've sought to stake out some common ground to protect that
principle of religious liberty.
   In the conflicts, the pendulum was described as having swung in
American history from one pole to another _ from religious to
secular semi-establishments.
   But the standard is set by Constitution's First Amendment:
``Congress shall make no law regarding an establishment of
religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereoff.''
   In the shifting applications of these doubled-edged clauses,
controversy lately has ballooned and confusion multiplied about
relationships of church and state, faith and politics.
   The issue has frayed political campaigns and engulfed the
courts. More lawsuits about it have landed in the U.S. Supreme
Court in the last 25 years than in all the nation's previous
history.
   The ``controversies over religion in public life pose both a
danger and an opportunity,'' says an unusual, new document, the
Williamsburg Charter, backed by a wide spectrum of religious,
academic, business and political leaders.
   Citing dangers either of forcing religion out of public affairs
or, in reaction, politicizing faith for laws to establish a
``Christian America,'' the charter calls for a ``renewed national
compact'' about it.
   Social scientist Os Guinness of Washington, D.C., head of the
project, says ``any sense of shared agreement about the place of
religion and politics has broken down.''
   He says ``recurring conflicts and the flood of cases about
textbooks, prayer, abortion, and an infinite number of things''
will intensify unless there is a process for restored consensus.
   ``It's important not just to religion but to democracy,'' he
said in an interview. ``Without it, there's danger down the line.''
   He described the new charter, already endorsed by about 150
national leaders in various fields and expected to be signed by
many others in state meetings this fall, as like the ``Queensbury
Rules'' that restrained boxing from sheer destructiveness.
   ``It sets forth the place of religion in public life _ that's
the heart of it _ and also guiding principles by which people of
different religions or none can debate and contend robustly but
with civility,'' he said.
   The 6,000-word charter says the constitution's ``religious
liberty provisions hold the key to American distinctiveness and
American destiny.''
   The guaranteed rights depend on recognition that ``they are
neither given by the state, nor can they be taken away by the
state,'' but are inherent in belief in the ``inviolability of the
human person,'' the charter says.
   It says the meaning of those provisions is ignored whenever
``the logic of arguments favors either an unwarranted intrusion of
religion into public life or an unwarranted exclusion of religion
from it.''
   Until well into the 20th century, the charter says that there
was a ``de facto semi-establishment'' of a generalized
Protestantism, especially in the public schools.
   But now, the tendency was seen as swinging the other way
``toward the de facto semi-establishment of a wholly secular
understanding'' of humanity and public institutions.
   The charter aims at mapping a middle course between the secular
left, which has worked to push religion out of public life, and the
religious right, which wants religious premises to predominate.
   The document, drawn up by the Williamsburg Charter Foundation, a
private, public-policy organization funded by individuals and
corporations, has gained an impressive array of backers.
   They include present and former chief justices, the chairmen of
the Republican and Democratic National Committees, Congress
members, corporate executives, educators and various faith leaders,
evangelical and mainline.
   However, it so far hasn't gained support of some aggressive
antagonists such as the American Civil Liberties Union, which
opposes religion in the public sphere, and Moral Majority, which
wants them prevailing there.
   The charter says religion too often is dimissed as a ``purely
private matter,'' but this ignores the fact that the American
system depends on ``ultimate beliefs, for otherwise we have no
right to the rights'' it upholds.
   The First Amendment guarantee of no interference with religion
puts ``religious expression on an equal footing with all other
forms of expressing in genuinely public forums,'' the charter says.
   It says that some in recent disputes have ``insisted that any
evidence of religious influence on public policy represents an
establishment of religion and is therefore precluded...
   ``Such exclusion of religion from public life is historically
unwarranted, philosophically inconsistent and profoundly
undemocratic...Many of the most dynamic social movements in
American history, including that of civil rights, were legitimately
inspired and shaped by religious motivation.''
   However, the document criticizes religionists who ``bring to
politics a misplaced absoluteness that idolizes politics,
`Satanizes' their enemies and politicizes their own faith.''
   In the conflict, participants often have been acrimonious and
unfair, the charter says, urging greater balance, mutual respect
and civility.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, July 22</NOTE>
