<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, July 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TUPELO, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the American Family Association
says Universal Pictures will be committing ``financial suicide'' if
it releases the movie, ``The Last Temptation of Christ.''
   The Rev. Donald E. Wildmon, executrive director of AFA, says he
sent copies of the script to 200 top Christian officials and those
who have read it are appalled.
   ``It is absolutely the most perverted, distorted account of the
historical and biblical Jesus I have ever read,'' says Wildmon, a
United Methodist minister.
   Thew movie, based on a novel by Nikos Kazantzakis, was scheduled
to be released this fall.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the face of drought across mid-America, Bishop
Herbert W. Chilstrom, head of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America, urges prayers in all its congregations that God ``send
rain to the thirsty ground.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Jewish Congress says a Hawaii law
recognizing Good Friday as a legal holiday violates the
Constitutions's ban against establishing religion.
   The friend-of-court brief was filed with the federal appeals
court after a U.S. district court in Hawaii had upheld the holiday,
saying it gave residents a needed day of rest to do as they chose.
   The day commemorates the crucifixion of Christ.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Salvation Army has honored President
Reagan for his leadership in encouraging voluntary, private efforts
to help the needy.
   At a White House cerermony, he was presented with the Army's
``Others Award,'' saying his ``leadership has encouraged
voluntarism and private sector initiative to the benefit of others
in all parts of our society.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Gallup survey conducted shortly after
Nancy Reagan was reported to consult an astrologist found that 80
per cent of Americans do not believe in astrology.
   The poll of l,204 adults found that only 12 percent believe that
movement of heavily bodies influence human events, while 8 percent
said they don't know.
   However, 25 percent of Americans regularly read astrology
columns, although they're considerably more skeptical about it than
in 1978, when 29 percent said they believed in it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relics have been returned to the Russian Orthodox
Church from state museums in the Kremlin, including relics of the
apostle Andrew, George the dragon slayer and John the Baptist, the
Soviet news agency Tass reports.
   Also included was material venerated as part of the cross on
which Jesus was crucified, the robes of Jesus' mother and the
Gospel writers Mark and Matthew, and the stone used to seal Jesus'
tomb.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-year agreement has been signed between
the United Methodist Board of Global Ministries and a newly formed
employees' association covering 193 non-executive staff members.
   The agreement, which replaces a union agreement, provides for a
pay increase of 7 percent this year, 6 percent in 1989 and 5
percent in 1990.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Causing damage to religious property or
interfering with a person's free exercise of religion is now a
federal crime under a law recently approved by Congress and signed
by President Reagan.
   It makes those who engage in interstate activity to damage
religious property because of its religious character or obstruct
by force or threat anyone's free exercise of religion subject to
fines and prison sentences.
   In debate on the legislation, members of Congress pointed to
increased incidents of religious violence and vandalism. Sen. Paul
Simon, D-Ill., said, ``Congress is sending a clear signal that the
desecrations, the injuries, the deaths are intolerable in a free
society such as ours.''
</TEXT>
