<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   07-19 0854</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0887</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At The Movies: ``Short Circuit 2,'' ``A Summer Story''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Short Circuit 2''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   In a summer that delivered an army of dwarfs and an extremely
charming rabbit to movie theaters, one might wonder whether a
talking robot is a little much.
   No way! ``Short Circuit 2,'' a sequel to the original of a few
seasons back, is a sweet surprise package that will charm your
socks off.
   Its star is unquestionably a robot, but never has a hunk of
metal been quite so adorable.
   If you remember the first, ``Short Circuit,'' the creature
dubbed ``Number Five'' was invented as a tool of war. But the robot
was struck by lightning, reprogrammed itself and escaped from the
military.
   ``Number Five is alive!'' said promos for the first movie.
   Now, two years later, the robot has taken a human name _ Johnny
Five _ and his adventurous spirit craves ``input,'' information on
the world around him.
   Meanwhile, his inventor, Ben Jahrvi, an Indian who speaks
Malaprop, has fallen on hard times. Fired from the military, the
inventor, played by Fisher Stevens, has taken to selling miniature
Johnny Fives on streetcorners. A department store buyer falls in
love with the toys, orders 1,000 of them and the plot is off and
running.
   When Johnny Five is shipped to the big city to help with toy
production, the country-bred robot's circuits get overloaded with
``input.'' Adventures abound. Johnny Five gets involved with street
hoodlums and bank robbers and becomes the intermediary in a love
affair. He gets mugged, hugged and spray painted with graffiti. And
he tries on an array of colorful outfits seeking his own fashion
image.
   When he's pushed out the window of a 34-story skyscraper, Johnny
Five has a magical way out. After all, this is a fairy tale. The
gleaming backdrop, by the way, is Toronto.
   In various action scenes, Johny Five flies, swings from a crane,
and dizzily spins two villains who intrude upon the toy factory.
   Johnny Five is supported by some able human actors. In addition
to Stevens as the addled Jahrvi, there's Michael McKean as a
small-time hustler whose baser instincts are reformed by Johnny
Five's friendship. The always amusing Jack Weston is a sneaky
villain named Oscar.
   Kenneth Johnson's direction of the script by S.S. Wilson and
Brent Maddock keeps things moving at a breathtaking pace and
focuses always on the man of the hour _ our iron-clad Superman.
   ``Short Circuit 2'' is rated PG , presumably for some fairly
mild language and violence (to a robot?). Take the kids by all
means.
   _^By Linda Deutsch, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``A Summer Story''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``A Summer Story'' is a sad, beautiful romance of human choices
and regrets, and of how love sometimes fails to overcome
differences between people.
   Set in the gorgeous Devon countryside just after the turn of the
century, the film focuses on upper-class Londoner Frank Ashton
(James Wilby), who is spending a holiday trekking through the moors
when he twists his ankle.
   While recovering, he rents a room in a farmhouse, where he soon
falls in love with the incredibly pretty Megan, a farm girl
portrayed by film newcomer Imogen Stubbs of the Royal Shakespeare
Company.
   Ashton's presence is resented by farm owner Mrs. Narracombe
(Susannah York) and by her son, Joe (Jerome Flynn), who long has
hoped to marry Megan.
   After a few idyllic and clandestine midnight meetings, the young
lovers must part, although Ashton promises to return to fetch Megan.
   The outcome of this romance is influenced by the social class
boundaries so rigid in England before World War I. But the choices
Ashton faces also deal with timeless issues of commitment,
responsibility and free will.
   Directed by Piers Haggard, ``A Summer Story'' is being shown in
theaters only in Los Angeles, New York and perhaps up to 50 other
big cities. It is a quiet film unlikely to attract the mass
audience drawn by blockbusters and adventure movies.
   But it belongs to a too often overlooked class of films that
deal with real people and genuine human emotions _ films that touch
the heart and the brain rather than blast the eardrums.
   Penelope Mortimer's screenplay is based on ``The Apple Tree,'' a
classic romance story written in 1916 by John Galsworthy, the
British author best known for his ``Forsyte Saga'' trilogy.
   ``A Summer Story,'' released by Atlantic Entertainment Group,
was produced by Danton Rissner. It is rated PG-13, with adult
themes and some sex and nudity. Running time: 95 minutes.
   _^By Lee Siegel, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
