<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After earning close to $33 million last year
when it was re-released to movie houses, Walt Disney's
``Cinderella'' is bibbidy bobbidi booing its way to home screens in
the fall.
   The $26.99 videocassette will join other Disney classics for
small-screen consumption, including ``The Wind in the Willows,''
``Mary Poppins'' and ``Dumbo.''
   Disney Home Video hopes the beautifully animated film will soar
past sales figures for its best-selling ``Lady and the Tramp''
video, which has sold 3.2 million copies.
   Released in 1950, the 75-minute feature was nominated for two
Academy Awards, including best song for ``Bibbidy Bobbidi Boo.''
   Also out this fall from Orion Home Video is a series of
contemporary foreign film classics, including Claude Berri's
award-winning ``Jean de Florette,'' which won four British
``Oscars'' including best film, and its sequel ``Manon of the
Spring.''
   And if you want to know what videos certain celebrities like to
watch, V magazine has polled a few and provides these nuggets in
its July issue:
   _ Robin Williams, ``Dr. Strangelove or How I Learned to Stop
Worrying and Love the Bomb.''
   _ Dudley Moore, ``It's a Wonderful Life.''
   _ Billy Crystal, ``The Godfather.''
   _ Patti Labelle, ``Imitation of Life.''
   _ Chuck Norris, anything starring John Wayne.
   _ Christopher Walken, ``Spartacus.''
   Films reviewed this week: ``Full Metal Jacket'' and ``Forever,
Lulu.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Full Metal Jacket''@ (Warner Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95;</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rated R)
   
   Stanley Kubrick was at a disadvantage when ``Full Metal Jacket''
hit the nation's movie screens last summer. Oliver Stone's
``Platoon'' had already nabbed Academy Awards, including best
picture, and helped galvanize a nation around the haunting
reminders of a terrifying time.
   Other Vietnam War movies also had floated by: Francis Coppola's
``Gardens of Stone,'' Lionel Chetwynd's ``The Hanoi Hilton'' and
John Irvin's ``Hamburger Hill.''
   Still, Kubrick's electrifying excursion into military mania
managed to snare its share of the moviegoing audience. In fact,
film buffs had long awaited Kubrick's next work, seven years after
``The Shining,'' and were curious to see how he would treat the
madness of Vietnam after depicting modern insanities in ``Paths of
Glory,'' ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' and ``Dr. Strangelove, Or How I
Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb.''
   Based on Gustav Hasford's gripping novel, ``The Short Timers,''
Kubrick's work actually is two movies with the same characters: The
first part, and by far the best, takes place at Parris Island,
S.C., where recruits are stripped of their humanity to become
killing machines; the second part shifts to Vietnam, where the
marines fight the Tet offensive.
   We see the best of Kubrick's talents in ``Full Metal Jacket'' _
the title refers to the casings on the bullets _ in the slick
editing and direction of Gunnery Sgt. Hartman working the last
nerves of his boys. ``You will be ready to eat your own guts and
ask for seconds,'' he tells them.
   Lee Ermey, a former marine drill instructor himself, is
outstanding as Hartman and Vincent D'Onofrio as his major victim,
dubbed Pvt. Gomer Pyle by the sergeant, also puts in an excellent
performance.
   Kubrick seals each training scene with a tension that zooms us
to the next.
   But when the action shifts to Vietnam all that tension is lost,
and one of the worst battles of the war becomes a whimper. Part of
the problem is that the movie was shot in England rather than
Southeast Asia, which would have lent a much-needed authenticity.
   Still, Kubrick's effort is worthy of home viewing.
   _^By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Forever, Lulu'' (RCA@Columbia Home Video, VHS-Beta, $79.95,</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rated R)
   
   ``Forever, Lulu'' has everything: a rock star (Deborah Harry), a
foreign film star (Hanna Schygulla), Dr. Ruth Westheimer, an S&M
club, Paul Newman's Own salad dressing, Manhattan, organized crime
and mystery.
   Unfortunately, though, when all those elements come together
what's created is not much more than an awkward, sloppy
misadventure.
   Amos Kollek's ``Forever, Lulu'' recalls the far better
``Desperately Seeking Susan,'' with its rock star, hapless heroine
and a mystery that turns on her getting someone else's coat. But
even the acclaimed Schygulla seems uncomfortable in this role.
   Schygulla plays Elaine, an unrecognized writer who's been
mugged, fired, dropped by her agent and is desperate enough to
consider killing herself. At one point her agent tells her,
``You'll always be on your own.'' She replies, ``So's Clint
Eastwood.'' Much of the movie makes as much sense.
   Because of the coat, Elaine finds herself trailing an elusive
woman called Lulu (Harry), wanders into a gangsters' hideaway,
witnesses a shootout and walks out with their loot. Of course, she
becomes a hero and a star.
   Annie Golden is a bright spot as Elaine's oddball friend.
   _^By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
