<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0630EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   07-19 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0535</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Scenes From the Southside'' (RCA) _ Bruce Hornsby and the</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Range
   
   While ``Scenes From the Southside'' isn't the first music to
evoke the atmosphere of Appalachia, it may be the first to do it
with a piano rather than a mandolin, banjo or fiddle. But few
records have a stronger sense of a region than the second album
from Bruce Hornsby and the Range.
   Hornsby pleads for preservation of the environment on ``Look Out
Any Window,'' sings about a small-town scandal on ``The Valley
Road'' and jabs fundamentalist preachers common to the region on
``Jacob's Ladder'' and ``Defenders of the Flag.'' Hornsby and his
brother and writing partner, John Hornsby, show a novelist's eye
for detail in describing the area where they were raised.
   Hornsby's piano is more dominant than on the band's first album,
the hit ``The Way It Is.'' Hornsby, who gives himself plenty of
time for solos on the 48-minute record, has a jazzy sense of
phrasing that recalls Keith Jarrett, but he plays with a Jerry Lee
Lewis-like velocity. It's a unique blend, and one to be embraced by
listeners weary of synthesizers.
   The record could use more diversity in tempo and
instrumentation; for example, Hornsby makes little use of his skill
on the accordian. Such quibbles aside, ``Scenes From the
Southside'' is an album delivered with considerable honesty and
heart.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Diesel and Dust'' (Columbia) _ Midnight Oil</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   If Mike Dukakis would adopt ``Dream World'' from Midnight Oil's
new album as his campaign theme, he'd beat the Republicans in a
landslide. The song is a sure vote-getter that sounds celebratory
for Democrats, ominous for the GOP.
   ``Your dream world is just about to end,'' Midnight Oil lead
singer Peter Garrett snarls above chiming guitars that provide the
wake-up call. The song, written with the Reagan revolution in mind,
is killer rock 'n' roll _ hook-filled, dance-inducing and
thought-provoking all at once.
   Happily, the rest of ``Diesel and Dust'' is of the same caliber
as ``Dream World,'' and the album could allow Midnight Oil a break
into the American market. Until now, the veteran Australian
quintet's socially conscious music hasn't found much of an audience
in the United States.
   But Midnight Oil deserves to be heard. Its sound reflects
five-star bands from other eras, including the Clash and the Byrds.
While Garrett sounds like a world-weary Joe Strummer, bassist Peter
Gifford and guitarists Jim Moginie and Martin Rotsey play with both
finesse and fire to help create music that is catchy and yet
thundering. The band must be great live.
   And its message is strong. Besides the call to activism on
``Dream World,'' Garrett sings about the arms race on ``Put Down
That Weapon'' and addresses land rights on ``Beds Are Burning.''
   Social concerns have become a more prominent part of pop music
in recent years, so there should be room on the charts for Midnight
Oil.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
