<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, July 29-31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Brother-Sister Duo Is Newest Family Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sanders have swapped rowdy Alaskan
bars for more gentle settings to sing their songs of love.
   After fighting off grizzly bears and gold thieves in the land of
the midnight sun, the brother-sister duo came to Nashville with
their close-knit vocals and launched a country music recording
career.
   Vicki Sanders, 31, and Dale, 33, spent the past 10 years singing
in Alaska at night and often mining for gold by day with their
father, a retired geology teacher.
   ``It was very rewarding,'' Dale Sanders said. ``It was nice
being able to make people smile all the time.''
   Vicki Sanders gave a sample of their experiences:
   _ ``We played in Barrow in the far northern part. We were hired
with 13 Colombians who never went to sleep; they partied nonstop.
There were two buckets for the bathroom and a shower stall that
said `girls Monday-Wednesday-Friday' and `boys Tuesday-Thursday.' ''
   _ ``In Seward, a girl was beating a guy up. She picked up a
chair and threw it at him. He ran into the bathroom and hid. He
stepped out and she sucker- punched him.''
   _ ``A guy threatened to tie his wife to a tree, so she shot him
nine times with a .22 at their cabin. She got on a snow machine and
went for help.''
   The darkness and remoteness of Alaska seemed to affect the
residents, the Sanders said.
   ``In all those remote places where it's dark, people have a
tendency to get wild and kick up their heels,'' Vicki said. ``It
gets depressing.''
   ``You get a different breed of people,'' said Dale. ``Those who
don't like society go to those type places. It's kind of the end of
the road.''
   The two also had to contend with bears while mining along the
Alaska-Canada border.
   ``We were pretty heavily armed at the mine because they would
surprise you or you would surprise them,'' Dale said in an
interview. ``You'd be in a bind without a weapon. They destroyed
our camp a couple of times. One time they walked through a
camper-trailer by going in one end and tearing out the whole wall
and destroying the inside. They pushed a refrigerator through the
wall and made another hole to go out.''
   They mined from 1973 until the mid-1980s, always on the lookout
for thieves.
   ``One guy took a chain saw and stole the floor out of a cabin,''
Dale said.
   The two, both born and raised in Alaska, compared the mining
business to the entertainment field.
   ``Some years were good and some were not very good at all,''
Vicki said. ``I wouldn't recommend it for someone who needs
security. It's like the music industry. You can't count on
anything. You work your hardest and hope it works out at the end.''
   They recently signed a recording contract with Airborne Records,
a new independent label in Nashville. Steve Roberts, an Airborne
vice president, had heard them sing several years ago while he was
a concert promoter in Anchorage.
   ``One listen and I was sold on their music,'' Roberts recalled
about his first exposure to them. ``I decided then that if I ever
had a label, they would be on it.''
   Their first single record is ``You Fit Right Into My Heart.''
   Their sound is sure to draw comparisons to the Carpenters, a
brother-sister duo who had hits 15 years ago with ``For All We
Know,'' ``Superstar'' and ``Rainy Days & Mondays.''
   ``We listen to them,'' Vicki said. ``But our style of harmony
doesn't resemble theirs in any way, only that we are brother and
sister. We do have kind of a folk influence which they did also.''
   ``Our music is kind of on the sweet side but ours is not as
sweet as theirs. Ours is more country,'' Dale said. ``We've got a
new sound with a different approach. We don't sound like anyone
else. Our music is easy to listen to, positive, straight ahead.''
   The Sanders are the latest in a variety of family acts in
country music, joining Larry Gatlin and the Gatlin Brothers, the
Judds (mother and daughter), the Forester Sisters, the Whites
(father and daughters) and others.
   ``The blend you get when you put family together is going to be
closer than if you are not related,'' said Vicki, who has two other
brothers.
   ``And you make more concessions when working with family on the
road. You have disagreements but you forgive your brother or
sister. It's harder to forgive someone not related.''
   Said Dale, ``A lot of families grow up singing and just fall
into it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 29-31</NOTE>
