<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Icahn Bjt   07-19 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn: Still Mulling Options After Texaco Defeat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover strategist Carl Icahn says he still has
a myriad of options to pursue despite his defeat in a June proxy
fight attempt to win a block of seats on Texaco Inc.'s board of
directors.
   Texaco management on Monday confirmed earlier estimates that
shareholders rejected Icahn's attempt to place himself and four
associates on the board. Texaco said Icahn's dissident slate was
voted down by 58.6 percent to 41.6 percent, a much bigger margin
than earlier thought.
   Icahn, who owns a 14.8 percent chunk of Texaco stock, had
conceded defeat after the oil giant's annual shareholder meeting,
but had contended the vote was close.
   There had been speculation Icahn was awaiting the exact results
to determine how close he came to winning before deciding what to
do with his Texaco investment.
   Some Texaco-watchers speculated that a narrow vote might prompt
Icahn to challenge the outcome or make another attempt to get on
the Texaco board as part of a broader campaign to acquire the
company or force a restructuring that would raise the value of his
shares.
   ``We obviously regret that we lost, but hope that management
will do as they said and work to enhance stockholder value,'' Icahn
said in a statement issued by D.F. King & Co., the firm that
handled his proxy campaign.
   ``To answer the many queries concerning our position, there are
a myriad of options open to us at this time,'' he said. ``We have
not yet determined which one we will follow.''
   Texaco stock rose 37{ cents a share to $45.75 in New York Stock
Exchange trading.
   Texaco's management stated that Corporation Trust Co., which
tabulated the shareholder votes, reported 85 percent of the
company's 242.9 million shares outstanding were represented in
person or by proxy at the June 17 annual meeting in Tulsa, Okla.
   Excluding Icahn's stake, all Texaco-nominated directors received
71.4 percent of the shares voted, while directors nominated by the
Icahn group received 28.6 percent, Texaco said. That gave
management an overall victory margin of 58.6 percent to Icahn's
41.4 percent.
   There had been speculation that the fatal blow against Icahn's
effort was the vote for management by the investment firm of
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., which had a 4.9 percent stake. But
the results announced Monday showed management would have won
regardless of how Kohlberg Kravis had voted.
   ``This substantial victory margin is the result of widespread
support among all Texaco stockholders,'' James W. Kinnear,
president and chief executive officer, said in the company's
statement on the results.
   Icahn sought board membership as part of an effort to force
Texaco management to consider his $60-a-share cash buyout offer,
which valued the company at $14.6 billion. Kinnear called the offer
insincere.
   Icahn, who has chased several big companies over the past few
years and acquired Trans World Airlines, began building a stake in
Texaco last year while the company was mired in bankruptcy court, a
result of its protracted multibillion-dollar legal battle with
Pennzoil Co.
   Icahn's motive of a possible takeover became clearer after
Texaco emerged from bankruptcy court a few months ago. He denounced
management's handling of the Pennzoil matter and claimed Texaco's
post-bankruptcy reorganization plan would not maximize shareholder
values.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
