<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PacificBell     07-19 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pacific Bell,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pac Bell Proposes Giving up Monopoly on Local Calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pacific Bell, breaking from tradition, has
made a surprise proposal to give up its monopoly on local toll
calls in exchange for reduced state regulation.
   The giant local phone company called its proposal ``the most
significant change since the breakup of the Bell System in 1984.''
   Under the offer, the company would also expand the local
toll-free zone and offer push-button phones without extra charge in
exchange for the decreased regulation. If approved by the Public
Utilities Commission, the plan would give customers access to
high-technology, low-cost services.
   Consumer representatives greeted the proposal with trepidation.
   ``My biggest fear is that we will have the pretense of
competition but not the safeguards of competition,'' said Robert
Gnaizda, a lawyer who represents six minority and low-income groups
in the Pacific Bell rate case before the Public Utilities
Commission.
   Others would compete in handling local toll calls, but ``there
won't be any real competition'' and ``the company will escape
effective public and PUC scrutiny,'' Gnaizda said. Pacific Bell's
profit will exceed $1 billion this year, more than twice its
highest level before deregulation, he said.
   The Public Utilities Commission, which has suggested increasing
phone company flexibility in the new market created by the
dismemberment of the Bell system, will consider all the proposals
during the next year.
   According to Pacific Bell, the new proposal is more generous
than a plan the company presented in January in an attempt to
loosen state regulation.
   The Public Utilities Commission would continue to approve
residential rates after 1992, but without the exhaustive,
three-year inquiry of Pacific Bell's financial structure. Under the
plan, regulatory controls would also be loosened to allow new
services to be introduced more quickly.
   Monthly business rates would be allowed to rise gradually to
approach the cost of service. However, rates on premium residential
services such as call-forwarding, call-waiting and speed-dialing
would be cut.
   Pacific Bell said it also would expect reduced local toll rates
because of competition.
</TEXT>
