<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Perot-EDS     07-19 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Perot-EDS,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perot Launches Contract Battle With EDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire H. Ross Perot is waging a bidding war
for a lucrative Medicaid contract, taking on Electronic Data
Systems, the company he founded and steered to a huge share of the
automated health services market.
   EDS, a General Motors Corp. subsidiary since 1984, won the Texas
Medicaid contract in 1976.
   J. Livingston Kosberg, chairman of the board of the Texas Human
Services Department, said the department had not expected another
qualified bidder and had begun negotiating with EDS on the
financial terms of the pact, until Perot Systems Corp. entered the
picture.
   ``We certainly will be there and will bid,'' EDS spokesman Roger
Still said. ``We look at this as a competitor and will treat them
as a competitor.''
   Under the pact _ EDS assumes data-processing and administrative
responsibility for more than $800 million in the state's Medicaid
program _ EDS could net close to $7 million depending in part on
performance.
   Perot founded EDS in 1962 and sold the firm to GM in 1984. In
December 1986, after highly-publicized conflict between Perot and
GM, Perot and three other top EDS executives left the computer
services company when GM agreed to pay them $850 million.
   Under terms of the GM buyout agreement, Perot is barred from
operating a for-profit firm until after December 1989.
   Perot built national respect for EDS through health care
contracts.
   Wall Street analysts said Perot's extensive knowledge of EDS,
complemented by the two dozen former EDS employees on his staff,
give his firm some competitive strengths.
   ``Ross and his people ought to know exactly, contract by
contract, what EDS has,'' said Stephen McClellan, a technology
analyst with Merrill Lynch & Co. in New York. ``They'll know what
deals are expiring, what their (profit) margins are, and what it'll
take to beat them on a bid.''

</TEXT>
