<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0905EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Robins     07-19 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robins,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robins' Reorganization Plan Overwhelmingly Favored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.H. Robins Co.'s plan to emerge from
nearly three years of bankruptcy protection has won the approval of
creditors, stockholders and Dalkon Shield claimants, but one hurdle
remains.
   At a hearing Monday, U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige said
he and U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Blackwell N. Shelley, who are
overseeing the case, cannot approve the plan unless it contains a
provision giving them authority to oversee a trust for Dalkon
Shield claimants.
   The plan would establish a trust of nearly $2.5 billion to
satisfy claims by women who allege they were injured by using the
Dalkon Shield intrauterine birth control device marketed by Robins
in the early 1970s. The plan also would provide for a $3.2 billion
buyout of the 122-year-old Richmond-based company by the American
Home Products Corp.
   Merhige gave attorneys a week to submit briefs on the proposed
revision.
   Robins attorney Dennis Drebsky told the judges the plan was
supported by about 95 percent of the 141,094 Dalkon Shield
claimants who sent in ballots, and by more than 99 percent of the
19 million stockholders who voted.
   The four banks owed a total of $15.6 million by Robins
unanimously backed the plan, under which the New York-based
American Home would pay Robins' creditors in full.
   Attorney Murray Drabkin of the Dalkon Shield Claimants Committee
said the plan, which needed the approval of two-thirds of each
class of voters, ``provides a just and fair resolution of the
case.''
   However, attorney Ralph Pittle, who represents several hundred
Dalkon Shield claimants, said the trust fund was inadequate and
that more claimants would have voted against the plan if they had
been better informed.
   The plan was difficult for claimants to understand, especially
since many of them do not have lawyers, Pittle said.
   If the judges approve the plan, there will be a 30-day period
before a confirmation order is issued. Even if appeals are filed,
payments to claimants would begin 30 days after court approval
using a $100 million fund set up by Robins.
   Robins filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in August 1985
in the face of mounting claims and settlement payments associated
with the Dalkon Shield.
</TEXT>
