<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     07-19 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0335</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mostly mixed today
following a sharp drop in share prices earlier in the Far East.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 2.13 points at
2,120.02 in the first half hour of trading.
   Advancing issues slightly outnumbered decliners in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 473 up, 446
down and 543 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.32 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts noted that earlier in Tokyo the key Nikkei 225-share
index plummeted more than 500 points amid panicky selling. ``It was
the largest point fall recorded this year,'' noted Hildegarde
Zagorski, a second vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc.
   She attributed the decline in Japan to inflation fears sparked
by higher oil prices, which rose on Monday following reports that
Iran had acceded to a United Nations resolution calling for a
cease-fire in its war against Iraq.
   On closer analysis, however, Zagorski said the first order of
business after any cease-fire would be for the two countries to
rebuild their economies, and that means pumping more crude.
   ``Oil prices have backed down today,'' she said, ``and the stock
market is not behaving too badly.''
   Among actively traded issues, IBM was off [ at 125; Union
Carbide was down ] at 24~; Philip Morris was up ~ at 91}, and Ford
was up [ at 51|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.10 to 152.93. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.12 at 309.20.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 11.56 to
2,117.89.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 9 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 518 up, 961 down and 484 unchanged. Big Board volume
came to 156.21 million shares, against 199.71 million in the
previous session.
