<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Shoot Up On News Of Possible Persian Gulf Cease-fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-8 new to update with oil prices dropping back; picks
up 8th graf pvs, The price ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices retreated today after a big jump in
the previous session that was fueled by speculation that peace
could break out in the Persian Gulf.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, fell 30 cents a barrel to $15.40 a barrel in the
opening minutes of trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   That contract had jumped 84 cents a barrel on Monday _ the
biggest daily rise since April _ after Iran said it would accept a
United Nations resolution calling for an immediate cease-fire in
its nearly 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   Analysts said an end to the Iran-Iraq war might make it easier
for the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to reach
agreement on limiting production in order to boost prices.
   But analysts also expressed skepticism about the ability of OPEC
nations and non-OPEC members to end their chronic infighting and
overproduction, even if the Persian Gulf war halts.
   ``This is a very, very hype-sensitive market,'' said Madison
Galbraith, senior energy specialist for Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures.
   ``Very little has changed here aside from the psychology,'' said
Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc.
   Monday's jump in the August contract was the biggest rise since
West Texas Intermediate soared $1.01 a barrel on April 11.
   The price jump was even bigger for the September contract, which
rose 92 cents to $15.89 a barrel.
   Monday's jump brought prices back to their levels of earlier
this month, before a steep skid in prices took hold because of
concerns about a worldwide oversupply of oil. Oil still remains
more than $1 a barrel below its level of mid-June.
   Among refined products traded on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, August No.2 heating oil jumped 2.15 cents a gallon to
43.27 cents a gallon. The August contract for unleaded gasoline
rose 1.38 cents a gallon to 51.11 cents a gallon.
   The rebound in West Texas Intermediate brought it back from its
recent low of $14.44 a barrel last Wednesday and nearly back to its
level of $15.83 a barrel on July 7.
   Analysts said crude futures were boosted by traders who had been
betting on further declines in prices and rushed to cover their
positions by buying contracts.
   Aiding the rebound in prices was a report that OPEC's price
monitoring committee would meet within the next 30 days.
   Part of OPEC's overproduction has been ``war relief'' production
by Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates, which have
given the proceeds to Iraq to help in the battle with Iran, said
Frank P. Knuettel, an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   A cease-fire could eliminate that source of production, he said.
   In addition, Saudi Arabia might be more willing to support
prices instead of punishing Iran by allowing prices to fall, said
Rosario Ilacqua, an analyst for Nikko Securities International Co.
Inc.
   But analysts remained uncertain about the outlook for harmony in
the fractious cartel. Furthermore, there was skepticism over the
possibility that any cease-fire would last.
   As part of its announcement, Iran said it would not withdraw its
troops from its borders and called on Iranians to prepare to thwart
further Iraqi attacks. Iraq, which has already accepted the
year-old U.N. resolution, said it remained skeptical about Iran's
intentions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
