<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Earns-Monsanto     07-19 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Monsanto,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 43 Percent Profit Hike in 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monsanto Co. said Tuesday its second-quarter
profit climbed 43 percent from a year earlier, reflecting growth in
its agricultural, sweetener, chemical and electronic materials
businesses.
   The company said it earned a record $220 million, or $3.04 per
share, in the three months ended June 30 compared with $154
million, or $1.95 per share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter sales rose 11.3 percent to $2.26 billion from
$2.03 billion a year earlier.
   For the first six months of 1988, net income reached a record
$430 million, or $5.90 per share, up 47 percent from a profit of
$292 million, or $3.71 per share, a year earlier.
   Six-month sales rose 12.9 percent to $4.39 billion from $3.89
billion a year earlier.
   Chairman Richard J. Mahoney said the results indicate that ``we
are making significant progress toward achieving our long range
financial goal of 20 percent return on equity by the early 1990s.''
   Monsanto is specializes in pharmaceuticals, agricultural
products, specialty chemicals, low-calorie sweeteners, industrial
controls and electronic materials.
   The Monsanto Agricultural Co. fueled the growth of
second-quarter earnings with significant sales growth of Roundup
and Lasso herbicides and Alimet poultry feed supplement, Monsanto
said.
   The NutraSweet Co. also had a strong quarter, reflecting
continued growth for products containing the artificial sweetener,
Monsanto said. Results from the quarter also included accelerated
shipments to certain customers to meet production scheduling
requirements. That will likely be reflected in somewhat lower
volume shipments in the second half of the year, Monsanto said.
   Its G.D. Searle, Fisher Controls and Monsanto Electronic
Materials Co. also showed strong improvements, Monsanto said.
</TEXT>
