<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Surge; Grain, Soybean Futures Plummet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs with oil prices, picks up 5th graf pvs,
Soybeans for</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction partially recovered in June, rising 5.1
percent after plummeting 12.6 percent in May, the government said
today.
   The Commerce Department said the increase in housing starts was
the steepest in four months. Mortgage rates eased in June,
contributing to the revival.
   On Monday, reports of a possible cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war
sent oil prices soaring, while grain and soybean futures plunged
following heavy weekend rains in the drought-stricken Midwest.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, shot up 84
cents a barrel Monday to settle at $15.70 a barrel. It was the
biggest rise since a jump of $1.01 a barrel on April 11.
   But prices retreated in early trading today. The August contract
for WTI fell 30 cents to $15.40 a barrel.
   Soybeans for July delivery skidded more than $1.09 a bushel, one
of the steepest one-day soybean price declines in the history of
the Chicago Board of Trade. July corn plunged 30 cents a bushel.
   The spike in oil prices reignited inflation worries on Wall
Street and in the credit markets.
   The concerns were heightened by a Federal Reserve Board report
that U.S. industry in June operated at 83.1 percent of capacity _
its highest point in eight years and edging closer to a level that
economists believe signals a pickup in inflation.
   The nervousness about inflation weakened stock prices. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials, up 23.30 points last week, dropped
11.56 to 2,117.89.
   Bond prices also fell, forcing interest rates higher. The yield
on the Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond jumped to 9.23
percent from 9.14 percent late Friday.
   The possibility of a breakthrough in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq
conflict, along with aggressive dollar sales by central banks,
pushed the U.S. currency to a weaker finish against most key
foreign currencies. The dollar historically is regarded as a
safe-haven currency during times of unrest, and the prospect of
peace between the two Middle Eastern enemies spurred investors to
sell dollars.
   The news of a possible cease-fire between Iran and Iraq alao
raised prospects that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries would be able to calm its chronic infighting, which has
led to overproduction of oil and lower prices.
   The ensuing price jump in the futures market brought oil back to
its levels of earlier this month, before a steep skid in prices
sparked by concerns about a worldwide oversupply of oil.
   Analysts said prices were driven up by traders who had been
betting on further declines in prices and rushed to cover their
positions by buying contracts.
   Iran said Monday it would accept a United Nations resolution
calling for an immediate cease-fire in its war with Iraq. However,
Iran also said it will not withdraw its troops from its borders and
called on Iranians to prepare to thwart further Iraqi attacks.
   Supporting the price rebound was a report that OPEC's pricing
committee would meet within the next 30 days.
</TEXT>
