<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Sharply Lower On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as forecasts for more rain in
the drought-stricken Midwest provoked intense selling pressure for
the second straight day.
   Prices on most contracts for future delivery of corn, oats and
soybeans plunged their permissible limits at the opening bell,
halting trading in all but the limitless July contracts, which
expire at noon Thursday.
   The limit-down opening caused sell orders to pile up. Some 40
million bushels of soybeans and about 50 million bushels of corn
were awaiting buyers about 15 minutes after the opening.
   Weekend showers soaked farm fields in much of the northern Corn
Belt, and substantial rains were forecast for the region's southern
portion today through Wednesday, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Despite irreversible drought damage to much of the U.S. corn
crop, ``some of it will benefit, and the soybeans definitely will
benefit from all this recent rain,'' Lespinasse said.
   The National Weather Service's latest 6-to-10-day forecast,
calling for above-normal temperatures and mostly normal rainfall in
the Corn Belt during the early part of next week, was another
bearish factor, Lespinasse said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 12\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.67 a bushel; corn was 3{ cents
to the limit 15 cents lower with July at $3 a bushel; oats were the
limit 15 cents lower to 1 cent higher with July at $2.88 a bushel;
soybeans were 18 cents to the limit 45 cents lower with July at
$8.67 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .45 cent lower to .33 cent higher with August
at 64.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .15
cent higher with August at 76.40 cents a pound; hogs were .85 cent
lower to .63 cent higher with July at 46.80 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.90 cents lower to .75 cent higher with July at
37.30 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled widely mixed on Monday.
</TEXT>
