<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-PhilipMorris     07-19 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Philip Morris,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 31.6 Percent Profit Gain for 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Companies Inc. said Tuesday its
second-quarter profit climbed 31.6 percent from a year earlier, as
its cigarette, food and brewing businesses each posted revenue
gains.
   The company said its after-tax profit rose to $627 million, or
$2.68 a share, in the three months ended June 30, compared with
earnings of $476 million, or $2 a share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose 10 percent to $7.8 billion from $7.1 billion.
   For the first six months of the year, Philip Morris's earnings
rose 30.9 pecent to $1.13 billion, or $4.80 a share, from $862
million, or $3.62 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 10.2
percent to $15.1 billion from $13.7 billion.
   Hamish Maxwell, chairman and chief executive, said domestic
cigarette revenue and unit volume each rose and the company
expanded its market share in the quarter and first half. Among its
cigarette brands are Marlboro, Virginia Slims, Benson & Hedges and
Merit.
   He said the company's Miller Brewing subsidiary had higher
operating revenue on higher barrel volume for both the quarter and
the half.
   Unit volume and revenue also grew at the General Foods USA
division, while the General Foods Worldwide Coffee & International
business had higher revenue on slightly lower volume.
   The company said volume growth was especially strong at the
Oscar Mayer Foods division, as both Oscar Mayer brand meats and
Louis Rich turkey products expanded their market shares.
</TEXT>
