<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 0634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv19   07-19 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 19,0613</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday July 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>It's How You Look at It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is it a sign of great weakness that the United
States owed $368 billion to foreign creditors at the end of 1987,
more than was owed by any other nation? Or is it a sign of strength?
   The popular position is that the ``debt'' is further evidence of
a decline of the U.S. economy. The United States, it is said, is
the world's largest debtor nation, the insinuation being that debt
is bad.
   In this instance, however, the debt referred to can also be
viewed as strength. There is even a school of thought that declines
to call it debt, pointing out instead that much of the money is
invested.
   They ask you to consider this simple equivalent:
   When you put $20,000 into a $100,000 house for your family do
you explain to your friends that you have just gone deeply into
debt, or do you tell them you've just made the best investment of
your life?
   Most people would say the $20,000 was invested. And so would any
foreigner who put money into U.S. stocks, bonds and real estate.
Such folks invest for a good return. They don't see themselves as
lenders. They really aren't.
   The popular view of the United States being the largest debtor
nation comes from a comparison of U.S. investments abroad vs.
foreign investments in the United States. It is true: Foreigners
invest more here than we do there.
   Do they do so because they lack faith? Or because of the
attractiveness of American investments? Does it indicate an Uncle
Sam with his hand out? Or foreigners eager to get in on good
investments?
   In short, is it debt, or is it investment? Is it weakness _ or
strength?
   While those who call it debt are entitled to do so, others point
out that if foreigners buy stock in a company, put money in an
American bank, buy U.S. government securities or purchase a
production plant, they are investing.
   It makes sense. The U.S. market is the world's biggest by far.
The country is also the most politically stable, a factor that has
dictated investments as far back as international trade itself. And
U.S. investments are inexpensive.
   It is the latter factor, a direct result of the decline of the
U.S. dollar, that has been the latest spur to foreign investments
in the United States.
   Sanford Simon, a New York-based broker who has arranged at least
70 U.S. investments for British companies, offers some succinct
reasons for the phenomenon.
   Despite belonging to the European Economic Community, he says,
the British have an island economy. It is a mature economy in which
successful companies long ago carved out their niches. The result:
``They butt heads in a small market.''
   They look for ways to expand, especially if they have good cash
flow, and they see the biggest market of all in the United States _
growing, evolving, changing and, to boot, English-speaking.
   English laws discourage dividend distributions, a situation that
produces problems for good companies. They must expand, and what
better place to do so than in America where, because of the
devalued dollar, businesses are available at a discount?
   There is another side of the coin. If the United States economy
is so attractive to foreigners, why shouldn't it be equally so to
Americans? That is, why should they have to send their money abroad?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues July 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
