<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   07-19 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fell Tuesday in a quiet session on the
London Stock Exchange as the market digested Monday's half-point
rise in the British commercial banks' base lending rate.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index dropped 4.5
points, or 0.2 percent, to close at 1,844.8.
   Volume rose to a moderate 447.7 million shares, compared with
Monday's 366.4 million shares.
   Dealers said British equities ignored developments on Wall
Street until about the last hour of London dealings, when a key
market indicator in New York abruptly fell about 15 points.
   The Dow Jones industrial average was off 14.94 at 2,102.95 as
London trading ended.
   Players were still preoccupied by concerns that Monday's
half-point rise in the British commercial banks' base rates to 10.5
percent would be insufficient to curb inflation, dealers said.
   However, sterling rose on the foreign exchange markets,
diffusing the immediate need for an interest rate hike, dealers
said.
   Meanwhile, amid uncertainty about the near-term direction for
London equities, buyers were only interested in selected stocks,
dealers said.
</TEXT>
