<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0434</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices held at sharply lower levels today
as computerized sell programs kicked in and took their toll on
equities.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 29.87 points at
2,088.02 by mid-afternoon.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
453 up, 970 down and 461 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 105.59 million shares as of 2
p.m. on Wall Street.
   The Dow average moved up about 2 points in the first half hour
of trading but sank below the psychologically important 2,100 level
at midday and then continued to fall despite continued reports of
higher corporate earnings for the second quarter.
   Hildegarde Zagorski, a second vice president at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., noted that the decline began in the technology
sector, where several stocks tumbled. ``That started the ball
rolling, and then we got the sell programs.''
   Other analysts remarked on a sense of apathy among investors.
``The primary problem is the mood of the market,'' said Alfred
Goldman, a vice president at A.G. Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis.
``I'm very disappointed with today's action. There's a worldwide
malaise about owning equities.''
   Goldman noted that despite relatively favorable fundamentals
such as lower interest rates and higher corporate earnings, ``the
vast majority of investors are in a very apathetic mood ... they're
not coming to the equities trough.''
   Earlier in Tokyo, the key Nikkei 225-share index plummeted more
than 500 points to its lowest level this year.
   Zagorski attributed the decline in Japan to inflation fears
sparked by higher oil prices, which rose on Monday following
reports that Iran had acceded to a United Nations resolution
calling for a cease-fire in its war against Iraq.
   But reports that Iran downed three Iraqi jets today cast a veil
of confusion over prospects for a cease-fire.
   Among technology issues, IBM was off 1~ at 123\. The company
introduced new computers and personal computer software. Tandem
fell } to 18\; the company faces a new challenge from Digital
Equipment in the transaction processing business.
   Among other actively traded Big Board issues, Union Carbide was
down 1 at 24\; Interco was up 3[ at 57{; and Exxon was off ~ at 45].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.67 to 151.16. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.03 at 308.05.
</TEXT>
