<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-19 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Close Limit Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for some corn and soybean futures
contracts closed down their permissible limits Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for more rain in the
drought-stricken Midwest.
   But analysts said that after two consecutive days of limit
losses, the markets appeared to have discounted all the rain that
the Corn Belt is likely to receive this week.
   ``I think we'll have a two-sided trade tomorrow,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
``We'll probably open lower but not necessarily.''
   Oat futures also closed lower but wheat futures advanced on
expectations of new export business, analysts said.
   The wet-weather pattern that drenched parts of the upper Midwest
over the weekend continued on Tuesday, bringing rain to the
region's parched southern and western portions. More rain was
expected in the northern Corn Belt on Wednesday.
   The rain halted further deterioration of the badly damaged corn
crop and greatly improved the prospects for good soybean yields,
analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 8\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.75} a bushel; corn was the
limit 15 cents lower to 4 cents higher with July at $3.08 a bushel;
oats were 13 cents lower to 3 cents higher with July at $2.90 a
bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents to the limit 45 cents lower with
July at $8.73 a bushel.
</TEXT>
