<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Phone     07-19 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Phone,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2nd-Qtr Profit Up at Ameritech, Down at Southwestern Bell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the regional Bell telephone holding companies reported
divergent second-quarter results Tuesday as Ameritech announced a
27 percent profit gain while Southwestern Bell Corp. said its
earnings fell 14 percent.
   Ameritech, based in Chicago and parent of five Bell phone
companies in the Midwest, said the sale of its Canadian cellular
telephone holdings and strong growth in its U.S. mobile phone
business helped boost its results.
   Ameritech reported net income of $351.5 million, or $2.58 per
share, for the three months ending June 30, compared with $275.8
million, or $1.96 per share, for the same period a year ago.
   Revenue for the quarter increased 4.6 percent to $2.48 billion
from $2.37 billion, Ameritech said in a statement.
   Net income for the first six months of 1988 totaled $646.6
million, or $4.73 per share, compared with $564.8 million, or $3.99
per share, for the same period a year ago.
   First-half revenues totaled $4.89 billion compared with $4.67
billion.
   Ameritech is the holding company for Bell companies serving
Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin.
   Southwestern Bell, based in St. Louis and parent of Southwestern
Bell Telephone Co. and some smaller subsidiaries, said it earned
$212.9 million, or 71 cents a share, down from $248.8 million, or
83 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 7.8 percent to $2.03
billion from $1.89 billion.
   For the first six months of the fiscal year, Southwestern Bell
fell 11.3 percent to $431.6 million, or $1.44 per share, from
$486.5 million, or $1.62 per share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to
$4.03 billion from $3.76 billion.
   The weaker earnings were in line with expectations and were
related to the expense of shutting down Silver Pages operations,
the cost of acquiring new cellular and paging properties, and
increases in telephone company expenses, the company said.
   ``We remain confident of our ability to produce earnings growth
for the year,'' Zack Barnes, the chairman and chief executive, said
in a written statement. He noted among other things that the
company's 10 largest Yellow Pages directories will be published in
the second half of 1988.
</TEXT>
