<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Northrop     07-19 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Northrop,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aerospace Firm Posts Profit of $21.9 Million in 2nd Qtr.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. posted a profit Tuesday of
$21.9 million in the second quarter, compared to a $15.4 million
loss a year earlier, when the company took a large write-off on a
secret project believed to be the Stealth bomber.
   The aerospace company reported that its sales for the quarter
fell 5.2 percent to $1.35 billion from $1.42 billion in the second
quarter of 1987.
   In the first six months of the year, Northrop's profit climbed
to $161.5 million, or $3.44 a share, compared with $25.2 million,
or 54 cents a share, a year earlier. Six-month revenue fell 4
percent to $2.71 billion from $2.83 billion a year earlier.
   The company attributed the improved second-quarter results to
absence of a $124.3 million write-off it took in the second quarter
of 1987 on a project it hasn't officially identified, but which is
widely believed to be the B-2, or Stealth bomber. Earlier this
year, Northrop and the Air Force acknowledged for the first time
the company is developing the bomber, which is designed to be
difficult to detect on enemy radar.
   Second-quarter operating profit was cut by lower revenues on the
unnamed classified program, as well as by reduced sales and lower
profit margins on guidance units for the Air Force's MX missile and
other military projects. Revenue also was reduced because of a
Pentagon policy that requires contractors to pay a larger share of
research and development costs that they previously did, the
company said.
   Production of inertial measurement units for the MX has lagged
behind schedule, but the company says it now is producing the units
on a schedule acceptable to the Air Force. The government is
withholding less than $50 million in progress payments on the MX
systems, down from a high of $145 million in December 1987,
Northrop said.
   Northrop is one of three Southern California aerospace companies
whose offices were searched last month in the nationwide
investigation of allegations that defense industry consultants
bribed Pentagon officials for information to help win contracts.
The company has said it is cooperating in the probe, which so far
has centered on independent industry consultants and former Defense
Department officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
