<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     07-19 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0142</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices sank today amid computer-driven
sell programs and investor nervousness following a sharply lower
markets overseas.
   Analysts said the market's momentum continues to abate, and a
500-plus point plunge in Tokyo's key Nikkei 225-share index only
served to heighten investor uneasiness as the session began.
   ``Some investors are hesitant to hold on amid even the slightest
weakness rather than ride out the correction,'' noted Eugene
Peroni, a technical analyst at Janney Montgomery Scott in
Philadelphia.
   Slightly higher bond prices and positive corporate earnings for
the second quarter provided only minimal support for equities.
   Traders pointed to the technology sector as being particularly
weak. ``The fact that we had very vague leadership was partly a
cause for the market's poor behavior,'' Peroni said.
</TEXT>
