<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 1831EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Banks     07-19 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Banks,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citicorp, Wells Fargo, Mellon, Irving Post 2nd-Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of the nation's largest banking companies on Tuesday
reported profits in the second quarter in contrast with steep
losses a year earlier.
   Citicorp, Wells Fargo & Co., Mellon Bank Corp. and Irving Bank
Corp. noted that the second-quarter losses in 1987 stemmed from
additions to loan reserves for potentially uncollectible loans to
developing countries.
   Great Western Financial Corp., one of the biggest U.S. thrifts,
said its second-quarter earnings jumped 22 percent _ to $64.7
million, or 50 cents a share, from $53 million, or 40 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   New York-based Citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding
company, said it earned $359 million, or $1.03 a share, compared
with a loss of $2.6 billion in the second quarter of last year.
   If the loan-loss provisions hadn't been made, Citicorp said, it
would have earned $285 million, or 93 cents a share, in the second
quarter of 1987.
   Citicorp attributed the improvement in the latest quarter to
continued strength in its core banking businesses in the United
States and abroad. Much of the momentum in banking came from
Citicorp's credit card business, the company said.
   The banking giant also credited positive results from securities
and currency trading during the quarter, as well as gains from
venture capital loans.
   In the first half of the year, Citicorp posted net profit of
$717 million, or $2.04 a share, compared with a net loss of $2.3
billion in the first six months of 1987.
   San Francisco-based Wells Fargo, the 11th-largest U.S. bank
company, reported second-quarter earnings of $124.4 million, or
$2.24 a share, compared with a net loss of $293.7 million a year
earlier.
   Excluding the provision for risky loans, Wells Fargo would have
earned $83.6 million, or $1.45 a share, in the second quarter of
last year.
   The company said an increase in net interest income, resulting
from favorable market conditions in California, was a major factor
in the second-quarter improvement. Wells Fargo, which acquired
Barclays Bank of California in May, is the third-largest banking
company in the state.
   In the first half of the year, the bank posted net profit of
$244.8 million, or $4.39 a share, compared with a net loss of
$215.4 million a year earlier.
   Mellon, based in Pittsburgh and the 16th-biggest bank company,
posted net income for the latest quarter of $28 million, or 75
cents a share, as opposed to a net loss of $566 million a year
earlier.
   For the first six months of the year, Mellon earned $53 million,
or $1.40 a share, compared with a net loss of $626 million in the
1987 half.
   New York-based Irving, the 24th-largest bank company and the
long-time target of a hostile takeover bid from Bank of New York
Co., said it earned a record $169.9 million, or $8.85 a share,
compared with a net loss of $142 million in the second quarter of
1987.
   In the first half, Irving had net income of $222.3 million, or
$11.56 a share, compared with a net loss of $113.4 million a year
earlier.
   Great Western Financial, based in Beverly Hills, Calif., said
the 22 percent rise in its second-quarter earnings reflected solid
performances by each of its core businesses, including continued
growth in lending.
   By contrast, earnings in the first half fell 14.8 percent _ to
$121 million, or 95 cents a share, from $142 million, or $1.11 a
share, a year earlier. The company said its results benefitted from
exceptionally strong gains from sales of home mortgage loans in the
first six months of 1987.
</TEXT>
