<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-McGraw-Hill     07-19 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-McGraw-Hill,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit Up 12 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McGraw-Hill Inc. reported Tuesday that its
profit rose 12 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier,
boosted by increased revenue from all its operating companies.
   The diversified publisher said its net income increased to $44.8
million, or 92 cents a share, in the latest three months from $40
million, or 79 cents a share, in the second quarter of last year.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 4.2 percent, to $443.7 million from
$425.9 million a year earlier.
   Results for the latest quarter include the sale of the company's
49 percent interest in Nikkei-McGraw-Hill, a joint venture
publishing company in Japan, for $283.1 million. The gain on the
sale was $109.8 million after taxes. McGraw-Hill said it also took
previously announced asset writedowns and other unusual charges in
the second quarter totaling $107.6 million after taxes.
   ``All of our operating companies produced revenue increases in
the second quarter,'' said Chairman Joseph L. Dionne.
   As of July 1, McGraw-Hill was restructured into three operating
companies: publishing, financial services and information services.
   For the first half of the year, earnings rose 14.9 percent _ to
$71.8 million, or $1.48 a share, from $62.5 million, or $1.23 a
share, a year earlier.
   First-half revenue was up 5.3 percent, to $839.3 million from
$797.4 million.
</TEXT>
