<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-19 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0615</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market skidded lower Tuesday as
investor nervousness over the direction of interest rates overrode
a flurry of favorable corporate earnings reports.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell more than 11
points on Monday, dropped another 20.63 to close at 2,097.26.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 9 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
517 issues up, 918 down and 492 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE was 144.11 million shares, down
from 156.21 million in Monday's session. Nationwide, consolidated
volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional
exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 168.11
million shares.
   Stock prices were mixed at the opening of trading but soon
headed lower. By midday the Dow sank below the psychologically
important 2,100 mark and continued to hold at depressed levels
despite repeated reports of higher corporate earnings for the
second quarter.
   Hugh Johnson, a senior vice president at First Albany Corp.,
noted that higher interest rates overseas coupled with fear that
the Federal Reserve may also hike rates in this country ``is the
principal reason making the market nervous.''
   He said the market largely discounted repeated double-digit
corporate earnings increases for fear ``they will be neutralized by
higher interest rates ... down the road.''
   The technology sector, which typically has been a leader in
propelling the market to higher levels, was particularly weak. ``It
can be a little depressing (elsewhere in the market) when you see
that group give ground,'' Johnson said.
   With the technology sector down, computer-driven sell programs
kicked in and further depressed stock prices.
   Noting that the market is continuing to lose momentum, some
analysts remarked on a sense of apathy among investors and a mood
that is negative toward equities.
   Eugene Peroni, a technical analyst at Janney Montgomery Scott in
Philadelphia, said investors ``are hesitant to hold on amid even
the slightest weakness, rather than ride a correction through.'' He
attributed the ``near-sighted behavior'' to residual trauma from
last October's stock crash.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the key Nikkei 225-share index plummeted more
than 500 points to its lowest level this year. But because the drop
largely was a reaction to Monday's sharply higher oil prices,
traders said it did not take a toll on domestic trading.
   Among technology issues, Seagate Technology plunged 5{ to 13
following a sharply lower earnings report. It was the most active
issue in over-the-counter trading, and one trader said Seagate's
decline affected other companies in the industry because it
provides parts to other computer makers.
   Elsewhere in the technology sector, IBM, which introduced new
computers and personal software Tuesday, fell 1] at 124; NCR fell
3] to 58\; Prime Computer was off \ at 15 and National
Semiconductor was off \ at 11\.
   Among other actively traded Big Board issues, Union Carbide was
down } at 24{; Interco was up 4 at 58]; Exxon was off | at 45|, and
Polaroid was unchanged at 34.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $17.18 billion, or 0.64
percent, in value.
   The NYSE index was off 1.03 at 151.80.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 2.52 to 310.18,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was off 2.04 at 268.47.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 0.69
to 308.39. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 391.28, off 3.49.
</TEXT>
