<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-19 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0827</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Plunge Again As Rain Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rainy weather brought another sharp drop in corn and soybean
futures prices Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade and some
analysts wondered if the Midwestern drought had finally been
quenched.
   On other markets, silver futures soared to a 10-month high;
energy futures fell; livestock and meat were mostly lower; and
stock-index futures retreated.
   The wet-weather pattern that drenched parts of the upper Midwest
over the weekend brought rain on Tuesday to the region's parched
southern and western portions. More rain was expected in the
northern Corn Belt on Wednesday.
   Analysts said the rain halted further deterioration of the badly
damaged corn crop and greatly improved the yield prospects for
soybeans, which are just entering the critical pod-forming stage.
   Some corn and soybean contracts plummeted their permissible
limits in reaction to the rain, and analysts said that after two
consecutive days of limit losses, the markets appeared to have
discounted all the rain in sight for the Corn Belt.
   ``I think we'll have a two-sided trade tomorrow,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
``We'll probably open lower but not necessarily.''
   Lespinasse said the weather would continue set the market's
course and Cathy Leow, an assistant vice president with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York, agreed.
   ``Last week a lot of people bought soybeans at $9 thinking they
were going to go to $13,'' she said. ``Now they're thinking, `My
god, what if we continue to get rain?'.
   ``It could be that the drought's broken,'' Ms. Leow said.
``Sure, we need 10 to 15 inches of rain in most areas to bring the
soil moisture back to normal ... but at least we're not seeing
further deterioration in the crops.''
   Although it was uncertain how much rain the western Corn Belt
would receive overnight, Ms. Leow said the price drop of the last
two days probably had taken a substantial rainfall into account.
   Oat futures also finished lower but wheat futures advanced on
expectations of new export business, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 6 cents to 8{ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.76 a bushel; corn was the limit 15 cents
lower to 5 cents higher with July at $3.08{ a bushel; oats were 14
cents lower to 3 cents higher with July at $2.90 a bushel; soybeans
were 6 cents to the limit 45 cents lower with July at $8.74{ a
bushel.
   The price for July delivery of silver soared more than 57 cents
on New York's Commodity Exchange to $7.727, the highest price for
near-month delivery since Sept. 10, when the September contract
closed at $8.
   Analysts cited a number of factors for the rise, including the
two-day old Peruvian silver miners' strike and growing investment
demand for silver as a hedge against inflation.
   World supplies of silver are plentiful and the strike in Peru,
which accounts for about 20 percent of world production, normally
would have little long-term effect on prices, said Fred Demler,
metals analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   ``If investment demand were not picking up, the fact that the
supply is being disrupted from Peru would not have a large impact''
on the supply-demand scenario, he said.
   A bullish technical picture also spurred buying of silver, which
helped boost prices of other precious metals, other analysts said.
   Gold settled $8.70 to $9.80 higher with August at $447.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 57.7 cents to 62.5 cents higher with July at
$7.727 a troy ounce.
   Oil futures prices retreated on the New York Mercantile Exchange
as traders grew skeptical that a possible cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq war would soon reduce the world oversupply of oil,
analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 47 cents
lower with August at $15.23 a barrel; heating oil was .37 cent to
.65 cent lower with August at 42.90 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .46 cent lower to .15 cent higher with August at 50.65
cents a gallon.
   Lower cash values pressured cattle futures prices on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange while pork futures fell on expectations of
weakening cash prices, analysts said.
   Live cattle were 1.18 cents lower to .23 cent higher with August
at 63.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .68 cent
lower with August at 76.10 cents a pound; hogs were .80 cent lower
to .48 cent higher with July at 46.65 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .70 cent to 1.20 cents lower with July at 35.85 cents
a pound.
   The contract for September delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
stock index settled 1.85 points lower at 270.45 on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</TEXT>
