<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BrazilLoan     07-19 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil Loan,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. To Participate in Short-Term Loan to Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department said Tuesday it had
agreed to participate in a $500 million, short-term bridge loan to
Brazil.
   The Bank for International Settlements, an organization in
Switzerland of the world's central banks, also is participating,
the department said in a statement.
   A Treasury Department official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said U.S. participation would amount to about half of
the loan, which must be repaid by Dec. 30. It is intended to tide
Brazil over until an International Monetary Fund loan is disbursed
later this year.
   Mailson Ferreira da Nobrega, Brazil's finance minister, recently
told bankers in London that this month his country will pay foreign
commercial banks the interest it owes them for June and July,
bringing it up to date for interest due from the beginning of the
year.
   Brazil and a committee of its major creditor banks reached an
agreement last month to end a moratorium on interest payments begun
by Brazil in February 1987. The agreement calls for the
rescheduling of Brazil's $62 billion debt to foreign banks and the
issuing of $5.2 billion in new loans.
   The nation's total foreign debt of $120 billion is the biggest
in the developing world.
   Brazil also is taking steps to restrain inflation and curtail
its government deficit.
   ``United States participation in this multilateral effort
indicates our strong support for Brazil's economic reform
efforts,'' the Treasury Department statement said.
</TEXT>
