<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 2008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Honeywell     07-19 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Honeywell,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honeywell Posts 41.8 Percent Profit Drop In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. on Tuesday posted a 41.8
percent drop in its second quarter profit from a year earlier, due
mainly to $43 million in one-time charges and to accounting changes.
   Honeywell said its net income fell to $31.6 million, or 75 cents
a share, from $54.3 million, or $1.21 a share, in second quarter
1987.
   Sales in the three months ended July 3 rose to $1.75 billion
from $1.57 billion a year earlier.
   James J. Renier, president and chief executive officer of the
defense contractor and maker of building controls, said quarterly
results reflected a $27 million after-tax charge related to cost
overruns on fixed-price contracts in the military avionics group
and a $16 million charge to cover losses in a semiconductor product
line.
   The military avionics group also suffered a reduced asset value
under more stringent accounting rules, said Susan Eich, a company
spokeswoman.
   ``With the exception of the previously announced charges in our
military avionics group, performance in our other major businesses
remains strong, with increases in both sales and operating
profit,'' Renier said.
   Renier said operating profit was up in the following divisions:
industrial automation and control, defense and marine systems, home
and building automation and control, and international business.
   Six-month net income was $89.3 million, or $2.11 a share, down
from $98.0 million, or $2.17 a year ago. Total sales for the first
half of 1988 were $3.48 billion, compared with $3.05 billion in
1987.
</TEXT>
