<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing Order,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Gets Orders and Options for 15 Airplanes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America West Airlines has placed orders and
options for 15 Boeing 737-300 twinjets, Boeing Commercial Airplanes
announced Tuesday.
   The total includes an unannounced prior order for five jets,
plus a new order for five and options for five more. The 10 firm
orders are valued at more than $280 million, Boeing said.
   Two of the jets were delivered last week, another is scheduled
to be delivered in September and two more in October. Other
deliveries will occur in December 1989 through April 1990, Boeing
said.
   America West is based in Phoenix, and has an all-Boeing fleet of
54 737s, seven 757s, and three de Havilland DHC-8-100s. de
Havilland is Boeing's Canadian subsidiary.
   The 737-300 seats 143 passengers in America West's configuration.
   Including the new order, 38 customers worldwide have ordered 770
of the -300 model. Total 737 orders for all models stand at 2,153.
</TEXT>
