<HEAD>First RepublicBank Announces Loss</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, Because of ... to CORRECT with six-month
earnings figure for 1987. Picks up 8th graf pvs, The holding ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Corp., undergoing a
federally-assisted bailout, reported Tuesday that it lost $758
million in the second quarter, citing deteriorating values on real
estate assets and foreclosed properties.
   ``As forecast at the annual meeting of shareholders last month,
the second-quarter losses were substantial,'' said Albert V. Casey,
chairman and chief executive officer.
   The company had lost $313.2 million in the second quarter a year
ago.
   During the first quarter of 1988, First RepublicBank recorded a
$1.5 billion loss, and its loss for the six months ending June 30
was $2.26 billion.
   First RepublicBank's first quarter loss, the largest ever for a
U.S. bank after Citcorp's $2.5 billion loss in 1987, forced the
company to launch an emergency federal recapitalization plan.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. in May infused $1 billion
into the holding company, formed through the merger of InterFirst
Corp. and RepublicBank Corp. in May 1987.
   For purposes of comparison, the company said it had a loss of
$302.8 million for the first six months of 1987.
   lost The holding company attributes its latest loss to
deteriorating values on real estate held as loan collateral and
repossessed properties which it is unable to resell.
   ``The market is very, very soft,'' said Joe Bowles, First
RepublicBank spokesman.
   It said its nonperforming assets totaled $5.135 billion, up $671
million from the quarter ending March 31.
   Casey said in a statement that declining values of its real
estate slowed slightly in the second quarter. ``I clearly cannot
report, however, that we have reached bottom at this point,'' he
said.
   The company's recapitalization plan is under examination by the
FDIC and Bowles said the second quarter earnings report would not
affect the agency's acceptance of it. ``We've kept the FDIC and
other regulatory parties fully apprised,'' Bowles said.
   The plan was submitted last month with several other proposals
and the FDIC was expected to choose a plan for the company this
month.
   ``We had hoped for a favorable decision on our plan by now, but
the FDIC has required additional time to study all available
options,'' said Casey. ``We remain confident that the First
Republic plan is the most viable of those options and will
ultimately be accepted.'' Company officials now expect a plan to be
chosen within a weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
