<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-88 2241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-China-Quality     07-19 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Quality,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Creates New Bureau to Oversee Quality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has set up a new state bureau to oversee
efforts to reduce the number of shoddy, substandard goods on the
market and help Chinese products meet international quality
standards, an official daily said Wednesday.
   State Councillor Song Jian said Tuesday the State Bureau of
Technical Supervision would strengthen supervision over technology
and establish an authoritative system of standardization and
measurement, the China Daily said.
   The bureau will manage and adjust national standards on
production, development, distribution and consumption. Song said
the country must actively adopt international standards and a
system of international quality authentication to make Chinese
goods more competitive on world markets.
   He said that since China initiated its economic reforms and
open-door trade policy in 1979, the country has put into effect
more than 11,000 state standards and 500 measurement regulations.
   But he said substandard products remain a serious problem for
China.
   The daily said a spot check of industrial products earlier this
year found that only 20 percent fully satisfied national standards.
Among tractor gears checked, for example, only 13.3 percent met
quality specifications.
</TEXT>
